{"mode":"editor","version":1,"windowDimensions":{"x":0,"y":23,"width":1024,"height":752,"maximized":false},"grammars":{"deserializer":"GrammarRegistry","grammarOverridesByPath":{}},"project":{"paths":["/Users/joegesualdo/code/node/vocabulary-context/videos-srt"],"buffers":[{"text":"1\n00:00:01,000 --> 00:00:02,533\nThe President:\nHello, everybody!\n\n2\n00:00:02,533 --> 00:00:03,867\nAudience:\nHello!\n\n3\n00:00:03,867 --> 00:00:08,033\nThe President:\nWelcome to the White House.\n\n4\n00:00:08,033 --> 00:00:12,000\nFirst of all, I take full\nresponsibility for the weather.\n\n5\n00:00:12,000 --> 00:00:13,767\n(laughter)\n\n6\n00:00:13,767 --> 00:00:17,333\nWhat a spectacular day for\na congressional picnic.\n\n7\n00:00:17,333 --> 00:00:22,834\nThis is always one of the best\nevents of the year for us,\n\n8\n00:00:22,834 --> 00:00:26,767\nmainly because with all the\nwork that we do with members\n\n9\n00:00:26,767 --> 00:00:32,000\nof Congress and their staffs,\nall too often we don't get a\n\n10\n00:00:32,000 --> 00:00:34,567\nchance to say thank\nyou to the families.\n\n11\n00:00:34,567 --> 00:00:41,734\nAnd we understand that public\nservice is tough on the families;\n\n12\n00:00:41,734 --> 00:00:43,433\nin some ways, tougher.\n\n13\n00:00:43,433 --> 00:00:46,000\nYou've got spouses who\nare away from home,\n\n14\n00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:48,767\nmoms or dads or grandpas\nor grandmas who don't get\n\n15\n00:00:48,767 --> 00:00:50,867\na chance to see you as\noften as they'd like.\n\n16\n00:00:50,867 --> 00:00:56,066\nAnd so this is just one modest\nway for us to say to all of you,\n\n17\n00:00:56,066 --> 00:00:58,633\nthank you for the enormous\ncontributions you make to\n\n18\n00:00:58,633 --> 00:00:59,834\nthe country.\n\n19\n00:00:59,834 --> 00:01:03,700\nWe are thrilled with everything\nthat you guys do each and every\n\n20\n00:01:03,700 --> 00:01:06,700\nday to make this country\nstronger and more secure\n\n21\n00:01:06,700 --> 00:01:09,367\nand more free.\n\n22\n00:01:09,367 --> 00:01:12,834\nIt is good to see a lot\nof familiar faces here.\n\n23\n00:01:12,834 --> 00:01:15,500\nI hope everybody is\ngetting enough to eat.\n\n24\n00:01:15,500 --> 00:01:18,133\nWe don't want to\nmake a long speech,\n\n25\n00:01:18,133 --> 00:01:26,700\nbut I do hope that the spirit of\ncommunity that is so evident on\n\n26\n00:01:26,700 --> 00:01:30,233\na day like today, that this\ncarries over each and every day.\n\n27\n00:01:30,233 --> 00:01:32,300\nWe've got Democrats here\nand the Republicans here,\n\n28\n00:01:32,300 --> 00:01:36,000\nand we all have differences on\nissues at every given moment,\n\n29\n00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:38,767\nbut the one thing that we have\nto remind ourselves every day\n\n30\n00:01:38,767 --> 00:01:41,367\nis we're all Americans and we're\nall part of the American family.\n\n31\n00:01:41,367 --> 00:01:44,533\n(applause)\n\n32\n00:01:44,533 --> 00:01:49,633\nSo, finally, the last point I'd\nmake is we've got some service\n\n33\n00:01:49,633 --> 00:01:57,500\nmembers here who helped to not\nonly play the banjo and make\n\n34\n00:01:57,500 --> 00:02:01,834\nsome wonderful music, but folks\nwho serve each and every day.\n\n35\n00:02:01,834 --> 00:02:05,000\nFor all of those who serve\nour country in uniform,\n\n36\n00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:07,166\nthank you so much\nand God bless you.\n\n37\n00:02:07,166 --> 00:02:08,266\nWe're all grateful to you.\n\n38\n00:02:08,266 --> 00:02:09,100\n(applause)\n\n39\n00:02:09,100 --> 00:02:14,266\nAll right? So you guys have fun.\n\n40\n00:02:14,266 --> 00:02:19,233\nAnd I want you guys to eat\nuntil you can't eat any more.\n\n41\n00:02:19,233 --> 00:02:20,133\n(laughter)\n\n42\n00:02:20,133 --> 00:02:22,367\nAll right? And then tomorrow\nyou can \"Let's Move.\"\n\n43\n00:02:22,367 --> 00:02:22,700\n(laughter)\n\n44\n00:02:22,700 --> 00:02:25,800\nAll right. Thank you very much,\neverybody. Appreciate it.\n\n45\n00:02:25,800 --> 00:02:27,800\n(applause)\n\n","markerStore":{"nextMarkerId":1,"markersById":{"0":{"range":{"start":{"row":17,"column":0},"end":{"row":17,"column":12}},"properties":{"type":"selection","editorId":8,"goalScreenRange":null,"preserveFolds":true},"reversed":true,"tailed":true,"valid":true,"invalidate":"never","maintainHistory":true}},"version":2},"history":{"version":3,"nextCheckpointId":4,"undoStack":[],"redoStack":[]},"encoding":"utf8","filePath":"/Users/joegesualdo/code/node/vocabulary-context/videos-srt/WhiteHouseCongressionalPicnic-XxcxZhat21w.en.srt","digestWhenLastPersisted":"411c194543f1483cad118cd5a895fe8ce2be2a49","preferredLineEnding":null,"deserializer":"TextBuffer","version":2},{"text":"1\n00:00:01,410 --> 00:00:07,980\nCHAPTER ONE\nThe Man Who Died\n\n2\n00:00:09,700 --> 00:00:14,589\nI returned from the City about three\no'clock on that May afternoon pretty well\n\n3\n00:00:14,589 --> 00:00:19,269\ndisgusted with life.\nI had been three months in the Old Country,\n\n4\n00:00:19,269 --> 00:00:21,680\nand was fed up with it.\n\n5\n00:00:21,680 --> 00:00:26,199\nIf anyone had told me a year ago that I\nwould have been feeling like that I should\n\n6\n00:00:26,199 --> 00:00:29,880\nhave laughed at him; but there was the\nfact.\n\n7\n00:00:29,880 --> 00:00:36,550\nThe weather made me liverish, the talk of\nthe ordinary Englishman made me sick, I\n\n8\n00:00:36,550 --> 00:00:41,350\ncouldn't get enough exercise, and the\namusements of London seemed as flat as\n\n9\n00:00:41,350 --> 00:00:45,460\nsoda-water that has been standing in the\nsun.\n\n10\n00:00:45,460 --> 00:00:51,140\n'Richard Hannay,' I kept telling myself,\n'you have got into the wrong ditch, my\n\n11\n00:00:51,140 --> 00:00:54,670\nfriend, and you had better climb out.'\n\n12\n00:00:54,670 --> 00:00:59,519\nIt made me bite my lips to think of the\nplans I had been building up those last\n\n13\n00:00:59,519 --> 00:01:02,140\nyears in Bulawayo.\n\n14\n00:01:01,890 --> 00:01:07,440\nI had got my pile--not one of the big ones,\nbut good enough for me; and I had figured\n\n15\n00:01:07,440 --> 00:01:12,730\nout all kinds of ways of enjoying myself.\n\n16\n00:01:12,480 --> 00:01:17,120\nMy father had brought me out from Scotland\nat the age of six, and I had never been\n\n17\n00:01:17,120 --> 00:01:22,950\nhome since; so England was a sort of\nArabian Nights to me, and I counted on\n\n18\n00:01:22,950 --> 00:01:26,130\nstopping there for the rest of my days.\n\n19\n00:01:26,130 --> 00:01:29,710\nBut from the first I was disappointed with\nit.\n\n20\n00:01:29,710 --> 00:01:35,130\nIn about a week I was tired of seeing\nsights, and in less than a month I had had\n\n21\n00:01:35,130 --> 00:01:38,020\nenough of restaurants and theatres and\nrace-meetings.\n\n22\n00:01:39,520 --> 00:01:44,630\nI had no real pal to go about with, which\nprobably explains things.\n\n23\n00:01:44,630 --> 00:01:48,250\nPlenty of people invited me to their\nhouses, but they didn't seem much\n\n24\n00:01:48,250 --> 00:01:50,850\ninterested in me.\n\n25\n00:01:50,850 --> 00:01:55,540\nThey would fling me a question or two about\nSouth Africa, and then get on their own\n\n26\n00:01:55,540 --> 00:01:57,220\naffairs.\n\n27\n00:01:56,970 --> 00:02:02,700\nA lot of Imperialist ladies asked me to tea\nto meet schoolmasters from New Zealand and\n\n28\n00:02:02,700 --> 00:02:08,149\neditors from Vancouver, and that was the\ndismalest business of all.\n\n29\n00:02:08,149 --> 00:02:15,340\nHere was I, thirty-seven years old, sound\nin wind and limb, with enough money to have\n\n30\n00:02:15,340 --> 00:02:19,599\na good time, yawning my head off all day.\n\n31\n00:02:19,340 --> 00:02:24,900\nI had just about settled to clear out and\nget back to the veld, for I was the best\n\n32\n00:02:24,900 --> 00:02:27,690\nbored man in the United Kingdom.\n\n33\n00:02:27,440 --> 00:02:32,420\nThat afternoon I had been worrying my\nbrokers about investments to give my mind\n\n34\n00:02:32,420 --> 00:02:38,750\nsomething to work on, and on my way home I\nturned into my club--rather a pot-house,\n\n35\n00:02:38,750 --> 00:02:41,830\nwhich took in Colonial members.\n\n36\n00:02:41,830 --> 00:02:45,410\nI had a long drink, and read the evening\npapers.\n\n37\n00:02:45,410 --> 00:02:50,710\nThey were full of the row in the Near East,\nand there was an article about Karolides,\n\n38\n00:02:50,710 --> 00:02:52,640\nthe Greek Premier.\n\n39\n00:02:52,640 --> 00:02:57,300\nI rather fancied the chap.\nFrom all accounts he seemed the one big man\n\n40\n00:02:57,300 --> 00:03:01,819\nin the show; and he played a straight game\ntoo, which was more than could be said for\n\n41\n00:03:01,819 --> 00:03:03,640\nmost of them.\n\n42\n00:03:03,640 --> 00:03:08,680\nI gathered that they hated him pretty\nblackly in Berlin and Vienna, but that we\n\n43\n00:03:08,680 --> 00:03:13,520\nwere going to stick by him, and one paper\nsaid that he was the only barrier between\n\n44\n00:03:13,520 --> 00:03:16,260\nEurope and Armageddon.\n\n45\n00:03:16,260 --> 00:03:21,090\nI remember wondering if I could get a job\nin those parts.\n\n46\n00:03:21,090 --> 00:03:26,940\nIt struck me that Albania was the sort of\nplace that might keep a man from yawning.\n\n47\n00:03:26,940 --> 00:03:32,840\nAbout six o'clock I went home, dressed,\ndined at the Cafe Royal, and turned into a\n\n48\n00:03:32,840 --> 00:03:37,590\nmusic-hall.\nIt was a silly show, all capering women and\n\n49\n00:03:37,590 --> 00:03:41,670\nmonkey-faced men, and I did not stay long.\n\n50\n00:03:41,670 --> 00:03:46,610\nThe night was fine and clear as I walked\nback to the flat I had hired near Portland\n\n51\n00:03:46,610 --> 00:03:48,160\nPlace.\n\n52\n00:03:47,910 --> 00:03:53,680\nThe crowd surged past me on the pavements,\nbusy and chattering, and I envied the\n\n53\n00:03:53,680 --> 00:03:57,209\npeople for having something to do.\n\n54\n00:03:56,959 --> 00:04:02,709\nThese shop-girls and clerks and dandies and\npolicemen had some interest in life that\n\n55\n00:04:02,709 --> 00:04:06,810\nkept them going.\nI gave half-a-crown to a beggar because I\n\n56\n00:04:06,810 --> 00:04:10,230\nsaw him yawn; he was a fellow-sufferer.\n\n57\n00:04:10,230 --> 00:04:16,539\nAt Oxford Circus I looked up into the\nspring sky and I made a vow.\n\n58\n00:04:16,539 --> 00:04:22,320\nI would give the Old Country another day to\nfit me into something; if nothing happened,\n\n59\n00:04:22,320 --> 00:04:26,990\nI would take the next boat for the Cape.\n\n60\n00:04:26,990 --> 00:04:31,580\nMy flat was the first floor in a new block\nbehind Langham Place.\n\n61\n00:04:31,580 --> 00:04:36,230\nThere was a common staircase, with a porter\nand a liftman at the entrance, but there\n\n62\n00:04:36,230 --> 00:04:41,480\nwas no restaurant or anything of that sort,\nand each flat was quite shut off from the\n\n63\n00:04:41,480 --> 00:04:41,730\nothers.\n\n64\n00:04:41,480 --> 00:04:47,660\nI hate servants on the premises, so I had a\nfellow to look after me who came in by the\n\n65\n00:04:47,660 --> 00:04:49,310\nday.\n\n66\n00:04:49,060 --> 00:04:53,850\nHe arrived before eight o'clock every\nmorning and used to depart at seven, for I\n\n67\n00:04:53,850 --> 00:04:58,230\nnever dined at home.\nI was just fitting my key into the door\n\n68\n00:04:58,230 --> 00:05:01,090\nwhen I noticed a man at my elbow.\n\n69\n00:05:01,090 --> 00:05:06,160\nI had not seen him approach, and the sudden\nappearance made me start.\n\n70\n00:05:06,160 --> 00:05:12,340\nHe was a slim man, with a short brown beard\nand small, gimlety blue eyes.\n\n71\n00:05:12,340 --> 00:05:17,090\nI recognized him as the occupant of a flat\non the top floor, with whom I had passed\n\n72\n00:05:17,090 --> 00:05:22,650\nthe time of day on the stairs.\n'Can I speak to you?' he said.\n\n73\n00:05:22,650 --> 00:05:25,690\n'May I come in for a minute?'\n\n74\n00:05:25,690 --> 00:05:30,730\nHe was steadying his voice with an effort,\nand his hand was pawing my arm.\n\n75\n00:05:30,730 --> 00:05:32,960\nI got my door open and motioned him in.\n\n76\n00:05:33,540 --> 00:05:37,740\nNo sooner was he over the threshold than he\nmade a dash for my back room, where I used\n\n77\n00:05:37,740 --> 00:05:41,750\nto smoke and write my letters.\nThen he bolted back.\n\n78\n00:05:41,750 --> 00:05:47,650\n'Is the door locked?' he asked feverishly,\nand he fastened the chain with his own\n\n79\n00:05:47,650 --> 00:05:52,310\nhand.\n'I'm very sorry,' he said humbly.\n\n80\n00:05:52,310 --> 00:05:57,010\n'It's a mighty liberty, but you looked the\nkind of man who would understand.\n\n81\n00:05:57,010 --> 00:06:01,320\nI've had you in my mind all this week when\nthings got troublesome.\n\n82\n00:06:01,320 --> 00:06:05,110\nSay, will you do me a good turn?'\n\n83\n00:06:05,110 --> 00:06:09,740\n'I'll listen to you,' I said.\n'That's all I'll promise.'\n\n84\n00:06:09,740 --> 00:06:13,380\nI was getting worried by the antics of this\nnervous little chap.\n\n85\n00:06:13,380 --> 00:06:18,740\nThere was a tray of drinks on a table\nbeside him, from which he filled himself a\n\n86\n00:06:18,740 --> 00:06:23,680\nstiff whisky-and-soda.\nHe drank it off in three gulps, and cracked\n\n87\n00:06:23,680 --> 00:06:25,949\nthe glass as he set it down.\n\n88\n00:06:25,949 --> 00:06:30,440\n'Pardon,' he said, 'I'm a bit rattled\ntonight.\n\n89\n00:06:30,440 --> 00:06:35,210\nYou see, I happen at this moment to be\ndead.'\n\n90\n00:06:35,210 --> 00:06:37,870\nI sat down in an armchair and lit my pipe.\n\n91\n00:06:37,870 --> 00:06:41,949\n'What does it feel like?'\nI asked.\n\n92\n00:06:41,949 --> 00:06:46,000\nI was pretty certain that I had to deal\nwith a madman.\n\n93\n00:06:46,000 --> 00:06:48,740\nA smile flickered over his drawn face.\n\n94\n00:06:48,740 --> 00:06:54,699\n'I'm not mad--yet.\nSay, Sir, I've been watching you, and I\n\n95\n00:06:54,699 --> 00:06:59,259\nreckon you're a cool customer.\nI reckon, too, you're an honest man, and\n\n96\n00:06:59,259 --> 00:07:02,800\nnot afraid of playing a bold hand.\n\n97\n00:07:02,800 --> 00:07:08,120\nI'm going to confide in you.\nI need help worse than any man ever needed\n\n98\n00:07:08,120 --> 00:07:12,099\nit, and I want to know if I can count you\nin.'\n\n99\n00:07:12,100 --> 00:07:18,000\n'Get on with your yarn,' I said, 'and I'll\ntell you.'\n\n100\n00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:22,940\nHe seemed to brace himself for a great\neffort, and then started on the queerest\n\n101\n00:07:22,940 --> 00:07:24,680\nrigmarole.\n\n102\n00:07:24,680 --> 00:07:29,389\nI didn't get hold of it at first, and I had\nto stop and ask him questions.\n\n103\n00:07:29,389 --> 00:07:32,199\nBut here is the gist of it:\n\n104\n00:07:31,949 --> 00:07:37,270\nHe was an American, from Kentucky, and\nafter college, being pretty well off, he\n\n105\n00:07:37,270 --> 00:07:39,900\nhad started out to see the world.\n\n106\n00:07:39,650 --> 00:07:44,540\nHe wrote a bit, and acted as war\ncorrespondent for a Chicago paper, and\n\n107\n00:07:44,540 --> 00:07:47,990\nspent a year or two in South-Eastern\nEurope.\n\n108\n00:07:47,990 --> 00:07:53,380\nI gathered that he was a fine linguist, and\nhad got to know pretty well the society in\n\n109\n00:07:53,380 --> 00:07:58,520\nthose parts.\nHe spoke familiarly of many names that I\n\n110\n00:07:58,520 --> 00:08:01,190\nremembered to have seen in the newspapers.\n\n111\n00:08:01,190 --> 00:08:07,199\nHe had played about with politics, he told\nme, at first for the interest of them, and\n\n112\n00:08:07,199 --> 00:08:10,690\nthen because he couldn't help himself.\n\n113\n00:08:10,440 --> 00:08:15,580\nI read him as a sharp, restless fellow, who\nalways wanted to get down to the roots of\n\n114\n00:08:15,580 --> 00:08:19,139\nthings.\nHe got a little further down than he\n\n115\n00:08:19,139 --> 00:08:21,600\nwanted.\n\n116\n00:08:21,600 --> 00:08:25,919\nI am giving you what he told me as well as\nI could make it out.\n\n117\n00:08:25,919 --> 00:08:29,770\nAway behind all the Governments and the\narmies there was a big subterranean\n\n118\n00:08:29,770 --> 00:08:35,140\nmovement going on, engineered by very\ndangerous people.\n\n119\n00:08:35,139 --> 00:08:40,619\nHe had come on it by accident; it\nfascinated him; he went further, and then\n\n120\n00:08:40,619 --> 00:08:42,939\nhe got caught.\n\n121\n00:08:42,689 --> 00:08:47,499\nI gathered that most of the people in it\nwere the sort of educated anarchists that\n\n122\n00:08:47,499 --> 00:08:52,660\nmake revolutions, but that beside them\nthere were financiers who were playing for\n\n123\n00:08:52,660 --> 00:08:53,420\nmoney.\n\n124\n00:08:53,420 --> 00:08:59,179\nA clever man can make big profits on a\nfalling market, and it suited the book of\n\n125\n00:08:59,179 --> 00:09:03,470\nboth classes to set Europe by the ears.\n\n126\n00:09:03,220 --> 00:09:08,709\nHe told me some queer things that explained\na lot that had puzzled me--things that\n\n127\n00:09:08,709 --> 00:09:14,959\nhappened in the Balkan War, how one state\nsuddenly came out on top, why alliances\n\n128\n00:09:14,959 --> 00:09:18,050\nwere made and broken, why certain men\n\n129\n00:09:18,050 --> 00:09:23,290\ndisappeared, and where the sinews of war\ncame from.\n\n130\n00:09:23,290 --> 00:09:27,249\nThe aim of the whole conspiracy was to get\nRussia and Germany at loggerheads.\n\n131\n00:09:27,249 --> 00:09:33,300\nWhen I asked why, he said that the\nanarchist lot thought it would give them\n\n132\n00:09:33,300 --> 00:09:38,129\ntheir chance.\nEverything would be in the melting-pot, and\n\n133\n00:09:38,129 --> 00:09:41,170\nthey looked to see a new world emerge.\n\n134\n00:09:41,170 --> 00:09:46,550\nThe capitalists would rake in the shekels,\nand make fortunes by buying up wreckage.\n\n135\n00:09:46,550 --> 00:09:51,689\nCapital, he said, had no conscience and no\nfatherland.\n\n136\n00:09:51,689 --> 00:09:58,019\nBesides, the Jew was behind it, and the Jew\nhated Russia worse than hell.\n\n137\n00:09:58,019 --> 00:10:01,319\n'Do you wonder?' he cried.\n\n138\n00:10:01,069 --> 00:10:06,279\n'For three hundred years they have been\npersecuted, and this is the return match\n\n139\n00:10:06,279 --> 00:10:11,209\nfor the pogroms.\nThe Jew is everywhere, but you have to go\n\n140\n00:10:11,209 --> 00:10:15,119\nfar down the backstairs to find him.\n\n141\n00:10:15,119 --> 00:10:21,730\nTake any big Teutonic business concern.\nIf you have dealings with it the first man\n\n142\n00:10:21,730 --> 00:10:28,829\nyou meet is Prince von und Zu Something, an\nelegant young man who talks Eton-and-Harrow\n\n143\n00:10:28,829 --> 00:10:29,489\nEnglish.\n\n144\n00:10:29,489 --> 00:10:36,259\nBut he cuts no ice.\nIf your business is big, you get behind him\n\n145\n00:10:36,259 --> 00:10:44,060\nand find a prognathous Westphalian with a\nretreating brow and the manners of a hog.\n\n146\n00:10:44,059 --> 00:10:48,889\nHe is the German business man that gives\nyour English papers the shakes.\n\n147\n00:10:48,889 --> 00:10:54,529\nBut if you're on the biggest kind of job\nand are bound to get to the real boss, ten\n\n148\n00:10:54,529 --> 00:11:01,350\nto one you are brought up against a little\nwhite-faced Jew in a bath-chair with an eye\n\n149\n00:11:01,350 --> 00:11:02,610\nlike a rattlesnake.\n\n150\n00:11:02,610 --> 00:11:08,610\nYes, Sir, he is the man who is ruling the\nworld just now, and he has his knife in the\n\n151\n00:11:08,610 --> 00:11:16,079\nEmpire of the Tzar, because his aunt was\noutraged and his father flogged in some\n\n152\n00:11:16,079 --> 00:11:20,139\none-horse location on the Volga.'\n\n153\n00:11:20,139 --> 00:11:25,610\nI could not help saying that his Jew-\nanarchists seemed to have got left behind a\n\n154\n00:11:25,610 --> 00:11:29,000\nlittle.\n'Yes and no,' he said.\n\n155\n00:11:28,999 --> 00:11:34,339\n'They won up to a point, but they struck a\nbigger thing than money, a thing that\n\n156\n00:11:34,339 --> 00:11:40,609\ncouldn't be bought, the old elemental\nfighting instincts of man.\n\n157\n00:11:40,610 --> 00:11:45,749\nIf you're going to be killed you invent\nsome kind of flag and country to fight for,\n\n158\n00:11:45,749 --> 00:11:49,500\nand if you survive you get to love the\nthing.\n\n159\n00:11:49,499 --> 00:11:56,059\nThose foolish devils of soldiers have found\nsomething they care for, and that has upset\n\n160\n00:11:56,059 --> 00:12:02,799\nthe pretty plan laid in Berlin and Vienna.\nBut my friends haven't played their last\n\n161\n00:12:02,799 --> 00:12:05,779\ncard by a long sight.\n\n162\n00:12:05,779 --> 00:12:10,939\nThey've gotten the ace up their sleeves,\nand unless I can keep alive for a month\n\n163\n00:12:10,939 --> 00:12:17,449\nthey are going to play it and win.'\n'But I thought you were dead,' I put in.\n\n164\n00:12:17,449 --> 00:12:22,069\n'MORS JANUA VITAE,' he smiled.\n\n165\n00:12:22,069 --> 00:12:27,179\n(I recognized the quotation: it was about\nall the Latin I knew.)\n\n166\n00:12:27,179 --> 00:12:33,360\n'I'm coming to that, but I've got to put\nyou wise about a lot of things first.\n\n167\n00:12:33,360 --> 00:12:39,350\nIf you read your newspaper, I guess you\nknow the name of Constantine Karolides?'\n\n168\n00:12:39,350 --> 00:12:44,249\nI sat up at that, for I had been reading\nabout him that very afternoon.\n\n169\n00:12:44,249 --> 00:12:48,279\n'He is the man that has wrecked all their\ngames.\n\n170\n00:12:48,279 --> 00:12:55,069\nHe is the one big brain in the whole show,\nand he happens also to be an honest man.\n\n171\n00:12:55,069 --> 00:12:59,269\nTherefore he has been marked down these\ntwelve months past.\n\n172\n00:12:59,269 --> 00:13:03,869\nI found that out--not that it was\ndifficult, for any fool could guess as\n\n173\n00:13:03,869 --> 00:13:04,319\nmuch.\n\n174\n00:13:04,319 --> 00:13:11,660\nBut I found out the way they were going to\nget him, and that knowledge was deadly.\n\n175\n00:13:11,660 --> 00:13:15,589\nThat's why I have had to decease.'\n\n176\n00:13:15,339 --> 00:13:20,110\nHe had another drink, and I mixed it for\nhim myself, for I was getting interested in\n\n177\n00:13:20,110 --> 00:13:21,649\nthe beggar.\n\n178\n00:13:21,399 --> 00:13:27,929\n'They can't get him in his own land, for he\nhas a bodyguard of Epirotes that would skin\n\n179\n00:13:27,929 --> 00:13:32,769\ntheir grandmothers.\nBut on the 15th day of June he is coming to\n\n180\n00:13:32,769 --> 00:13:34,879\nthis city.\n\n181\n00:13:34,879 --> 00:13:40,119\nThe British Foreign Office has taken to\nhaving International tea-parties, and the\n\n182\n00:13:40,119 --> 00:13:42,679\nbiggest of them is due on that date.\n\n183\n00:13:42,429 --> 00:13:47,829\nNow Karolides is reckoned the principal\nguest, and if my friends have their way he\n\n184\n00:13:47,829 --> 00:13:50,739\nwill never return to his admiring\ncountrymen.'\n\n185\n00:13:50,739 --> 00:13:54,829\n'That's simple enough, anyhow,' I said.\n\n186\n00:13:54,829 --> 00:14:01,949\n'You can warn him and keep him at home.'\n'And play their game?' he asked sharply.\n\n187\n00:14:01,949 --> 00:14:06,970\n'If he does not come they win, for he's the\nonly man that can straighten out the\n\n188\n00:14:06,970 --> 00:14:08,189\ntangle.\n\n189\n00:14:08,189 --> 00:14:12,959\nAnd if his Government are warned he won't\ncome, for he does not know how big the\n\n190\n00:14:12,959 --> 00:14:19,239\nstakes will be on June the 15th.'\n'What about the British Government?'\n\n191\n00:14:19,239 --> 00:14:20,100\nI said.\n\n192\n00:14:20,100 --> 00:14:23,230\n'They're not going to let their guests be\nmurdered.\n\n193\n00:14:23,230 --> 00:14:26,189\nTip them the wink, and they'll take extra\nprecautions.'\n\n194\n00:14:26,189 --> 00:14:28,369\n'No good.\n\n195\n00:14:28,369 --> 00:14:33,699\nThey might stuff your city with plain-\nclothes detectives and double the police\n\n196\n00:14:33,699 --> 00:14:37,549\nand Constantine would still be a doomed\nman.\n\n197\n00:14:37,549 --> 00:14:40,749\nMy friends are not playing this game for\ncandy.\n\n198\n00:14:40,749 --> 00:14:45,600\nThey want a big occasion for the taking\noff, with the eyes of all Europe on it.\n\n199\n00:14:45,600 --> 00:14:49,929\nHe'll be murdered by an Austrian, and\nthere'll be plenty of evidence to show the\n\n200\n00:14:49,929 --> 00:14:53,869\nconnivance of the big folk in Vienna and\nBerlin.\n\n201\n00:14:53,869 --> 00:14:59,269\nIt will all be an infernal lie, of course,\nbut the case will look black enough to the\n\n202\n00:14:59,269 --> 00:15:02,639\nworld.\nI'm not talking hot air, my friend.\n\n203\n00:15:02,639 --> 00:15:09,019\nI happen to know every detail of the\nhellish contrivance, and I can tell you it\n\n204\n00:15:09,019 --> 00:15:14,209\nwill be the most finished piece of\nblackguardism since the Borgias.\n\n205\n00:15:14,209 --> 00:15:18,449\nBut it's not going to come off if there's a\ncertain man who knows the wheels of the\n\n206\n00:15:18,449 --> 00:15:23,850\nbusiness alive right here in London on the\n15th day of June.\n\n207\n00:15:23,850 --> 00:15:30,049\nAnd that man is going to be your servant,\nFranklin P. Scudder.'\n\n208\n00:15:30,049 --> 00:15:35,669\nI was getting to like the little chap.\nHis jaw had shut like a rat-trap, and there\n\n209\n00:15:35,669 --> 00:15:39,069\nwas the fire of battle in his gimlety eyes.\n\n210\n00:15:39,069 --> 00:15:42,559\nIf he was spinning me a yarn he could act\nup to it.\n\n211\n00:15:42,559 --> 00:15:46,720\n'Where did you find out this story?'\nI asked.\n\n212\n00:15:46,720 --> 00:15:52,209\n'I got the first hint in an inn on the\nAchensee in Tyrol.\n\n213\n00:15:52,209 --> 00:15:57,549\nThat set me inquiring, and I collected my\nother clues in a fur-shop in the Galician\n\n214\n00:15:57,549 --> 00:16:03,949\nquarter of Buda, in a Strangers' Club in\nVienna, and in a little bookshop off the\n\n215\n00:16:03,949 --> 00:16:06,939\nRacknitzstrasse in Leipsic.\n\n216\n00:16:06,939 --> 00:16:10,949\nI completed my evidence ten days ago in\nParis.\n\n217\n00:16:10,949 --> 00:16:14,730\nI can't tell you the details now, for it's\nsomething of a history.\n\n218\n00:16:14,730 --> 00:16:20,239\nWhen I was quite sure in my own mind I\njudged it my business to disappear, and I\n\n219\n00:16:20,239 --> 00:16:24,240\nreached this city by a mighty queer\ncircuit.\n\n220\n00:16:24,239 --> 00:16:29,699\nI left Paris a dandified young French-\nAmerican, and I sailed from Hamburg a Jew\n\n221\n00:16:29,699 --> 00:16:31,969\ndiamond merchant.\n\n222\n00:16:31,720 --> 00:16:37,369\nIn Norway I was an English student of Ibsen\ncollecting materials for lectures, but when\n\n223\n00:16:37,369 --> 00:16:42,429\nI left Bergen I was a cinema-man with\nspecial ski films.\n\n224\n00:16:42,429 --> 00:16:47,079\nAnd I came here from Leith with a lot of\npulp-wood propositions in my pocket to put\n\n225\n00:16:47,079 --> 00:16:51,790\nbefore the London newspapers.\nTill yesterday I thought I had muddied my\n\n226\n00:16:51,790 --> 00:16:55,919\ntrail some, and was feeling pretty happy.\n\n227\n00:16:55,919 --> 00:16:59,629\nThen ...'\nThe recollection seemed to upset him, and\n\n228\n00:16:59,629 --> 00:17:05,440\nhe gulped down some more whisky.\n'Then I saw a man standing in the street\n\n229\n00:17:05,440 --> 00:17:07,020\noutside this block.\n\n230\n00:17:07,020 --> 00:17:12,270\nI used to stay close in my room all day,\nand only slip out after dark for an hour or\n\n231\n00:17:12,270 --> 00:17:16,020\ntwo.\nI watched him for a bit from my window, and\n\n232\n00:17:16,020 --> 00:17:18,300\nI thought I recognized him ...\n\n233\n00:17:18,300 --> 00:17:24,320\nHe came in and spoke to the porter ...\nWhen I came back from my walk last night I\n\n234\n00:17:24,320 --> 00:17:29,800\nfound a card in my letter-box.\nIt bore the name of the man I want least to\n\n235\n00:17:29,800 --> 00:17:32,870\nmeet on God's earth.'\n\n236\n00:17:32,870 --> 00:17:39,550\nI think that the look in my companion's\neyes, the sheer naked scare on his face,\n\n237\n00:17:39,550 --> 00:17:45,420\ncompleted my conviction of his honesty.\nMy own voice sharpened a bit as I asked him\n\n238\n00:17:45,420 --> 00:17:47,310\nwhat he did next.\n\n239\n00:17:47,310 --> 00:17:53,370\n'I realized that I was bottled as sure as a\npickled herring, and that there was only\n\n240\n00:17:53,370 --> 00:17:57,230\none way out.\nI had to die.\n\n241\n00:17:57,230 --> 00:18:02,010\nIf my pursuers knew I was dead they would\ngo to sleep again.'\n\n242\n00:18:02,010 --> 00:18:03,960\n'How did you manage it?'\n\n243\n00:18:03,710 --> 00:18:10,350\n'I told the man that valets me that I was\nfeeling pretty bad, and I got myself up to\n\n244\n00:18:10,350 --> 00:18:15,790\nlook like death.\nThat wasn't difficult, for I'm no slouch at\n\n245\n00:18:15,790 --> 00:18:16,690\ndisguises.\n\n246\n00:18:16,690 --> 00:18:21,740\nThen I got a corpse--you can always get a\nbody in London if you know where to go for\n\n247\n00:18:21,740 --> 00:18:22,920\nit.\n\n248\n00:18:22,670 --> 00:18:27,330\nI fetched it back in a trunk on the top of\na four-wheeler, and I had to be assisted\n\n249\n00:18:27,330 --> 00:18:31,630\nupstairs to my room.\nYou see I had to pile up some evidence for\n\n250\n00:18:31,630 --> 00:18:33,540\nthe inquest.\n\n251\n00:18:33,540 --> 00:18:38,580\nI went to bed and got my man to mix me a\nsleeping-draught, and then told him to\n\n252\n00:18:38,580 --> 00:18:42,610\nclear out.\nHe wanted to fetch a doctor, but I swore\n\n253\n00:18:42,610 --> 00:18:46,630\nsome and said I couldn't abide leeches.\n\n254\n00:18:46,630 --> 00:18:50,820\nWhen I was left alone I started in to fake\nup that corpse.\n\n255\n00:18:50,820 --> 00:18:56,190\nHe was my size, and I judged had perished\nfrom too much alcohol, so I put some\n\n256\n00:18:56,190 --> 00:18:59,160\nspirits handy about the place.\n\n257\n00:18:59,160 --> 00:19:04,530\nThe jaw was the weak point in the likeness,\nso I blew it away with a revolver.\n\n258\n00:19:04,530 --> 00:19:10,000\nI daresay there will be somebody tomorrow\nto swear to having heard a shot, but there\n\n259\n00:19:10,000 --> 00:19:14,750\nare no neighbours on my floor, and I\nguessed I could risk it.\n\n260\n00:19:14,750 --> 00:19:20,380\nSo I left the body in bed dressed up in my\npyjamas, with a revolver lying on the bed-\n\n261\n00:19:20,380 --> 00:19:26,350\nclothes and a considerable mess around.\nThen I got into a suit of clothes I had\n\n262\n00:19:26,350 --> 00:19:28,630\nkept waiting for emergencies.\n\n263\n00:19:28,630 --> 00:19:34,400\nI didn't dare to shave for fear of leaving\ntracks, and besides, it wasn't any kind of\n\n264\n00:19:34,400 --> 00:19:37,630\nuse my trying to get into the streets.\n\n265\n00:19:37,380 --> 00:19:42,290\nI had had you in my mind all day, and there\nseemed nothing to do but to make an appeal\n\n266\n00:19:42,290 --> 00:19:44,169\nto you.\n\n267\n00:19:43,920 --> 00:19:48,370\nI watched from my window till I saw you\ncome home, and then slipped down the stair\n\n268\n00:19:48,370 --> 00:19:52,470\nto meet you ...\nThere, Sir, I guess you know about as much\n\n269\n00:19:52,470 --> 00:19:56,040\nas me of this business.'\n\n270\n00:19:56,040 --> 00:20:02,650\nHe sat blinking like an owl, fluttering\nwith nerves and yet desperately determined.\n\n271\n00:20:02,650 --> 00:20:06,809\nBy this time I was pretty well convinced\nthat he was going straight with me.\n\n272\n00:20:06,810 --> 00:20:12,040\nIt was the wildest sort of narrative, but I\nhad heard in my time many steep tales which\n\n273\n00:20:12,040 --> 00:20:18,300\nhad turned out to be true, and I had made a\npractice of judging the man rather than the\n\n274\n00:20:18,300 --> 00:20:19,350\nstory.\n\n275\n00:20:19,350 --> 00:20:23,760\nIf he had wanted to get a location in my\nflat, and then cut my throat, he would have\n\n276\n00:20:23,760 --> 00:20:29,260\npitched a milder yarn.\n'Hand me your key,' I said, 'and I'll take\n\n277\n00:20:29,260 --> 00:20:30,990\na look at the corpse.\n\n278\n00:20:30,990 --> 00:20:36,130\nExcuse my caution, but I'm bound to verify\na bit if I can.'\n\n279\n00:20:36,130 --> 00:20:40,850\nHe shook his head mournfully.\n'I reckoned you'd ask for that, but I\n\n280\n00:20:40,850 --> 00:20:41,640\nhaven't got it.\n\n281\n00:20:41,640 --> 00:20:46,140\nIt's on my chain on the dressing-table.\nI had to leave it behind, for I couldn't\n\n282\n00:20:46,140 --> 00:20:51,910\nleave any clues to breed suspicions.\nThe gentry who are after me are pretty\n\n283\n00:20:51,910 --> 00:20:54,270\nbright-eyed citizens.\n\n284\n00:20:54,270 --> 00:20:58,910\nYou'll have to take me on trust for the\nnight, and tomorrow you'll get proof of the\n\n285\n00:20:58,910 --> 00:21:04,680\ncorpse business right enough.'\nI thought for an instant or two.\n\n286\n00:21:04,680 --> 00:21:05,850\n'Right.\n\n287\n00:21:05,850 --> 00:21:10,590\nI'll trust you for the night.\nI'll lock you into this room and keep the\n\n288\n00:21:10,590 --> 00:21:13,500\nkey.\nJust one word, Mr Scudder.\n\n289\n00:21:13,500 --> 00:21:19,330\nI believe you're straight, but if so be you\nare not I should warn you that I'm a handy\n\n290\n00:21:19,330 --> 00:21:24,250\nman with a gun.'\n'Sure,' he said, jumping up with some\n\n291\n00:21:24,250 --> 00:21:25,090\nbriskness.\n\n292\n00:21:25,090 --> 00:21:30,620\n'I haven't the privilege of your name, Sir,\nbut let me tell you that you're a white\n\n293\n00:21:30,620 --> 00:21:33,260\nman.\nI'll thank you to lend me a razor.'\n\n294\n00:21:33,260 --> 00:21:37,820\nI took him into my bedroom and turned him\nloose.\n\n295\n00:21:37,820 --> 00:21:43,160\nIn half an hour's time a figure came out\nthat I scarcely recognized.\n\n296\n00:21:43,160 --> 00:21:47,040\nOnly his gimlety, hungry eyes were the\nsame.\n\n297\n00:21:47,040 --> 00:21:52,840\nHe was shaved clean, his hair was parted in\nthe middle, and he had cut his eyebrows.\n\n298\n00:21:52,840 --> 00:21:59,060\nFurther, he carried himself as if he had\nbeen drilled, and was the very model, even\n\n299\n00:21:59,060 --> 00:22:05,500\nto the brown complexion, of some British\nofficer who had had a long spell in India.\n\n300\n00:22:05,500 --> 00:22:10,850\nHe had a monocle, too, which he stuck in\nhis eye, and every trace of the American\n\n301\n00:22:10,850 --> 00:22:14,780\nhad gone out of his speech.\n'My hat!\n\n302\n00:22:14,780 --> 00:22:17,250\nMr Scudder--' I stammered.\n\n303\n00:22:17,250 --> 00:22:22,850\n'Not Mr Scudder,' he corrected; 'Captain\nTheophilus Digby, of the 40th Gurkhas,\n\n304\n00:22:22,850 --> 00:22:27,880\npresently home on leave.\nI'll thank you to remember that, Sir.'\n\n305\n00:22:27,890 --> 00:22:32,910\nI made him up a bed in my smoking-room and\nsought my own couch, more cheerful than I\n\n306\n00:22:32,910 --> 00:22:37,620\nhad been for the past month.\nThings did happen occasionally, even in\n\n307\n00:22:37,620 --> 00:22:41,330\nthis God-forgotten metropolis.\n\n308\n00:22:41,330 --> 00:22:45,940\nI woke next morning to hear my man,\nPaddock, making the deuce of a row at the\n\n309\n00:22:45,940 --> 00:22:48,850\nsmoking-room door.\n\n310\n00:22:48,600 --> 00:22:54,470\nPaddock was a fellow I had done a good turn\nto out on the Selakwe, and I had inspanned\n\n311\n00:22:54,470 --> 00:22:58,570\nhim as my servant as soon as I got to\nEngland.\n\n312\n00:22:58,570 --> 00:23:04,490\nHe had about as much gift of the gab as a\nhippopotamus, and was not a great hand at\n\n313\n00:23:04,490 --> 00:23:08,840\nvaleting, but I knew I could count on his\nloyalty.\n\n314\n00:23:08,840 --> 00:23:11,410\n'Stop that row, Paddock,' I said.\n\n315\n00:23:11,410 --> 00:23:16,810\n'There's a friend of mine, Captain--\nCaptain' (I couldn't remember the name)\n\n316\n00:23:16,810 --> 00:23:20,240\n'dossing down in there.\nGet breakfast for two and then come and\n\n317\n00:23:20,240 --> 00:23:21,680\nspeak to me.'\n\n318\n00:23:21,680 --> 00:23:27,710\nI told Paddock a fine story about how my\nfriend was a great swell, with his nerves\n\n319\n00:23:27,710 --> 00:23:34,370\npretty bad from overwork, who wanted\nabsolute rest and stillness.\n\n320\n00:23:34,370 --> 00:23:38,940\nNobody had got to know he was here, or he\nwould be besieged by communications from\n\n321\n00:23:38,940 --> 00:23:42,820\nthe India Office and the Prime Minister and\nhis cure would be ruined.\n\n322\n00:23:42,820 --> 00:23:48,769\nI am bound to say Scudder played up\nsplendidly when he came to breakfast.\n\n323\n00:23:48,770 --> 00:23:53,780\nHe fixed Paddock with his eyeglass, just\nlike a British officer, asked him about the\n\n324\n00:23:53,780 --> 00:24:00,850\nBoer War, and slung out at me a lot of\nstuff about imaginary pals.\n\n325\n00:24:00,850 --> 00:24:05,990\nPaddock couldn't learn to call me 'Sir',\nbut he 'sirred' Scudder as if his life\n\n326\n00:24:05,990 --> 00:24:08,480\ndepended on it.\n\n327\n00:24:08,230 --> 00:24:13,000\nI left him with the newspaper and a box of\ncigars, and went down to the City till\n\n328\n00:24:13,000 --> 00:24:16,470\nluncheon.\nWhen I got back the lift-man had an\n\n329\n00:24:16,470 --> 00:24:18,010\nimportant face.\n\n330\n00:24:18,010 --> 00:24:24,220\n'Nawsty business 'ere this morning, Sir.\nGent in No. 15 been and shot 'isself.\n\n331\n00:24:24,220 --> 00:24:30,180\nThey've just took 'im to the mortiary.\nThe police are up there now.'\n\n332\n00:24:30,180 --> 00:24:36,350\nI ascended to No. 15, and found a couple of\nbobbies and an inspector busy making an\n\n333\n00:24:36,350 --> 00:24:39,580\nexamination.\nI asked a few idiotic questions, and they\n\n334\n00:24:39,580 --> 00:24:42,060\nsoon kicked me out.\n\n335\n00:24:42,060 --> 00:24:46,960\nThen I found the man that had valeted\nScudder, and pumped him, but I could see he\n\n336\n00:24:46,960 --> 00:24:49,390\nsuspected nothing.\n\n337\n00:24:49,140 --> 00:24:54,770\nHe was a whining fellow with a churchyard\nface, and half-a-crown went far to console\n\n338\n00:24:54,770 --> 00:24:57,620\nhim.\nI attended the inquest next day.\n\n339\n00:24:57,620 --> 00:25:03,160\nA partner of some publishing firm gave\nevidence that the deceased had brought him\n\n340\n00:25:03,160 --> 00:25:10,050\nwood-pulp propositions, and had been, he\nbelieved, an agent of an American business.\n\n341\n00:25:10,050 --> 00:25:15,450\nThe jury found it a case of suicide while\nof unsound mind, and the few effects were\n\n342\n00:25:15,450 --> 00:25:19,270\nhanded over to the American Consul to deal\nwith.\n\n343\n00:25:19,270 --> 00:25:25,450\nI gave Scudder a full account of the\naffair, and it interested him greatly.\n\n344\n00:25:25,450 --> 00:25:29,570\nHe said he wished he could have attended\nthe inquest, for he reckoned it would be\n\n345\n00:25:29,570 --> 00:25:34,420\nabout as spicy as to read one's own\nobituary notice.\n\n346\n00:25:34,420 --> 00:25:39,250\nThe first two days he stayed with me in\nthat back room he was very peaceful.\n\n347\n00:25:39,250 --> 00:25:44,250\nHe read and smoked a bit, and made a heap\nof jottings in a note-book, and every night\n\n348\n00:25:44,250 --> 00:25:48,690\nwe had a game of chess, at which he beat me\nhollow.\n\n349\n00:25:48,690 --> 00:25:53,320\nI think he was nursing his nerves back to\nhealth, for he had had a pretty trying\n\n350\n00:25:53,320 --> 00:25:56,590\ntime.\nBut on the third day I could see he was\n\n351\n00:25:56,590 --> 00:25:59,010\nbeginning to get restless.\n\n352\n00:25:59,010 --> 00:26:04,160\nHe fixed up a list of the days till June\n15th, and ticked each off with a red\n\n353\n00:26:04,160 --> 00:26:08,850\npencil, making remarks in shorthand against\nthem.\n\n354\n00:26:08,850 --> 00:26:14,800\nI would find him sunk in a brown study,\nwith his sharp eyes abstracted, and after\n\n355\n00:26:14,800 --> 00:26:20,919\nthose spells of meditation he was apt to be\nvery despondent.\n\n356\n00:26:20,920 --> 00:26:24,300\nThen I could see that he began to get edgy\nagain.\n\n357\n00:26:24,300 --> 00:26:28,600\nHe listened for little noises, and was\nalways asking me if Paddock could be\n\n358\n00:26:28,600 --> 00:26:29,340\ntrusted.\n\n359\n00:26:29,340 --> 00:26:34,500\nOnce or twice he got very peevish, and\napologized for it.\n\n360\n00:26:34,500 --> 00:26:38,690\nI didn't blame him.\nI made every allowance, for he had taken on\n\n361\n00:26:38,690 --> 00:26:40,620\na fairly stiff job.\n\n362\n00:26:40,620 --> 00:26:46,380\nIt was not the safety of his own skin that\ntroubled him, but the success of the scheme\n\n363\n00:26:46,380 --> 00:26:52,060\nhe had planned.\nThat little man was clean grit all through,\n\n364\n00:26:52,060 --> 00:26:55,280\nwithout a soft spot in him.\n\n365\n00:26:55,280 --> 00:27:01,650\nOne night he was very solemn.\n'Say, Hannay,' he said, 'I judge I should\n\n366\n00:27:01,650 --> 00:27:06,260\nlet you a bit deeper into this business.\nI should hate to go out without leaving\n\n367\n00:27:06,260 --> 00:27:09,720\nsomebody else to put up a fight.'\n\n368\n00:27:09,720 --> 00:27:14,780\nAnd he began to tell me in detail what I\nhad only heard from him vaguely.\n\n369\n00:27:14,780 --> 00:27:19,750\nI did not give him very close attention.\nThe fact is, I was more interested in his\n\n370\n00:27:19,750 --> 00:27:23,150\nown adventures than in his high politics.\n\n371\n00:27:23,150 --> 00:27:29,140\nI reckoned that Karolides and his affairs\nwere not my business, leaving all that to\n\n372\n00:27:29,140 --> 00:27:33,020\nhim.\nSo a lot that he said slipped clean out of\n\n373\n00:27:33,020 --> 00:27:35,059\nmy memory.\n\n374\n00:27:35,059 --> 00:27:39,720\nI remember that he was very clear that the\ndanger to Karolides would not begin till he\n\n375\n00:27:39,720 --> 00:27:44,420\nhad got to London, and would come from the\nvery highest quarters, where there would be\n\n376\n00:27:44,420 --> 00:27:47,840\nno thought of suspicion.\n\n377\n00:27:47,840 --> 00:27:52,900\nHe mentioned the name of a woman--Julia\nCzechenyi--as having something to do with\n\n378\n00:27:52,900 --> 00:27:56,800\nthe danger.\nShe would be the decoy, I gathered, to get\n\n379\n00:27:56,800 --> 00:28:00,450\nKarolides out of the care of his guards.\n\n380\n00:28:00,450 --> 00:28:06,200\nHe talked, too, about a Black Stone and a\nman that lisped in his speech, and he\n\n381\n00:28:06,200 --> 00:28:12,420\ndescribed very particularly somebody that\nhe never referred to without a shudder--an\n\n382\n00:28:12,420 --> 00:28:18,160\nold man with a young voice who could hood\nhis eyes like a hawk.\n\n383\n00:28:18,160 --> 00:28:21,300\nHe spoke a good deal about death, too.\n\n384\n00:28:21,050 --> 00:28:25,990\nHe was mortally anxious about winning\nthrough with his job, but he didn't care a\n\n385\n00:28:25,990 --> 00:28:28,030\nrush for his life.\n\n386\n00:28:27,780 --> 00:28:33,650\n'I reckon it's like going to sleep when you\nare pretty well tired out, and waking to\n\n387\n00:28:33,650 --> 00:28:39,049\nfind a summer day with the scent of hay\ncoming in at the window.\n\n388\n00:28:39,050 --> 00:28:45,580\nI used to thank God for such mornings way\nback in the Blue-Grass country, and I guess\n\n389\n00:28:45,580 --> 00:28:48,880\nI'll thank Him when I wake up on the other\nside of Jordan.'\n\n390\n00:28:50,750 --> 00:28:55,390\nNext day he was much more cheerful, and\nread the life of Stonewall Jackson much of\n\n391\n00:28:55,390 --> 00:28:57,330\nthe time.\n\n392\n00:28:57,080 --> 00:29:02,370\nI went out to dinner with a mining engineer\nI had got to see on business, and came back\n\n393\n00:29:02,370 --> 00:29:06,390\nabout half-past ten in time for our game of\nchess before turning in.\n\n394\n00:29:07,430 --> 00:29:13,510\nI had a cigar in my mouth, I remember, as I\npushed open the smoking-room door.\n\n395\n00:29:13,510 --> 00:29:17,240\nThe lights were not lit, which struck me as\nodd.\n\n396\n00:29:17,240 --> 00:29:20,330\nI wondered if Scudder had turned in\nalready.\n\n397\n00:29:20,330 --> 00:29:24,220\nI snapped the switch, but there was nobody\nthere.\n\n398\n00:29:24,220 --> 00:29:30,800\nThen I saw something in the far corner\nwhich made me drop my cigar and fall into a\n\n399\n00:29:30,800 --> 00:29:37,059\ncold sweat.\nMy guest was lying sprawled on his back.\n\n400\n00:29:37,059 --> 00:29:45,429\nThere was a long knife through his heart\nwhich skewered him to the floor.\n\n","markerStore":{"nextMarkerId":75,"markersById":{"0":{"range":{"start":{"row":32,"column":23},"end":{"row":32,"column":36}},"properties":{"type":"selection","editorId":12,"goalScreenRange":null,"autoscroll":false,"preserveFolds":true},"reversed":false,"tailed":true,"valid":true,"invalidate":"never","maintainHistory":true}},"version":2},"history":{"version":3,"nextCheckpointId":7,"undoStack":[],"redoStack":[]},"encoding":"utf8","filePath":"/Users/joegesualdo/code/node/vocabulary-context/videos-srt/TheThirty-NineStepsbyJohnBuchan-Chapter01-TheManWhoDied-IkZqLBSKCqQ.en.srt","digestWhenLastPersisted":"67fa9d7621174003d0e78bc7220943cde3010de3","preferredLineEnding":null,"deserializer":"TextBuffer","version":2},{"text":"1\n00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,480\nCHAPTER ONE\nThe Man Who Died\n\n2\n00:00:09,200 --> 00:00:14,089\nI returned from the City about three\no'clock on that May afternoon pretty well\n\n3\n00:00:14,089 --> 00:00:18,769\ndisgusted with life.\nI had been three months in the Old Country,\n\n4\n00:00:18,769 --> 00:00:21,180\nand was fed up with it.\n\n5\n00:00:21,180 --> 00:00:25,699\nIf anyone had told me a year ago that I\nwould have been feeling like that I should\n\n6\n00:00:25,699 --> 00:00:29,380\nhave laughed at him; but there was the\nfact.\n\n7\n00:00:29,380 --> 00:00:36,050\nThe weather made me liverish, the talk of\nthe ordinary Englishman made me sick, I\n\n8\n00:00:36,050 --> 00:00:40,850\ncouldn't get enough exercise, and the\namusements of London seemed as flat as\n\n9\n00:00:40,850 --> 00:00:44,960\nsoda-water that has been standing in the\nsun.\n\n10\n00:00:44,960 --> 00:00:50,640\n'Richard Hannay,' I kept telling myself,\n'you have got into the wrong ditch, my\n\n11\n00:00:50,640 --> 00:00:54,170\nfriend, and you had better climb out.'\n\n12\n00:00:54,170 --> 00:00:59,019\nIt made me bite my lips to think of the\nplans I had been building up those last\n\n13\n00:00:59,019 --> 00:01:01,640\nyears in Bulawayo.\n\n14\n00:01:01,390 --> 00:01:06,940\nI had got my pile--not one of the big ones,\nbut good enough for me; and I had figured\n\n15\n00:01:06,940 --> 00:01:12,230\nout all kinds of ways of enjoying myself.\n\n16\n00:01:11,980 --> 00:01:16,620\nMy father had brought me out from Scotland\nat the age of six, and I had never been\n\n17\n00:01:16,620 --> 00:01:22,450\nhome since; so England was a sort of\nArabian Nights to me, and I counted on\n\n18\n00:01:22,450 --> 00:01:25,630\nstopping there for the rest of my days.\n\n19\n00:01:25,630 --> 00:01:29,210\nBut from the first I was disappointed with\nit.\n\n20\n00:01:29,210 --> 00:01:34,630\nIn about a week I was tired of seeing\nsights, and in less than a month I had had\n\n21\n00:01:34,630 --> 00:01:37,520\nenough of restaurants and theatres and\nrace-meetings.\n\n22\n00:01:39,020 --> 00:01:44,130\nI had no real pal to go about with, which\nprobably explains things.\n\n23\n00:01:44,130 --> 00:01:47,750\nPlenty of people invited me to their\nhouses, but they didn't seem much\n\n24\n00:01:47,750 --> 00:01:50,350\ninterested in me.\n\n25\n00:01:50,350 --> 00:01:55,040\nThey would fling me a question or two about\nSouth Africa, and then get on their own\n\n26\n00:01:55,040 --> 00:01:56,720\naffairs.\n\n27\n00:01:56,470 --> 00:02:02,200\nA lot of Imperialist ladies asked me to tea\nto meet schoolmasters from New Zealand and\n\n28\n00:02:02,200 --> 00:02:07,649\neditors from Vancouver, and that was the\ndismalest business of all.\n\n29\n00:02:07,649 --> 00:02:14,840\nHere was I, thirty-seven years old, sound\nin wind and limb, with enough money to have\n\n30\n00:02:14,840 --> 00:02:19,099\na good time, yawning my head off all day.\n\n31\n00:02:18,840 --> 00:02:24,400\nI had just about settled to clear out and\nget back to the veld, for I was the best\n\n32\n00:02:24,400 --> 00:02:27,190\nbored man in the United Kingdom.\n\n33\n00:02:26,940 --> 00:02:31,920\nThat afternoon I had been worrying my\nbrokers about investments to give my mind\n\n34\n00:02:31,920 --> 00:02:38,250\nsomething to work on, and on my way home I\nturned into my club--rather a pot-house,\n\n35\n00:02:38,250 --> 00:02:41,330\nwhich took in Colonial members.\n\n36\n00:02:41,330 --> 00:02:44,910\nI had a long drink, and read the evening\npapers.\n\n37\n00:02:44,910 --> 00:02:50,210\nThey were full of the row in the Near East,\nand there was an article about Karolides,\n\n38\n00:02:50,210 --> 00:02:52,140\nthe Greek Premier.\n\n39\n00:02:52,140 --> 00:02:56,800\nI rather fancied the chap.\nFrom all accounts he seemed the one big man\n\n40\n00:02:56,800 --> 00:03:01,319\nin the show; and he played a straight game\ntoo, which was more than could be said for\n\n41\n00:03:01,319 --> 00:03:03,140\nmost of them.\n\n42\n00:03:03,140 --> 00:03:08,180\nI gathered that they hated him pretty\nblackly in Berlin and Vienna, but that we\n\n43\n00:03:08,180 --> 00:03:13,020\nwere going to stick by him, and one paper\nsaid that he was the only barrier between\n\n44\n00:03:13,020 --> 00:03:15,760\nEurope and Armageddon.\n\n45\n00:03:15,760 --> 00:03:20,590\nI remember wondering if I could get a job\nin those parts.\n\n46\n00:03:20,590 --> 00:03:26,440\nIt struck me that Albania was the sort of\nplace that might keep a man from yawning.\n\n47\n00:03:26,440 --> 00:03:32,340\nAbout six o'clock I went home, dressed,\ndined at the Cafe Royal, and turned into a\n\n48\n00:03:32,340 --> 00:03:37,090\nmusic-hall.\nIt was a silly show, all capering women and\n\n49\n00:03:37,090 --> 00:03:41,170\nmonkey-faced men, and I did not stay long.\n\n50\n00:03:41,170 --> 00:03:46,110\nThe night was fine and clear as I walked\nback to the flat I had hired near Portland\n\n51\n00:03:46,110 --> 00:03:47,660\nPlace.\n\n52\n00:03:47,410 --> 00:03:53,180\nThe crowd surged past me on the pavements,\nbusy and chattering, and I envied the\n\n53\n00:03:53,180 --> 00:03:56,709\npeople for having something to do.\n\n54\n00:03:56,459 --> 00:04:02,209\nThese shop-girls and clerks and dandies and\npolicemen had some interest in life that\n\n55\n00:04:02,209 --> 00:04:06,310\nkept them going.\nI gave half-a-crown to a beggar because I\n\n56\n00:04:06,310 --> 00:04:09,730\nsaw him yawn; he was a fellow-sufferer.\n\n57\n00:04:09,730 --> 00:04:16,039\nAt Oxford Circus I looked up into the\nspring sky and I made a vow.\n\n58\n00:04:16,039 --> 00:04:21,820\nI would give the Old Country another day to\nfit me into something; if nothing happened,\n\n59\n00:04:21,820 --> 00:04:26,490\nI would take the next boat for the Cape.\n\n60\n00:04:26,490 --> 00:04:31,080\nMy flat was the first floor in a new block\nbehind Langham Place.\n\n61\n00:04:31,080 --> 00:04:35,730\nThere was a common staircase, with a porter\nand a liftman at the entrance, but there\n\n62\n00:04:35,730 --> 00:04:40,980\nwas no restaurant or anything of that sort,\nand each flat was quite shut off from the\n\n63\n00:04:40,980 --> 00:04:41,230\nothers.\n\n64\n00:04:40,980 --> 00:04:47,160\nI hate servants on the premises, so I had a\nfellow to look after me who came in by the\n\n65\n00:04:47,160 --> 00:04:48,810\nday.\n\n66\n00:04:48,560 --> 00:04:53,350\nHe arrived before eight o'clock every\nmorning and used to depart at seven, for I\n\n67\n00:04:53,350 --> 00:04:57,730\nnever dined at home.\nI was just fitting my key into the door\n\n68\n00:04:57,730 --> 00:05:00,590\nwhen I noticed a man at my elbow.\n\n69\n00:05:00,590 --> 00:05:05,660\nI had not seen him approach, and the sudden\nappearance made me start.\n\n70\n00:05:05,660 --> 00:05:11,840\nHe was a slim man, with a short brown beard\nand small, gimlety blue eyes.\n\n71\n00:05:11,840 --> 00:05:16,590\nI recognized him as the occupant of a flat\non the top floor, with whom I had passed\n\n72\n00:05:16,590 --> 00:05:22,150\nthe time of day on the stairs.\n'Can I speak to you?' he said.\n\n73\n00:05:22,150 --> 00:05:25,190\n'May I come in for a minute?'\n\n74\n00:05:25,190 --> 00:05:30,230\nHe was steadying his voice with an effort,\nand his hand was pawing my arm.\n\n75\n00:05:30,230 --> 00:05:32,460\nI got my door open and motioned him in.\n\n76\n00:05:33,040 --> 00:05:37,240\nNo sooner was he over the threshold than he\nmade a dash for my back room, where I used\n\n77\n00:05:37,240 --> 00:05:41,250\nto smoke and write my letters.\nThen he bolted back.\n\n78\n00:05:41,250 --> 00:05:47,150\n'Is the door locked?' he asked feverishly,\nand he fastened the chain with his own\n\n79\n00:05:47,150 --> 00:05:51,810\nhand.\n'I'm very sorry,' he said humbly.\n\n80\n00:05:51,810 --> 00:05:56,510\n'It's a mighty liberty, but you looked the\nkind of man who would understand.\n\n81\n00:05:56,510 --> 00:06:00,820\nI've had you in my mind all this week when\nthings got troublesome.\n\n82\n00:06:00,820 --> 00:06:04,610\nSay, will you do me a good turn?'\n\n83\n00:06:04,610 --> 00:06:09,240\n'I'll listen to you,' I said.\n'That's all I'll promise.'\n\n84\n00:06:09,240 --> 00:06:12,880\nI was getting worried by the antics of this\nnervous little chap.\n\n85\n00:06:12,880 --> 00:06:18,240\nThere was a tray of drinks on a table\nbeside him, from which he filled himself a\n\n86\n00:06:18,240 --> 00:06:23,180\nstiff whisky-and-soda.\nHe drank it off in three gulps, and cracked\n\n87\n00:06:23,180 --> 00:06:25,449\nthe glass as he set it down.\n\n88\n00:06:25,449 --> 00:06:29,940\n'Pardon,' he said, 'I'm a bit rattled\ntonight.\n\n89\n00:06:29,940 --> 00:06:34,710\nYou see, I happen at this moment to be\ndead.'\n\n90\n00:06:34,710 --> 00:06:37,370\nI sat down in an armchair and lit my pipe.\n\n91\n00:06:37,370 --> 00:06:41,449\n'What does it feel like?'\nI asked.\n\n92\n00:06:41,449 --> 00:06:45,500\nI was pretty certain that I had to deal\nwith a madman.\n\n93\n00:06:45,500 --> 00:06:48,240\nA smile flickered over his drawn face.\n\n94\n00:06:48,240 --> 00:06:54,199\n'I'm not mad--yet.\nSay, Sir, I've been watching you, and I\n\n95\n00:06:54,199 --> 00:06:58,759\nreckon you're a cool customer.\nI reckon, too, you're an honest man, and\n\n96\n00:06:58,759 --> 00:07:02,300\nnot afraid of playing a bold hand.\n\n97\n00:07:02,300 --> 00:07:07,620\nI'm going to confide in you.\nI need help worse than any man ever needed\n\n98\n00:07:07,620 --> 00:07:11,599\nit, and I want to know if I can count you\nin.'\n\n99\n00:07:11,600 --> 00:07:17,500\n'Get on with your yarn,' I said, 'and I'll\ntell you.'\n\n100\n00:07:17,500 --> 00:07:22,440\nHe seemed to brace himself for a great\neffort, and then started on the queerest\n\n101\n00:07:22,440 --> 00:07:24,180\nrigmarole.\n\n102\n00:07:24,180 --> 00:07:28,889\nI didn't get hold of it at first, and I had\nto stop and ask him questions.\n\n103\n00:07:28,889 --> 00:07:31,699\nBut here is the gist of it:\n\n104\n00:07:31,449 --> 00:07:36,770\nHe was an American, from Kentucky, and\nafter college, being pretty well off, he\n\n105\n00:07:36,770 --> 00:07:39,400\nhad started out to see the world.\n\n106\n00:07:39,150 --> 00:07:44,040\nHe wrote a bit, and acted as war\ncorrespondent for a Chicago paper, and\n\n107\n00:07:44,040 --> 00:07:47,490\nspent a year or two in South-Eastern\nEurope.\n\n108\n00:07:47,490 --> 00:07:52,880\nI gathered that he was a fine linguist, and\nhad got to know pretty well the society in\n\n109\n00:07:52,880 --> 00:07:58,020\nthose parts.\nHe spoke familiarly of many names that I\n\n110\n00:07:58,020 --> 00:08:00,690\nremembered to have seen in the newspapers.\n\n111\n00:08:00,690 --> 00:08:06,699\nHe had played about with politics, he told\nme, at first for the interest of them, and\n\n112\n00:08:06,699 --> 00:08:10,190\nthen because he couldn't help himself.\n\n113\n00:08:09,940 --> 00:08:15,080\nI read him as a sharp, restless fellow, who\nalways wanted to get down to the roots of\n\n114\n00:08:15,080 --> 00:08:18,639\nthings.\nHe got a little further down than he\n\n115\n00:08:18,639 --> 00:08:21,100\nwanted.\n\n116\n00:08:21,100 --> 00:08:25,419\nI am giving you what he told me as well as\nI could make it out.\n\n117\n00:08:25,419 --> 00:08:29,270\nAway behind all the Governments and the\narmies there was a big subterranean\n\n118\n00:08:29,270 --> 00:08:34,640\nmovement going on, engineered by very\ndangerous people.\n\n119\n00:08:34,639 --> 00:08:40,119\nHe had come on it by accident; it\nfascinated him; he went further, and then\n\n120\n00:08:40,119 --> 00:08:42,439\nhe got caught.\n\n121\n00:08:42,189 --> 00:08:46,999\nI gathered that most of the people in it\nwere the sort of educated anarchists that\n\n122\n00:08:46,999 --> 00:08:52,160\nmake revolutions, but that beside them\nthere were financiers who were playing for\n\n123\n00:08:52,160 --> 00:08:52,920\nmoney.\n\n124\n00:08:52,920 --> 00:08:58,679\nA clever man can make big profits on a\nfalling market, and it suited the book of\n\n125\n00:08:58,679 --> 00:09:02,970\nboth classes to set Europe by the ears.\n\n126\n00:09:02,720 --> 00:09:08,209\nHe told me some queer things that explained\na lot that had puzzled me--things that\n\n127\n00:09:08,209 --> 00:09:14,459\nhappened in the Balkan War, how one state\nsuddenly came out on top, why alliances\n\n128\n00:09:14,459 --> 00:09:17,550\nwere made and broken, why certain men\n\n129\n00:09:17,550 --> 00:09:22,790\ndisappeared, and where the sinews of war\ncame from.\n\n130\n00:09:22,790 --> 00:09:26,749\nThe aim of the whole conspiracy was to get\nRussia and Germany at loggerheads.\n\n131\n00:09:26,749 --> 00:09:32,800\nWhen I asked why, he said that the\nanarchist lot thought it would give them\n\n132\n00:09:32,800 --> 00:09:37,629\ntheir chance.\nEverything would be in the melting-pot, and\n\n133\n00:09:37,629 --> 00:09:40,670\nthey looked to see a new world emerge.\n\n134\n00:09:40,670 --> 00:09:46,050\nThe capitalists would rake in the shekels,\nand make fortunes by buying up wreckage.\n\n135\n00:09:46,050 --> 00:09:51,189\nCapital, he said, had no conscience and no\nfatherland.\n\n136\n00:09:51,189 --> 00:09:57,519\nBesides, the Jew was behind it, and the Jew\nhated Russia worse than hell.\n\n137\n00:09:57,519 --> 00:10:00,819\n'Do you wonder?' he cried.\n\n138\n00:10:00,569 --> 00:10:05,779\n'For three hundred years they have been\npersecuted, and this is the return match\n\n139\n00:10:05,779 --> 00:10:10,709\nfor the pogroms.\nThe Jew is everywhere, but you have to go\n\n140\n00:10:10,709 --> 00:10:14,619\nfar down the backstairs to find him.\n\n141\n00:10:14,619 --> 00:10:21,230\nTake any big Teutonic business concern.\nIf you have dealings with it the first man\n\n142\n00:10:21,230 --> 00:10:28,329\nyou meet is Prince von und Zu Something, an\nelegant young man who talks Eton-and-Harrow\n\n143\n00:10:28,329 --> 00:10:28,989\nEnglish.\n\n144\n00:10:28,989 --> 00:10:35,759\nBut he cuts no ice.\nIf your business is big, you get behind him\n\n145\n00:10:35,759 --> 00:10:43,560\nand find a prognathous Westphalian with a\nretreating brow and the manners of a hog.\n\n146\n00:10:43,559 --> 00:10:48,389\nHe is the German business man that gives\nyour English papers the shakes.\n\n147\n00:10:48,389 --> 00:10:54,029\nBut if you're on the biggest kind of job\nand are bound to get to the real boss, ten\n\n148\n00:10:54,029 --> 00:11:00,850\nto one you are brought up against a little\nwhite-faced Jew in a bath-chair with an eye\n\n149\n00:11:00,850 --> 00:11:02,110\nlike a rattlesnake.\n\n150\n00:11:02,110 --> 00:11:08,110\nYes, Sir, he is the man who is ruling the\nworld just now, and he has his knife in the\n\n151\n00:11:08,110 --> 00:11:15,579\nEmpire of the Tzar, because his aunt was\noutraged and his father flogged in some\n\n152\n00:11:15,579 --> 00:11:19,639\none-horse location on the Volga.'\n\n153\n00:11:19,639 --> 00:11:25,110\nI could not help saying that his Jew-\nanarchists seemed to have got left behind a\n\n154\n00:11:25,110 --> 00:11:28,500\nlittle.\n'Yes and no,' he said.\n\n155\n00:11:28,499 --> 00:11:33,839\n'They won up to a point, but they struck a\nbigger thing than money, a thing that\n\n156\n00:11:33,839 --> 00:11:40,109\ncouldn't be bought, the old elemental\nfighting instincts of man.\n\n157\n00:11:40,110 --> 00:11:45,249\nIf you're going to be killed you invent\nsome kind of flag and country to fight for,\n\n158\n00:11:45,249 --> 00:11:49,000\nand if you survive you get to love the\nthing.\n\n159\n00:11:48,999 --> 00:11:55,559\nThose foolish devils of soldiers have found\nsomething they care for, and that has upset\n\n160\n00:11:55,559 --> 00:12:02,299\nthe pretty plan laid in Berlin and Vienna.\nBut my friends haven't played their last\n\n161\n00:12:02,299 --> 00:12:05,279\ncard by a long sight.\n\n162\n00:12:05,279 --> 00:12:10,439\nThey've gotten the ace up their sleeves,\nand unless I can keep alive for a month\n\n163\n00:12:10,439 --> 00:12:16,949\nthey are going to play it and win.'\n'But I thought you were dead,' I put in.\n\n164\n00:12:16,949 --> 00:12:21,569\n'MORS JANUA VITAE,' he smiled.\n\n165\n00:12:21,569 --> 00:12:26,679\n(I recognized the quotation: it was about\nall the Latin I knew.)\n\n166\n00:12:26,679 --> 00:12:32,860\n'I'm coming to that, but I've got to put\nyou wise about a lot of things first.\n\n167\n00:12:32,860 --> 00:12:38,850\nIf you read your newspaper, I guess you\nknow the name of Constantine Karolides?'\n\n168\n00:12:38,850 --> 00:12:43,749\nI sat up at that, for I had been reading\nabout him that very afternoon.\n\n169\n00:12:43,749 --> 00:12:47,779\n'He is the man that has wrecked all their\ngames.\n\n170\n00:12:47,779 --> 00:12:54,569\nHe is the one big brain in the whole show,\nand he happens also to be an honest man.\n\n171\n00:12:54,569 --> 00:12:58,769\nTherefore he has been marked down these\ntwelve months past.\n\n172\n00:12:58,769 --> 00:13:03,369\nI found that out--not that it was\ndifficult, for any fool could guess as\n\n173\n00:13:03,369 --> 00:13:03,819\nmuch.\n\n174\n00:13:03,819 --> 00:13:11,160\nBut I found out the way they were going to\nget him, and that knowledge was deadly.\n\n175\n00:13:11,160 --> 00:13:15,089\nThat's why I have had to decease.'\n\n176\n00:13:14,839 --> 00:13:19,610\nHe had another drink, and I mixed it for\nhim myself, for I was getting interested in\n\n177\n00:13:19,610 --> 00:13:21,149\nthe beggar.\n\n178\n00:13:20,899 --> 00:13:27,429\n'They can't get him in his own land, for he\nhas a bodyguard of Epirotes that would skin\n\n179\n00:13:27,429 --> 00:13:32,269\ntheir grandmothers.\nBut on the 15th day of June he is coming to\n\n180\n00:13:32,269 --> 00:13:34,379\nthis city.\n\n181\n00:13:34,379 --> 00:13:39,619\nThe British Foreign Office has taken to\nhaving International tea-parties, and the\n\n182\n00:13:39,619 --> 00:13:42,179\nbiggest of them is due on that date.\n\n183\n00:13:41,929 --> 00:13:47,329\nNow Karolides is reckoned the principal\nguest, and if my friends have their way he\n\n184\n00:13:47,329 --> 00:13:50,239\nwill never return to his admiring\ncountrymen.'\n\n185\n00:13:50,239 --> 00:13:54,329\n'That's simple enough, anyhow,' I said.\n\n186\n00:13:54,329 --> 00:14:01,449\n'You can warn him and keep him at home.'\n'And play their game?' he asked sharply.\n\n187\n00:14:01,449 --> 00:14:06,470\n'If he does not come they win, for he's the\nonly man that can straighten out the\n\n188\n00:14:06,470 --> 00:14:07,689\ntangle.\n\n189\n00:14:07,689 --> 00:14:12,459\nAnd if his Government are warned he won't\ncome, for he does not know how big the\n\n190\n00:14:12,459 --> 00:14:18,739\nstakes will be on June the 15th.'\n'What about the British Government?'\n\n191\n00:14:18,739 --> 00:14:19,600\nI said.\n\n192\n00:14:19,600 --> 00:14:22,730\n'They're not going to let their guests be\nmurdered.\n\n193\n00:14:22,730 --> 00:14:25,689\nTip them the wink, and they'll take extra\nprecautions.'\n\n194\n00:14:25,689 --> 00:14:27,869\n'No good.\n\n195\n00:14:27,869 --> 00:14:33,199\nThey might stuff your city with plain-\nclothes detectives and double the police\n\n196\n00:14:33,199 --> 00:14:37,049\nand Constantine would still be a doomed\nman.\n\n197\n00:14:37,049 --> 00:14:40,249\nMy friends are not playing this game for\ncandy.\n\n198\n00:14:40,249 --> 00:14:45,100\nThey want a big occasion for the taking\noff, with the eyes of all Europe on it.\n\n199\n00:14:45,100 --> 00:14:49,429\nHe'll be murdered by an Austrian, and\nthere'll be plenty of evidence to show the\n\n200\n00:14:49,429 --> 00:14:53,369\nconnivance of the big folk in Vienna and\nBerlin.\n\n201\n00:14:53,369 --> 00:14:58,769\nIt will all be an infernal lie, of course,\nbut the case will look black enough to the\n\n202\n00:14:58,769 --> 00:15:02,139\nworld.\nI'm not talking hot air, my friend.\n\n203\n00:15:02,139 --> 00:15:08,519\nI happen to know every detail of the\nhellish contrivance, and I can tell you it\n\n204\n00:15:08,519 --> 00:15:13,709\nwill be the most finished piece of\nblackguardism since the Borgias.\n\n205\n00:15:13,709 --> 00:15:17,949\nBut it's not going to come off if there's a\ncertain man who knows the wheels of the\n\n206\n00:15:17,949 --> 00:15:23,350\nbusiness alive right here in London on the\n15th day of June.\n\n207\n00:15:23,350 --> 00:15:29,549\nAnd that man is going to be your servant,\nFranklin P. Scudder.'\n\n208\n00:15:29,549 --> 00:15:35,169\nI was getting to like the little chap.\nHis jaw had shut like a rat-trap, and there\n\n209\n00:15:35,169 --> 00:15:38,569\nwas the fire of battle in his gimlety eyes.\n\n210\n00:15:38,569 --> 00:15:42,059\nIf he was spinning me a yarn he could act\nup to it.\n\n211\n00:15:42,059 --> 00:15:46,220\n'Where did you find out this story?'\nI asked.\n\n212\n00:15:46,220 --> 00:15:51,709\n'I got the first hint in an inn on the\nAchensee in Tyrol.\n\n213\n00:15:51,709 --> 00:15:57,049\nThat set me inquiring, and I collected my\nother clues in a fur-shop in the Galician\n\n214\n00:15:57,049 --> 00:16:03,449\nquarter of Buda, in a Strangers' Club in\nVienna, and in a little bookshop off the\n\n215\n00:16:03,449 --> 00:16:06,439\nRacknitzstrasse in Leipsic.\n\n216\n00:16:06,439 --> 00:16:10,449\nI completed my evidence ten days ago in\nParis.\n\n217\n00:16:10,449 --> 00:16:14,230\nI can't tell you the details now, for it's\nsomething of a history.\n\n218\n00:16:14,230 --> 00:16:19,739\nWhen I was quite sure in my own mind I\njudged it my business to disappear, and I\n\n219\n00:16:19,739 --> 00:16:23,740\nreached this city by a mighty queer\ncircuit.\n\n220\n00:16:23,739 --> 00:16:29,199\nI left Paris a dandified young French-\nAmerican, and I sailed from Hamburg a Jew\n\n221\n00:16:29,199 --> 00:16:31,469\ndiamond merchant.\n\n222\n00:16:31,220 --> 00:16:36,869\nIn Norway I was an English student of Ibsen\ncollecting materials for lectures, but when\n\n223\n00:16:36,869 --> 00:16:41,929\nI left Bergen I was a cinema-man with\nspecial ski films.\n\n224\n00:16:41,929 --> 00:16:46,579\nAnd I came here from Leith with a lot of\npulp-wood propositions in my pocket to put\n\n225\n00:16:46,579 --> 00:16:51,290\nbefore the London newspapers.\nTill yesterday I thought I had muddied my\n\n226\n00:16:51,290 --> 00:16:55,419\ntrail some, and was feeling pretty happy.\n\n227\n00:16:55,419 --> 00:16:59,129\nThen ...'\nThe recollection seemed to upset him, and\n\n228\n00:16:59,129 --> 00:17:04,940\nhe gulped down some more whisky.\n'Then I saw a man standing in the street\n\n229\n00:17:04,940 --> 00:17:06,520\noutside this block.\n\n230\n00:17:06,520 --> 00:17:11,770\nI used to stay close in my room all day,\nand only slip out after dark for an hour or\n\n231\n00:17:11,770 --> 00:17:15,520\ntwo.\nI watched him for a bit from my window, and\n\n232\n00:17:15,520 --> 00:17:17,800\nI thought I recognized him ...\n\n233\n00:17:17,800 --> 00:17:23,820\nHe came in and spoke to the porter ...\nWhen I came back from my walk last night I\n\n234\n00:17:23,820 --> 00:17:29,300\nfound a card in my letter-box.\nIt bore the name of the man I want least to\n\n235\n00:17:29,300 --> 00:17:32,370\nmeet on God's earth.'\n\n236\n00:17:32,370 --> 00:17:39,050\nI think that the look in my companion's\neyes, the sheer naked scare on his face,\n\n237\n00:17:39,050 --> 00:17:44,920\ncompleted my conviction of his honesty.\nMy own voice sharpened a bit as I asked him\n\n238\n00:17:44,920 --> 00:17:46,810\nwhat he did next.\n\n239\n00:17:46,810 --> 00:17:52,870\n'I realized that I was bottled as sure as a\npickled herring, and that there was only\n\n240\n00:17:52,870 --> 00:17:56,730\none way out.\nI had to die.\n\n241\n00:17:56,730 --> 00:18:01,510\nIf my pursuers knew I was dead they would\ngo to sleep again.'\n\n242\n00:18:01,510 --> 00:18:03,460\n'How did you manage it?'\n\n243\n00:18:03,210 --> 00:18:09,850\n'I told the man that valets me that I was\nfeeling pretty bad, and I got myself up to\n\n244\n00:18:09,850 --> 00:18:15,290\nlook like death.\nThat wasn't difficult, for I'm no slouch at\n\n245\n00:18:15,290 --> 00:18:16,190\ndisguises.\n\n246\n00:18:16,190 --> 00:18:21,240\nThen I got a corpse--you can always get a\nbody in London if you know where to go for\n\n247\n00:18:21,240 --> 00:18:22,420\nit.\n\n248\n00:18:22,170 --> 00:18:26,830\nI fetched it back in a trunk on the top of\na four-wheeler, and I had to be assisted\n\n249\n00:18:26,830 --> 00:18:31,130\nupstairs to my room.\nYou see I had to pile up some evidence for\n\n250\n00:18:31,130 --> 00:18:33,040\nthe inquest.\n\n251\n00:18:33,040 --> 00:18:38,080\nI went to bed and got my man to mix me a\nsleeping-draught, and then told him to\n\n252\n00:18:38,080 --> 00:18:42,110\nclear out.\nHe wanted to fetch a doctor, but I swore\n\n253\n00:18:42,110 --> 00:18:46,130\nsome and said I couldn't abide leeches.\n\n254\n00:18:46,130 --> 00:18:50,320\nWhen I was left alone I started in to fake\nup that corpse.\n\n255\n00:18:50,320 --> 00:18:55,690\nHe was my size, and I judged had perished\nfrom too much alcohol, so I put some\n\n256\n00:18:55,690 --> 00:18:58,660\nspirits handy about the place.\n\n257\n00:18:58,660 --> 00:19:04,030\nThe jaw was the weak point in the likeness,\nso I blew it away with a revolver.\n\n258\n00:19:04,030 --> 00:19:09,500\nI daresay there will be somebody tomorrow\nto swear to having heard a shot, but there\n\n259\n00:19:09,500 --> 00:19:14,250\nare no neighbours on my floor, and I\nguessed I could risk it.\n\n260\n00:19:14,250 --> 00:19:19,880\nSo I left the body in bed dressed up in my\npyjamas, with a revolver lying on the bed-\n\n261\n00:19:19,880 --> 00:19:25,850\nclothes and a considerable mess around.\nThen I got into a suit of clothes I had\n\n262\n00:19:25,850 --> 00:19:28,130\nkept waiting for emergencies.\n\n263\n00:19:28,130 --> 00:19:33,900\nI didn't dare to shave for fear of leaving\ntracks, and besides, it wasn't any kind of\n\n264\n00:19:33,900 --> 00:19:37,130\nuse my trying to get into the streets.\n\n265\n00:19:36,880 --> 00:19:41,790\nI had had you in my mind all day, and there\nseemed nothing to do but to make an appeal\n\n266\n00:19:41,790 --> 00:19:43,669\nto you.\n\n267\n00:19:43,420 --> 00:19:47,870\nI watched from my window till I saw you\ncome home, and then slipped down the stair\n\n268\n00:19:47,870 --> 00:19:51,970\nto meet you ...\nThere, Sir, I guess you know about as much\n\n269\n00:19:51,970 --> 00:19:55,540\nas me of this business.'\n\n270\n00:19:55,540 --> 00:20:02,150\nHe sat blinking like an owl, fluttering\nwith nerves and yet desperately determined.\n\n271\n00:20:02,150 --> 00:20:06,309\nBy this time I was pretty well convinced\nthat he was going straight with me.\n\n272\n00:20:06,310 --> 00:20:11,540\nIt was the wildest sort of narrative, but I\nhad heard in my time many steep tales which\n\n273\n00:20:11,540 --> 00:20:17,800\nhad turned out to be true, and I had made a\npractice of judging the man rather than the\n\n274\n00:20:17,800 --> 00:20:18,850\nstory.\n\n275\n00:20:18,850 --> 00:20:23,260\nIf he had wanted to get a location in my\nflat, and then cut my throat, he would have\n\n276\n00:20:23,260 --> 00:20:28,760\npitched a milder yarn.\n'Hand me your key,' I said, 'and I'll take\n\n277\n00:20:28,760 --> 00:20:30,490\na look at the corpse.\n\n278\n00:20:30,490 --> 00:20:35,630\nExcuse my caution, but I'm bound to verify\na bit if I can.'\n\n279\n00:20:35,630 --> 00:20:40,350\nHe shook his head mournfully.\n'I reckoned you'd ask for that, but I\n\n280\n00:20:40,350 --> 00:20:41,140\nhaven't got it.\n\n281\n00:20:41,140 --> 00:20:45,640\nIt's on my chain on the dressing-table.\nI had to leave it behind, for I couldn't\n\n282\n00:20:45,640 --> 00:20:51,410\nleave any clues to breed suspicions.\nThe gentry who are after me are pretty\n\n283\n00:20:51,410 --> 00:20:53,770\nbright-eyed citizens.\n\n284\n00:20:53,770 --> 00:20:58,410\nYou'll have to take me on trust for the\nnight, and tomorrow you'll get proof of the\n\n285\n00:20:58,410 --> 00:21:04,180\ncorpse business right enough.'\nI thought for an instant or two.\n\n286\n00:21:04,180 --> 00:21:05,350\n'Right.\n\n287\n00:21:05,350 --> 00:21:10,090\nI'll trust you for the night.\nI'll lock you into this room and keep the\n\n288\n00:21:10,090 --> 00:21:13,000\nkey.\nJust one word, Mr Scudder.\n\n289\n00:21:13,000 --> 00:21:18,830\nI believe you're straight, but if so be you\nare not I should warn you that I'm a handy\n\n290\n00:21:18,830 --> 00:21:23,750\nman with a gun.'\n'Sure,' he said, jumping up with some\n\n291\n00:21:23,750 --> 00:21:24,590\nbriskness.\n\n292\n00:21:24,590 --> 00:21:30,120\n'I haven't the privilege of your name, Sir,\nbut let me tell you that you're a white\n\n293\n00:21:30,120 --> 00:21:32,760\nman.\nI'll thank you to lend me a razor.'\n\n294\n00:21:32,760 --> 00:21:37,320\nI took him into my bedroom and turned him\nloose.\n\n295\n00:21:37,320 --> 00:21:42,660\nIn half an hour's time a figure came out\nthat I scarcely recognized.\n\n296\n00:21:42,660 --> 00:21:46,540\nOnly his gimlety, hungry eyes were the\nsame.\n\n297\n00:21:46,540 --> 00:21:52,340\nHe was shaved clean, his hair was parted in\nthe middle, and he had cut his eyebrows.\n\n298\n00:21:52,340 --> 00:21:58,560\nFurther, he carried himself as if he had\nbeen drilled, and was the very model, even\n\n299\n00:21:58,560 --> 00:22:05,000\nto the brown complexion, of some British\nofficer who had had a long spell in India.\n\n300\n00:22:05,000 --> 00:22:10,350\nHe had a monocle, too, which he stuck in\nhis eye, and every trace of the American\n\n301\n00:22:10,350 --> 00:22:14,280\nhad gone out of his speech.\n'My hat!\n\n302\n00:22:14,280 --> 00:22:16,750\nMr Scudder--' I stammered.\n\n303\n00:22:16,750 --> 00:22:22,350\n'Not Mr Scudder,' he corrected; 'Captain\nTheophilus Digby, of the 40th Gurkhas,\n\n304\n00:22:22,350 --> 00:22:27,380\npresently home on leave.\nI'll thank you to remember that, Sir.'\n\n305\n00:22:27,390 --> 00:22:32,410\nI made him up a bed in my smoking-room and\nsought my own couch, more cheerful than I\n\n306\n00:22:32,410 --> 00:22:37,120\nhad been for the past month.\nThings did happen occasionally, even in\n\n307\n00:22:37,120 --> 00:22:40,830\nthis God-forgotten metropolis.\n\n308\n00:22:40,830 --> 00:22:45,440\nI woke next morning to hear my man,\nPaddock, making the deuce of a row at the\n\n309\n00:22:45,440 --> 00:22:48,350\nsmoking-room door.\n\n310\n00:22:48,100 --> 00:22:53,970\nPaddock was a fellow I had done a good turn\nto out on the Selakwe, and I had inspanned\n\n311\n00:22:53,970 --> 00:22:58,070\nhim as my servant as soon as I got to\nEngland.\n\n312\n00:22:58,070 --> 00:23:03,990\nHe had about as much gift of the gab as a\nhippopotamus, and was not a great hand at\n\n313\n00:23:03,990 --> 00:23:08,340\nvaleting, but I knew I could count on his\nloyalty.\n\n314\n00:23:08,340 --> 00:23:10,910\n'Stop that row, Paddock,' I said.\n\n315\n00:23:10,910 --> 00:23:16,310\n'There's a friend of mine, Captain--\nCaptain' (I couldn't remember the name)\n\n316\n00:23:16,310 --> 00:23:19,740\n'dossing down in there.\nGet breakfast for two and then come and\n\n317\n00:23:19,740 --> 00:23:21,180\nspeak to me.'\n\n318\n00:23:21,180 --> 00:23:27,210\nI told Paddock a fine story about how my\nfriend was a great swell, with his nerves\n\n319\n00:23:27,210 --> 00:23:33,870\npretty bad from overwork, who wanted\nabsolute rest and stillness.\n\n320\n00:23:33,870 --> 00:23:38,440\nNobody had got to know he was here, or he\nwould be besieged by communications from\n\n321\n00:23:38,440 --> 00:23:42,320\nthe India Office and the Prime Minister and\nhis cure would be ruined.\n\n322\n00:23:42,320 --> 00:23:48,269\nI am bound to say Scudder played up\nsplendidly when he came to breakfast.\n\n323\n00:23:48,270 --> 00:23:53,280\nHe fixed Paddock with his eyeglass, just\nlike a British officer, asked him about the\n\n324\n00:23:53,280 --> 00:24:00,350\nBoer War, and slung out at me a lot of\nstuff about imaginary pals.\n\n325\n00:24:00,350 --> 00:24:05,490\nPaddock couldn't learn to call me 'Sir',\nbut he 'sirred' Scudder as if his life\n\n326\n00:24:05,490 --> 00:24:07,980\ndepended on it.\n\n327\n00:24:07,730 --> 00:24:12,500\nI left him with the newspaper and a box of\ncigars, and went down to the City till\n\n328\n00:24:12,500 --> 00:24:15,970\nluncheon.\nWhen I got back the lift-man had an\n\n329\n00:24:15,970 --> 00:24:17,510\nimportant face.\n\n330\n00:24:17,510 --> 00:24:23,720\n'Nawsty business 'ere this morning, Sir.\nGent in No. 15 been and shot 'isself.\n\n331\n00:24:23,720 --> 00:24:29,680\nThey've just took 'im to the mortiary.\nThe police are up there now.'\n\n332\n00:24:29,680 --> 00:24:35,850\nI ascended to No. 15, and found a couple of\nbobbies and an inspector busy making an\n\n333\n00:24:35,850 --> 00:24:39,080\nexamination.\nI asked a few idiotic questions, and they\n\n334\n00:24:39,080 --> 00:24:41,560\nsoon kicked me out.\n\n335\n00:24:41,560 --> 00:24:46,460\nThen I found the man that had valeted\nScudder, and pumped him, but I could see he\n\n336\n00:24:46,460 --> 00:24:48,890\nsuspected nothing.\n\n337\n00:24:48,640 --> 00:24:54,270\nHe was a whining fellow with a churchyard\nface, and half-a-crown went far to console\n\n338\n00:24:54,270 --> 00:24:57,120\nhim.\nI attended the inquest next day.\n\n339\n00:24:57,120 --> 00:25:02,660\nA partner of some publishing firm gave\nevidence that the deceased had brought him\n\n340\n00:25:02,660 --> 00:25:09,550\nwood-pulp propositions, and had been, he\nbelieved, an agent of an American business.\n\n341\n00:25:09,550 --> 00:25:14,950\nThe jury found it a case of suicide while\nof unsound mind, and the few effects were\n\n342\n00:25:14,950 --> 00:25:18,770\nhanded over to the American Consul to deal\nwith.\n\n343\n00:25:18,770 --> 00:25:24,950\nI gave Scudder a full account of the\naffair, and it interested him greatly.\n\n344\n00:25:24,950 --> 00:25:29,070\nHe said he wished he could have attended\nthe inquest, for he reckoned it would be\n\n345\n00:25:29,070 --> 00:25:33,920\nabout as spicy as to read one's own\nobituary notice.\n\n346\n00:25:33,920 --> 00:25:38,750\nThe first two days he stayed with me in\nthat back room he was very peaceful.\n\n347\n00:25:38,750 --> 00:25:43,750\nHe read and smoked a bit, and made a heap\nof jottings in a note-book, and every night\n\n348\n00:25:43,750 --> 00:25:48,190\nwe had a game of chess, at which he beat me\nhollow.\n\n349\n00:25:48,190 --> 00:25:52,820\nI think he was nursing his nerves back to\nhealth, for he had had a pretty trying\n\n350\n00:25:52,820 --> 00:25:56,090\ntime.\nBut on the third day I could see he was\n\n351\n00:25:56,090 --> 00:25:58,510\nbeginning to get restless.\n\n352\n00:25:58,510 --> 00:26:03,660\nHe fixed up a list of the days till June\n15th, and ticked each off with a red\n\n353\n00:26:03,660 --> 00:26:08,350\npencil, making remarks in shorthand against\nthem.\n\n354\n00:26:08,350 --> 00:26:14,300\nI would find him sunk in a brown study,\nwith his sharp eyes abstracted, and after\n\n355\n00:26:14,300 --> 00:26:20,419\nthose spells of meditation he was apt to be\nvery despondent.\n\n356\n00:26:20,420 --> 00:26:23,800\nThen I could see that he began to get edgy\nagain.\n\n357\n00:26:23,800 --> 00:26:28,100\nHe listened for little noises, and was\nalways asking me if Paddock could be\n\n358\n00:26:28,100 --> 00:26:28,840\ntrusted.\n\n359\n00:26:28,840 --> 00:26:34,000\nOnce or twice he got very peevish, and\napologized for it.\n\n360\n00:26:34,000 --> 00:26:38,190\nI didn't blame him.\nI made every allowance, for he had taken on\n\n361\n00:26:38,190 --> 00:26:40,120\na fairly stiff job.\n\n362\n00:26:40,120 --> 00:26:45,880\nIt was not the safety of his own skin that\ntroubled him, but the success of the scheme\n\n363\n00:26:45,880 --> 00:26:51,560\nhe had planned.\nThat little man was clean grit all through,\n\n364\n00:26:51,560 --> 00:26:54,780\nwithout a soft spot in him.\n\n365\n00:26:54,780 --> 00:27:01,150\nOne night he was very solemn.\n'Say, Hannay,' he said, 'I judge I should\n\n366\n00:27:01,150 --> 00:27:05,760\nlet you a bit deeper into this business.\nI should hate to go out without leaving\n\n367\n00:27:05,760 --> 00:27:09,220\nsomebody else to put up a fight.'\n\n368\n00:27:09,220 --> 00:27:14,280\nAnd he began to tell me in detail what I\nhad only heard from him vaguely.\n\n369\n00:27:14,280 --> 00:27:19,250\nI did not give him very close attention.\nThe fact is, I was more interested in his\n\n370\n00:27:19,250 --> 00:27:22,650\nown adventures than in his high politics.\n\n371\n00:27:22,650 --> 00:27:28,640\nI reckoned that Karolides and his affairs\nwere not my business, leaving all that to\n\n372\n00:27:28,640 --> 00:27:32,520\nhim.\nSo a lot that he said slipped clean out of\n\n373\n00:27:32,520 --> 00:27:34,559\nmy memory.\n\n374\n00:27:34,559 --> 00:27:39,220\nI remember that he was very clear that the\ndanger to Karolides would not begin till he\n\n375\n00:27:39,220 --> 00:27:43,920\nhad got to London, and would come from the\nvery highest quarters, where there would be\n\n376\n00:27:43,920 --> 00:27:47,340\nno thought of suspicion.\n\n377\n00:27:47,340 --> 00:27:52,400\nHe mentioned the name of a woman--Julia\nCzechenyi--as having something to do with\n\n378\n00:27:52,400 --> 00:27:56,300\nthe danger.\nShe would be the decoy, I gathered, to get\n\n379\n00:27:56,300 --> 00:27:59,950\nKarolides out of the care of his guards.\n\n380\n00:27:59,950 --> 00:28:05,700\nHe talked, too, about a Black Stone and a\nman that lisped in his speech, and he\n\n381\n00:28:05,700 --> 00:28:11,920\ndescribed very particularly somebody that\nhe never referred to without a shudder--an\n\n382\n00:28:11,920 --> 00:28:17,660\nold man with a young voice who could hood\nhis eyes like a hawk.\n\n383\n00:28:17,660 --> 00:28:20,800\nHe spoke a good deal about death, too.\n\n384\n00:28:20,550 --> 00:28:25,490\nHe was mortally anxious about winning\nthrough with his job, but he didn't care a\n\n385\n00:28:25,490 --> 00:28:27,530\nrush for his life.\n\n386\n00:28:27,280 --> 00:28:33,150\n'I reckon it's like going to sleep when you\nare pretty well tired out, and waking to\n\n387\n00:28:33,150 --> 00:28:38,549\nfind a summer day with the scent of hay\ncoming in at the window.\n\n388\n00:28:38,550 --> 00:28:45,080\nI used to thank God for such mornings way\nback in the Blue-Grass country, and I guess\n\n389\n00:28:45,080 --> 00:28:48,380\nI'll thank Him when I wake up on the other\nside of Jordan.'\n\n390\n00:28:50,250 --> 00:28:54,890\nNext day he was much more cheerful, and\nread the life of Stonewall Jackson much of\n\n391\n00:28:54,890 --> 00:28:56,830\nthe time.\n\n392\n00:28:56,580 --> 00:29:01,870\nI went out to dinner with a mining engineer\nI had got to see on business, and came back\n\n393\n00:29:01,870 --> 00:29:05,890\nabout half-past ten in time for our game of\nchess before turning in.\n\n394\n00:29:06,930 --> 00:29:13,010\nI had a cigar in my mouth, I remember, as I\npushed open the smoking-room door.\n\n395\n00:29:13,010 --> 00:29:16,740\nThe lights were not lit, which struck me as\nodd.\n\n396\n00:29:16,740 --> 00:29:19,830\nI wondered if Scudder had turned in\nalready.\n\n397\n00:29:19,830 --> 00:29:23,720\nI snapped the switch, but there was nobody\nthere.\n\n398\n00:29:23,720 --> 00:29:30,300\nThen I saw something in the far corner\nwhich made me drop my cigar and fall into a\n\n399\n00:29:30,300 --> 00:29:36,559\ncold sweat.\nMy guest was lying sprawled on his back.\n\n400\n00:29:36,559 --> 00:29:44,929\nThere was a long knife through his heart\nwhich skewered him to the floor.\n\n401\n00:29:45,500 --> 00:29:46,500\n>\n\n402\n00:29:46,500 --> 00:29:56,199\nCHAPTER TWO\nThe Milkman Sets Out on his Travels\n\n403\n00:29:57,290 --> 00:30:01,869\nI sat down in an armchair and felt very\nsick.\n\n404\n00:30:01,869 --> 00:30:08,320\nThat lasted for maybe five minutes, and was\nsucceeded by a fit of the horrors.\n\n405\n00:30:08,320 --> 00:30:14,800\nThe poor staring white face on the floor\nwas more than I could bear, and I managed\n\n406\n00:30:14,800 --> 00:30:20,920\nto get a table-cloth and cover it.\nThen I staggered to a cupboard, found the\n\n407\n00:30:20,920 --> 00:30:24,559\nbrandy and swallowed several mouthfuls.\n\n408\n00:30:24,559 --> 00:30:30,989\nI had seen men die violently before; indeed\nI had killed a few myself in the Matabele\n\n409\n00:30:30,989 --> 00:30:36,690\nWar; but this cold-blooded indoor business\nwas different.\n\n410\n00:30:36,690 --> 00:30:40,039\nStill I managed to pull myself together.\n\n411\n00:30:40,039 --> 00:30:44,039\nI looked at my watch, and saw that it was\nhalf-past ten.\n\n412\n00:30:44,039 --> 00:30:49,519\nAn idea seized me, and I went over the flat\nwith a small-tooth comb.\n\n413\n00:30:49,519 --> 00:30:55,590\nThere was nobody there, nor any trace of\nanybody, but I shuttered and bolted all the\n\n414\n00:30:55,590 --> 00:31:01,750\nwindows and put the chain on the door.\nBy this time my wits were coming back to\n\n415\n00:31:01,750 --> 00:31:04,710\nme, and I could think again.\n\n416\n00:31:04,710 --> 00:31:09,450\nIt took me about an hour to figure the\nthing out, and I did not hurry, for, unless\n\n417\n00:31:09,450 --> 00:31:15,619\nthe murderer came back, I had till about\nsix o'clock in the morning for my\n\n418\n00:31:15,619 --> 00:31:16,390\ncogitations.\n\n419\n00:31:16,390 --> 00:31:22,060\nI was in the soup--that was pretty clear.\nAny shadow of a doubt I might have had\n\n420\n00:31:22,060 --> 00:31:26,099\nabout the truth of Scudder's tale was now\ngone.\n\n421\n00:31:26,100 --> 00:31:30,540\nThe proof of it was lying under the table-\ncloth.\n\n422\n00:31:30,540 --> 00:31:36,189\nThe men who knew that he knew what he knew\nhad found him, and had taken the best way\n\n423\n00:31:36,189 --> 00:31:39,530\nto make certain of his silence.\n\n424\n00:31:39,530 --> 00:31:45,820\nYes; but he had been in my rooms four days,\nand his enemies must have reckoned that he\n\n425\n00:31:45,820 --> 00:31:51,700\nhad confided in me.\nSo I would be the next to go.\n\n426\n00:31:51,700 --> 00:31:59,769\nIt might be that very night, or next day,\nor the day after, but my number was up all\n\n427\n00:31:59,769 --> 00:32:02,620\nright.\nThen suddenly I thought of another\n\n428\n00:32:02,620 --> 00:32:03,980\nprobability.\n\n429\n00:32:03,980 --> 00:32:09,790\nSupposing I went out now and called in the\npolice, or went to bed and let Paddock find\n\n430\n00:32:09,790 --> 00:32:15,980\nthe body and call them in the morning.\nWhat kind of a story was I to tell about\n\n431\n00:32:15,980 --> 00:32:17,129\nScudder?\n\n432\n00:32:17,129 --> 00:32:22,959\nI had lied to Paddock about him, and the\nwhole thing looked desperately fishy.\n\n433\n00:32:22,959 --> 00:32:27,480\nIf I made a clean breast of it and told the\npolice everything he had told me, they\n\n434\n00:32:27,480 --> 00:32:30,069\nwould simply laugh at me.\n\n435\n00:32:30,069 --> 00:32:33,980\nThe odds were a thousand to one that I\nwould be charged with the murder, and the\n\n436\n00:32:33,980 --> 00:32:38,350\ncircumstantial evidence was strong enough\nto hang me.\n\n437\n00:32:38,349 --> 00:32:43,950\nFew people knew me in England; I had no\nreal pal who could come forward and swear\n\n438\n00:32:43,950 --> 00:32:48,510\nto my character.\nPerhaps that was what those secret enemies\n\n439\n00:32:48,510 --> 00:32:50,420\nwere playing for.\n\n440\n00:32:50,420 --> 00:32:54,950\nThey were clever enough for anything, and\nan English prison was as good a way of\n\n441\n00:32:54,950 --> 00:33:01,079\ngetting rid of me till after June 15th as a\nknife in my chest.\n\n442\n00:33:01,080 --> 00:33:07,209\nBesides, if I told the whole story, and by\nany miracle was believed, I would be\n\n443\n00:33:07,209 --> 00:33:12,170\nplaying their game.\nKarolides would stay at home, which was\n\n444\n00:33:12,170 --> 00:33:14,510\nwhat they wanted.\n\n445\n00:33:14,510 --> 00:33:19,780\nSomehow or other the sight of Scudder's\ndead face had made me a passionate believer\n\n446\n00:33:19,780 --> 00:33:22,590\nin his scheme.\n\n447\n00:33:22,340 --> 00:33:27,580\nHe was gone, but he had taken me into his\nconfidence, and I was pretty well bound to\n\n448\n00:33:27,580 --> 00:33:30,450\ncarry on his work.\n\n449\n00:33:30,200 --> 00:33:35,840\nYou may think this ridiculous for a man in\ndanger of his life, but that was the way I\n\n450\n00:33:35,840 --> 00:33:37,169\nlooked at it.\n\n451\n00:33:36,920 --> 00:33:43,709\nI am an ordinary sort of fellow, not braver\nthan other people, but I hate to see a good\n\n452\n00:33:43,709 --> 00:33:50,010\nman downed, and that long knife would not\nbe the end of Scudder if I could play the\n\n453\n00:33:50,010 --> 00:33:52,519\ngame in his place.\n\n454\n00:33:52,519 --> 00:33:57,120\nIt took me an hour or two to think this\nout, and by that time I had come to a\n\n455\n00:33:57,120 --> 00:34:01,659\ndecision.\nI must vanish somehow, and keep vanished\n\n456\n00:34:01,659 --> 00:34:05,110\ntill the end of the second week in June.\n\n457\n00:34:05,110 --> 00:34:10,350\nThen I must somehow find a way to get in\ntouch with the Government people and tell\n\n458\n00:34:10,350 --> 00:34:13,350\nthem what Scudder had told me.\n\n459\n00:34:13,100 --> 00:34:17,890\nI wished to Heaven he had told me more, and\nthat I had listened more carefully to the\n\n460\n00:34:17,890 --> 00:34:23,530\nlittle he had told me.\nI knew nothing but the barest facts.\n\n461\n00:34:23,530 --> 00:34:28,500\nThere was a big risk that, even if I\nweathered the other dangers, I would not be\n\n462\n00:34:28,500 --> 00:34:30,810\nbelieved in the end.\n\n463\n00:34:30,560 --> 00:34:35,050\nI must take my chance of that, and hope\nthat something might happen which would\n\n464\n00:34:35,050 --> 00:34:39,130\nconfirm my tale in the eyes of the\nGovernment.\n\n465\n00:34:39,130 --> 00:34:43,080\nMy first job was to keep going for the next\nthree weeks.\n\n466\n00:34:43,080 --> 00:34:48,690\nIt was now the 24th day of May, and that\nmeant twenty days of hiding before I could\n\n467\n00:34:48,690 --> 00:34:51,280\nventure to approach the powers that be.\n\n468\n00:34:51,280 --> 00:34:57,720\nI reckoned that two sets of people would be\nlooking for me--Scudder's enemies to put me\n\n469\n00:34:57,720 --> 00:35:02,730\nout of existence, and the police, who would\nwant me for Scudder's murder.\n\n470\n00:35:02,730 --> 00:35:10,320\nIt was going to be a giddy hunt, and it was\nqueer how the prospect comforted me.\n\n471\n00:35:10,320 --> 00:35:15,100\nI had been slack so long that almost any\nchance of activity was welcome.\n\n472\n00:35:15,100 --> 00:35:20,790\nWhen I had to sit alone with that corpse\nand wait on Fortune I was no better than a\n\n473\n00:35:20,790 --> 00:35:27,400\ncrushed worm, but if my neck's safety was\nto hang on my own wits I was prepared to be\n\n474\n00:35:27,400 --> 00:35:30,120\ncheerful about it.\n\n475\n00:35:30,120 --> 00:35:34,840\nMy next thought was whether Scudder had any\npapers about him to give me a better clue\n\n476\n00:35:34,840 --> 00:35:37,250\nto the business.\n\n477\n00:35:37,000 --> 00:35:41,670\nI drew back the table-cloth and searched\nhis pockets, for I had no longer any\n\n478\n00:35:41,670 --> 00:35:46,400\nshrinking from the body.\nThe face was wonderfully calm for a man who\n\n479\n00:35:46,400 --> 00:35:49,070\nhad been struck down in a moment.\n\n480\n00:35:49,070 --> 00:35:53,730\nThere was nothing in the breast-pocket, and\nonly a few loose coins and a cigar-holder\n\n481\n00:35:53,730 --> 00:35:56,070\nin the waistcoat.\n\n482\n00:35:55,820 --> 00:36:00,720\nThe trousers held a little penknife and\nsome silver, and the side pocket of his\n\n483\n00:36:00,720 --> 00:36:03,950\njacket contained an old crocodile-skin\ncigar-case.\n\n484\n00:36:05,550 --> 00:36:10,800\nThere was no sign of the little black book\nin which I had seen him making notes.\n\n485\n00:36:10,800 --> 00:36:15,520\nThat had no doubt been taken by his\nmurderer.\n\n486\n00:36:15,520 --> 00:36:19,450\nBut as I looked up from my task I saw that\nsome drawers had been pulled out in the\n\n487\n00:36:19,450 --> 00:36:23,500\nwriting-table.\nScudder would never have left them in that\n\n488\n00:36:23,500 --> 00:36:27,720\nstate, for he was the tidiest of mortals.\n\n489\n00:36:27,720 --> 00:36:32,060\nSomeone must have been searching for\nsomething--perhaps for the pocket-book.\n\n490\n00:36:33,720 --> 00:36:38,710\nI went round the flat and found that\neverything had been ransacked--the inside\n\n491\n00:36:38,710 --> 00:36:45,000\nof books, drawers, cupboards, boxes, even\nthe pockets of the clothes in my wardrobe,\n\n492\n00:36:45,000 --> 00:36:47,750\nand the sideboard in the dining-room.\n\n493\n00:36:47,750 --> 00:36:52,770\nThere was no trace of the book.\nMost likely the enemy had found it, but\n\n494\n00:36:52,770 --> 00:36:59,160\nthey had not found it on Scudder's body.\nThen I got out an atlas and looked at a big\n\n495\n00:36:59,160 --> 00:37:01,070\nmap of the British Isles.\n\n496\n00:37:01,070 --> 00:37:06,580\nMy notion was to get off to some wild\ndistrict, where my veldcraft would be of\n\n497\n00:37:06,580 --> 00:37:12,190\nsome use to me, for I would be like a\ntrapped rat in a city.\n\n498\n00:37:12,190 --> 00:37:17,730\nI considered that Scotland would be best,\nfor my people were Scotch and I could pass\n\n499\n00:37:17,730 --> 00:37:21,340\nanywhere as an ordinary Scotsman.\n\n500\n00:37:21,090 --> 00:37:26,160\nI had half an idea at first to be a German\ntourist, for my father had had German\n\n501\n00:37:26,160 --> 00:37:31,620\npartners, and I had been brought up to\nspeak the tongue pretty fluently, not to\n\n502\n00:37:31,620 --> 00:37:33,530\nmention having put in three years\n\n503\n00:37:33,530 --> 00:37:37,710\nprospecting for copper in German\nDamaraland.\n\n504\n00:37:37,710 --> 00:37:42,740\nBut I calculated that it would be less\nconspicuous to be a Scot, and less in a\n\n505\n00:37:42,740 --> 00:37:46,410\nline with what the police might know of my\npast.\n\n506\n00:37:46,410 --> 00:37:50,220\nI fixed on Galloway as the best place to\ngo.\n\n507\n00:37:50,220 --> 00:37:55,180\nIt was the nearest wild part of Scotland,\nso far as I could figure it out, and from\n\n508\n00:37:55,180 --> 00:38:00,090\nthe look of the map was not over thick with\npopulation.\n\n509\n00:38:00,090 --> 00:38:05,430\nA search in Bradshaw informed me that a\ntrain left St Pancras at 7.10, which would\n\n510\n00:38:05,430 --> 00:38:09,710\nland me at any Galloway station in the late\nafternoon.\n\n511\n00:38:09,710 --> 00:38:14,740\nThat was well enough, but a more important\nmatter was how I was to make my way to St\n\n512\n00:38:14,740 --> 00:38:18,709\nPancras, for I was pretty certain that\nScudder's friends would be watching\n\n513\n00:38:18,709 --> 00:38:20,649\noutside.\n\n514\n00:38:20,649 --> 00:38:26,560\nThis puzzled me for a bit; then I had an\ninspiration, on which I went to bed and\n\n515\n00:38:26,560 --> 00:38:33,070\nslept for two troubled hours.\nI got up at four and opened my bedroom\n\n516\n00:38:33,070 --> 00:38:34,240\nshutters.\n\n517\n00:38:34,240 --> 00:38:39,060\nThe faint light of a fine summer morning\nwas flooding the skies, and the sparrows\n\n518\n00:38:39,060 --> 00:38:44,540\nhad begun to chatter.\nI had a great revulsion of feeling, and\n\n519\n00:38:44,540 --> 00:38:47,780\nfelt a God-forgotten fool.\n\n520\n00:38:47,780 --> 00:38:52,570\nMy inclination was to let things slide, and\ntrust to the British police taking a\n\n521\n00:38:52,570 --> 00:38:54,560\nreasonable view of my case.\n\n522\n00:38:54,310 --> 00:39:00,020\nBut as I reviewed the situation I could\nfind no arguments to bring against my\n\n523\n00:39:00,020 --> 00:39:08,050\ndecision of the previous night, so with a\nwry mouth I resolved to go on with my plan.\n\n524\n00:39:08,050 --> 00:39:14,080\nI was not feeling in any particular funk;\nonly disinclined to go looking for trouble,\n\n525\n00:39:14,080 --> 00:39:16,640\nif you understand me.\n\n526\n00:39:16,390 --> 00:39:22,990\nI hunted out a well-used tweed suit, a pair\nof strong nailed boots, and a flannel shirt\n\n527\n00:39:22,990 --> 00:39:25,200\nwith a collar.\n\n528\n00:39:24,950 --> 00:39:31,710\nInto my pockets I stuffed a spare shirt, a\ncloth cap, some handkerchiefs, and a tooth-\n\n529\n00:39:31,710 --> 00:39:32,540\nbrush.\n\n530\n00:39:32,300 --> 00:39:37,140\nI had drawn a good sum in gold from the\nbank two days before, in case Scudder\n\n531\n00:39:37,140 --> 00:39:42,330\nshould want money, and I took fifty pounds\nof it in sovereigns in a belt which I had\n\n532\n00:39:42,330 --> 00:39:44,810\nbrought back from Rhodesia.\n\n533\n00:39:44,810 --> 00:39:49,200\nThat was about all I wanted.\nThen I had a bath, and cut my moustache,\n\n534\n00:39:49,200 --> 00:39:54,570\nwhich was long and drooping, into a short\nstubbly fringe.\n\n535\n00:39:54,570 --> 00:39:57,270\nNow came the next step.\n\n536\n00:39:57,270 --> 00:40:01,629\nPaddock used to arrive punctually at 7.30\nand let himself in with a latch-key.\n\n537\n00:40:01,630 --> 00:40:07,880\nBut about twenty minutes to seven, as I\nknew from bitter experience, the milkman\n\n538\n00:40:07,880 --> 00:40:15,140\nturned up with a great clatter of cans, and\ndeposited my share outside my door.\n\n539\n00:40:15,140 --> 00:40:19,910\nI had seen that milkman sometimes when I\nhad gone out for an early ride.\n\n540\n00:40:19,910 --> 00:40:24,610\nHe was a young man about my own height,\nwith an ill-nourished moustache, and he\n\n541\n00:40:24,610 --> 00:40:27,150\nwore a white overall.\n\n542\n00:40:27,150 --> 00:40:33,490\nOn him I staked all my chances.\nI went into the darkened smoking-room where\n\n543\n00:40:33,490 --> 00:40:38,220\nthe rays of morning light were beginning to\ncreep through the shutters.\n\n544\n00:40:38,220 --> 00:40:43,280\nThere I breakfasted off a whisky-and-soda\nand some biscuits from the cupboard.\n\n545\n00:40:43,280 --> 00:40:46,240\nBy this time it was getting on for six\no'clock.\n\n546\n00:40:46,240 --> 00:40:51,370\nI put a pipe in My Pocket and filled my\npouch from the tobacco jar on the table by\n\n547\n00:40:51,370 --> 00:40:53,550\nthe fireplace.\n\n548\n00:40:53,300 --> 00:40:59,610\nAs I poked into the tobacco my fingers\ntouched something hard, and I drew out\n\n549\n00:40:59,610 --> 00:41:05,600\nScudder's little black pocket-book ...\nThat seemed to me a good omen.\n\n550\n00:41:05,600 --> 00:41:10,590\nI lifted the cloth from the body and was\namazed at the peace and dignity of the dead\n\n551\n00:41:10,590 --> 00:41:15,390\nface.\n'Goodbye, old chap,' I said; 'I am going to\n\n552\n00:41:15,390 --> 00:41:16,890\ndo my best for you.\n\n553\n00:41:16,890 --> 00:41:22,210\nWish me well, wherever you are.'\nThen I hung about in the hall waiting for\n\n554\n00:41:22,210 --> 00:41:24,690\nthe milkman.\n\n555\n00:41:24,440 --> 00:41:29,100\nThat was the worst part of the business,\nfor I was fairly choking to get out of\n\n556\n00:41:29,100 --> 00:41:34,090\ndoors.\nSix-thirty passed, then six-forty, but\n\n557\n00:41:34,090 --> 00:41:36,530\nstill he did not come.\n\n558\n00:41:36,530 --> 00:41:42,480\nThe fool had chosen this day of all days to\nbe late.\n\n559\n00:41:42,480 --> 00:41:47,920\nAt one minute after the quarter to seven I\nheard the rattle of the cans outside.\n\n560\n00:41:47,920 --> 00:41:53,260\nI opened the front door, and there was my\nman, singling out my cans from a bunch he\n\n561\n00:41:53,260 --> 00:41:59,190\ncarried and whistling through his teeth.\nHe jumped a bit at the sight of me.\n\n562\n00:41:59,190 --> 00:42:02,140\n'Come in here a moment,' I said.\n\n563\n00:42:02,140 --> 00:42:04,540\n'I want a word with you.'\nAnd I led him into the dining-room.\n\n564\n00:42:04,540 --> 00:42:11,820\n'I reckon you're a bit of a sportsman,' I\nsaid, 'and I want you to do me a service.\n\n565\n00:42:11,820 --> 00:42:18,210\nLend me your cap and overall for ten\nminutes, and here's a sovereign for you.'\n\n566\n00:42:18,210 --> 00:42:22,400\nHis eyes opened at the sight of the gold,\nand he grinned broadly.\n\n567\n00:42:22,400 --> 00:42:25,080\n'Wot's the gyme?'he asked.\n\n568\n00:42:25,080 --> 00:42:30,260\n'A bet,' I said.\n'I haven't time to explain, but to win it\n\n569\n00:42:30,260 --> 00:42:33,680\nI've got to be a milkman for the next ten\nminutes.\n\n570\n00:42:33,680 --> 00:42:37,750\nAll you've got to do is to stay here till I\ncome back.\n\n571\n00:42:37,750 --> 00:42:42,110\nYou'll be a bit late, but nobody will\ncomplain, and you'll have that quid for\n\n572\n00:42:42,110 --> 00:42:42,900\nyourself.'\n\n573\n00:42:42,900 --> 00:42:49,230\n'Right-o!' he said cheerily.\n'I ain't the man to spoil a bit of sport.\n\n574\n00:42:49,230 --> 00:42:51,749\n'Ere's the rig, guv'nor.'\n\n575\n00:42:51,500 --> 00:42:56,990\nI stuck on his flat blue hat and his white\noverall, picked up the cans, banged my\n\n576\n00:42:56,990 --> 00:43:00,690\ndoor, and went whistling downstairs.\n\n577\n00:43:00,440 --> 00:43:05,470\nThe porter at the foot told me to shut my\njaw, which sounded as if my make-up was\n\n578\n00:43:05,470 --> 00:43:08,960\nadequate.\nAt first I thought there was nobody in the\n\n579\n00:43:08,960 --> 00:43:10,279\nstreet.\n\n580\n00:43:10,279 --> 00:43:14,800\nThen I caught sight of a policeman a\nhundred yards down, and a loafer shuffling\n\n581\n00:43:14,800 --> 00:43:18,100\npast on the other side.\n\n582\n00:43:17,850 --> 00:43:23,470\nSome impulse made me raise my eyes to the\nhouse opposite, and there at a first-floor\n\n583\n00:43:23,470 --> 00:43:29,190\nwindow was a face.\nAs the loafer passed he looked up, and I\n\n584\n00:43:29,190 --> 00:43:32,880\nfancied a signal was exchanged.\n\n585\n00:43:32,880 --> 00:43:38,920\nI crossed the street, whistling gaily and\nimitating the jaunty swing of the milkman.\n\n586\n00:43:38,920 --> 00:43:44,460\nThen I took the first side street, and went\nup a left-hand turning which led past a bit\n\n587\n00:43:44,460 --> 00:43:46,940\nof vacant ground.\n\n588\n00:43:46,940 --> 00:43:51,770\nThere was no one in the little street, so I\ndropped the milk-cans inside the hoarding\n\n589\n00:43:51,770 --> 00:43:58,230\nand sent the cap and overall after them.\nI had only just put on my cloth cap when a\n\n590\n00:43:58,230 --> 00:44:00,430\npostman came round the corner.\n\n591\n00:44:00,430 --> 00:44:05,339\nI gave him good morning and he answered me\nunsuspiciously.\n\n592\n00:44:05,339 --> 00:44:11,140\nAt the moment the clock of a neighbouring\nchurch struck the hour of seven.\n\n593\n00:44:11,140 --> 00:44:13,130\nThere was not a second to spare.\n\n594\n00:44:13,130 --> 00:44:17,770\nAs soon as I got to Euston Road I took to\nmy heels and ran.\n\n595\n00:44:17,770 --> 00:44:21,860\nThe clock at Euston Station showed five\nminutes past the hour.\n\n596\n00:44:21,860 --> 00:44:26,540\nAt St Pancras I had no time to take a\nticket, let alone that I had not settled\n\n597\n00:44:26,540 --> 00:44:29,160\nupon my destination.\n\n598\n00:44:28,910 --> 00:44:33,800\nA porter told me the platform, and as I\nentered it I saw the train already in\n\n599\n00:44:33,800 --> 00:44:35,290\nmotion.\n\n600\n00:44:35,040 --> 00:44:40,250\nTwo station officials blocked the way, but\nI dodged them and clambered into the last\n\n601\n00:44:40,250 --> 00:44:42,050\ncarriage.\n\n602\n00:44:41,800 --> 00:44:46,150\nThree minutes later, as we were roaring\nthrough the northern tunnels, an irate\n\n603\n00:44:46,150 --> 00:44:48,790\nguard interviewed me.\n\n604\n00:44:48,540 --> 00:44:53,830\nHe wrote out for me a ticket to Newton-\nStewart, a name which had suddenly come\n\n605\n00:44:53,830 --> 00:44:58,920\nback to my memory, and he conducted me from\nthe first-class compartment where I had\n\n606\n00:44:58,920 --> 00:45:02,279\nensconced myself to a third-class smoker,\n\n607\n00:45:02,279 --> 00:45:06,790\noccupied by a sailor and a stout woman with\na child.\n\n608\n00:45:06,790 --> 00:45:11,900\nHe went off grumbling, and as I mopped my\nbrow I observed to my companions in my\n\n609\n00:45:11,900 --> 00:45:16,940\nbroadest Scots that it was a sore job\ncatching trains.\n\n610\n00:45:16,940 --> 00:45:20,310\nI had already entered upon my part.\n\n611\n00:45:20,310 --> 00:45:24,649\n'The impidence o' that gyaird!' said the\nlady bitterly.\n\n612\n00:45:24,649 --> 00:45:25,830\n'He needit a Scotch tongue to pit him in\nhis place.\n\n613\n00:45:25,779 --> 00:45:31,920\nHe was complainin' o' this wean no haein' a\nticket and her no fower till August\n\n614\n00:45:31,920 --> 00:45:34,910\ntwalmonth, and he was objectin' to this\ngentleman spittin'.'\n\n615\n00:45:36,290 --> 00:45:42,170\nThe sailor morosely agreed, and I started\nmy new life in an atmosphere of protest\n\n616\n00:45:42,170 --> 00:45:47,310\nagainst authority.\nI reminded myself that a week ago I had\n\n617\n00:45:47,310 --> 00:45:52,430\nbeen finding the world dull.\n\n618\n00:45:54,500 --> 00:45:55,500\n>\n\n619\n00:45:55,500 --> 00:46:04,760\nCHAPTER THREE\nThe Adventure of the Literary Innkeeper\n\n620\n00:46:06,250 --> 00:46:09,969\nI had a solemn time travelling north that\nday.\n\n621\n00:46:09,969 --> 00:46:15,200\nIt was fine May weather, with the hawthorn\nflowering on every hedge, and I asked\n\n622\n00:46:15,200 --> 00:46:21,480\nmyself why, when I was still a free man, I\nhad stayed on in London and not got the\n\n623\n00:46:21,480 --> 00:46:24,720\ngood of this heavenly country.\n\n624\n00:46:24,720 --> 00:46:30,570\nI didn't dare face the restaurant car, but\nI got a luncheon-basket at Leeds and shared\n\n625\n00:46:30,570 --> 00:46:32,989\nit with the fat woman.\n\n626\n00:46:32,739 --> 00:46:37,180\nAlso I got the morning's papers, with news\nabout starters for the Derby and the\n\n627\n00:46:37,180 --> 00:46:41,990\nbeginning of the cricket season, and some\nparagraphs about how Balkan affairs were\n\n628\n00:46:41,989 --> 00:46:47,049\nsettling down and a British squadron was\ngoing to Kiel.\n\n629\n00:46:47,049 --> 00:46:51,190\nWhen I had done with them I got out\nScudder's little black pocket-book and\n\n630\n00:46:51,190 --> 00:46:52,949\nstudied it.\n\n631\n00:46:52,949 --> 00:46:58,850\nIt was pretty well filled with jottings,\nchiefly figures, though now and then a name\n\n632\n00:46:58,850 --> 00:46:59,920\nwas printed in.\n\n633\n00:47:00,510 --> 00:47:09,030\nFor example, I found the words 'Hofgaard',\n'Luneville', and 'Avocado' pretty often,\n\n634\n00:47:09,030 --> 00:47:12,759\nand especially the word 'Pavia'.\n\n635\n00:47:12,509 --> 00:47:18,119\nNow I was certain that Scudder never did\nanything without a reason, and I was pretty\n\n636\n00:47:18,119 --> 00:47:22,200\nsure that there was a cypher in all this.\n\n637\n00:47:21,950 --> 00:47:26,780\nThat is a subject which has always\ninterested me, and I did a bit at it myself\n\n638\n00:47:26,780 --> 00:47:33,059\nonce as intelligence officer at Delagoa Bay\nduring the Boer War.\n\n639\n00:47:33,060 --> 00:47:38,069\nI have a head for things like chess and\npuzzles, and I used to reckon myself pretty\n\n640\n00:47:38,069 --> 00:47:40,560\ngood at finding out cyphers.\n\n641\n00:47:40,310 --> 00:47:46,429\nThis one looked like the numerical kind\nwhere sets of figures correspond to the\n\n642\n00:47:46,429 --> 00:47:51,960\nletters of the alphabet, but any fairly\nshrewd man can find the clue to that sort\n\n643\n00:47:51,960 --> 00:47:54,270\nafter an hour or two's work, and I didn't\n\n644\n00:47:54,270 --> 00:47:59,010\nthink Scudder would have been content with\nanything so easy.\n\n645\n00:47:59,009 --> 00:48:04,750\nSo I fastened on the printed words, for you\ncan make a pretty good numerical cypher if\n\n646\n00:48:04,750 --> 00:48:08,700\nyou have a key word which gives you the\nsequence of the letters.\n\n647\n00:48:08,700 --> 00:48:13,800\nI tried for hours, but none of the words\nanswered.\n\n648\n00:48:13,800 --> 00:48:19,380\nThen I fell asleep and woke at Dumfries\njust in time to bundle out and get into the\n\n649\n00:48:19,380 --> 00:48:21,910\nslow Galloway train.\n\n650\n00:48:21,910 --> 00:48:27,090\nThere was a man on the platform whose looks\nI didn't like, but he never glanced at me,\n\n651\n00:48:27,090 --> 00:48:32,080\nand when I caught sight of myself in the\nmirror of an automatic machine I didn't\n\n652\n00:48:32,080 --> 00:48:33,220\nwonder.\n\n653\n00:48:33,220 --> 00:48:38,920\nWith my brown face, my old tweeds, and my\nslouch, I was the very model of one of the\n\n654\n00:48:38,920 --> 00:48:43,310\nhill farmers who were crowding into the\nthird-class carriages.\n\n655\n00:48:43,310 --> 00:48:47,460\nI travelled with half a dozen in an\natmosphere of shag and clay pipes.\n\n656\n00:48:47,460 --> 00:48:53,310\nThey had come from the weekly market, and\ntheir mouths were full of prices.\n\n657\n00:48:53,310 --> 00:48:58,390\nI heard accounts of how the lambing had\ngone up the Cairn and the Deuch and a dozen\n\n658\n00:48:58,390 --> 00:49:01,590\nother mysterious waters.\n\n659\n00:49:01,340 --> 00:49:06,540\nAbove half the men had lunched heavily and\nwere highly flavoured with whisky, but they\n\n660\n00:49:06,540 --> 00:49:09,120\ntook no notice of me.\n\n661\n00:49:08,870 --> 00:49:14,760\nWe rumbled slowly into a land of little\nwooded glens and then to a great wide\n\n662\n00:49:14,760 --> 00:49:22,720\nmoorland place, gleaming with lochs, with\nhigh blue hills showing northwards.\n\n663\n00:49:22,720 --> 00:49:27,670\nAbout five o'clock the carriage had\nemptied, and I was left alone as I had\n\n664\n00:49:27,670 --> 00:49:28,370\nhoped.\n\n665\n00:49:28,120 --> 00:49:33,590\nI got out at the next station, a little\nplace whose name I scarcely noted, set\n\n666\n00:49:33,590 --> 00:49:38,450\nright in the heart of a bog.\nIt reminded me of one of those forgotten\n\n667\n00:49:38,450 --> 00:49:41,450\nlittle stations in the Karroo.\n\n668\n00:49:41,450 --> 00:49:45,780\nAn old station-master was digging in his\ngarden, and with his spade over his\n\n669\n00:49:45,780 --> 00:49:50,760\nshoulder sauntered to the train, took\ncharge of a parcel, and went back to his\n\n670\n00:49:50,760 --> 00:49:52,280\npotatoes.\n\n671\n00:49:52,280 --> 00:49:57,530\nA child of ten received my ticket, and I\nemerged on a white road that straggled over\n\n672\n00:49:57,530 --> 00:49:59,700\nthe brown moor.\n\n673\n00:49:59,450 --> 00:50:04,940\nIt was a gorgeous spring evening, with\nevery hill showing as clear as a cut\n\n674\n00:50:04,940 --> 00:50:06,900\namethyst.\n\n675\n00:50:06,650 --> 00:50:13,259\nThe air had the queer, rooty smell of bogs,\nbut it was as fresh as mid-ocean, and it\n\n676\n00:50:13,259 --> 00:50:17,959\nhad the strangest effect on my spirits.\nI actually felt light-hearted.\n\n677\n00:50:18,889 --> 00:50:24,020\nI might have been a boy out for a spring\nholiday tramp, instead of a man of thirty-\n\n678\n00:50:24,020 --> 00:50:28,699\nseven very much wanted by the police.\n\n679\n00:50:28,449 --> 00:50:33,520\nI felt just as I used to feel when I was\nstarting for a big trek on a frosty morning\n\n680\n00:50:33,520 --> 00:50:38,490\non the high veld.\nIf you believe me, I swung along that road\n\n681\n00:50:38,490 --> 00:50:40,270\nwhistling.\n\n682\n00:50:40,270 --> 00:50:46,569\nThere was no plan of campaign in my head,\nonly just to go on and on in this blessed,\n\n683\n00:50:46,569 --> 00:50:53,770\nhonest-smelling hill country, for every\nmile put me in better humour with myself.\n\n684\n00:50:53,770 --> 00:50:58,879\nIn a roadside planting I cut a walking-\nstick of hazel, and presently struck off\n\n685\n00:50:58,879 --> 00:51:04,360\nthe highway up a bypath which followed the\nglen of a brawling stream.\n\n686\n00:51:04,360 --> 00:51:09,599\nI reckoned that I was still far ahead of\nany pursuit, and for that night might\n\n687\n00:51:09,599 --> 00:51:12,159\nplease myself.\n\n688\n00:51:11,909 --> 00:51:16,939\nIt was some hours since I had tasted food,\nand I was getting very hungry when I came\n\n689\n00:51:16,939 --> 00:51:22,149\nto a herd's cottage set in a nook beside a\nwaterfall.\n\n690\n00:51:22,150 --> 00:51:26,870\nA brown-faced woman was standing by the\ndoor, and greeted me with the kindly\n\n691\n00:51:26,870 --> 00:51:30,169\nshyness of moorland places.\n\n692\n00:51:29,919 --> 00:51:35,279\nWhen I asked for a night's lodging she said\nI was welcome to the 'bed in the loft', and\n\n693\n00:51:35,279 --> 00:51:41,749\nvery soon she set before me a hearty meal\nof ham and eggs, scones, and thick sweet\n\n694\n00:51:41,749 --> 00:51:44,090\nmilk.\n\n695\n00:51:44,090 --> 00:51:49,629\nAt the darkening her man came in from the\nhills, a lean giant, who in one step\n\n696\n00:51:49,629 --> 00:51:54,639\ncovered as much ground as three paces of\nordinary mortals.\n\n697\n00:51:54,639 --> 00:51:59,400\nThey asked me no questions, for they had\nthe perfect breeding of all dwellers in the\n\n698\n00:51:59,400 --> 00:52:05,520\nwilds, but I could see they set me down as\na kind of dealer, and I took some trouble\n\n699\n00:52:05,520 --> 00:52:07,490\nto confirm their view.\n\n700\n00:52:07,490 --> 00:52:13,139\nI spoke a lot about cattle, of which my\nhost knew little, and I picked up from him\n\n701\n00:52:13,139 --> 00:52:18,150\na good deal about the local Galloway\nmarkets, which I tucked away in my memory\n\n702\n00:52:18,150 --> 00:52:20,919\nfor future use.\n\n703\n00:52:20,919 --> 00:52:26,849\nAt ten I was nodding in my chair, and the\n'bed in the loft' received a weary man who\n\n704\n00:52:26,849 --> 00:52:32,999\nnever opened his eyes till five o'clock set\nthe little homestead a-going once more.\n\n705\n00:52:32,999 --> 00:52:38,550\nThey refused any payment, and by six I had\nbreakfasted and was striding southwards\n\n706\n00:52:38,550 --> 00:52:40,360\nagain.\n\n707\n00:52:40,110 --> 00:52:44,620\nMy notion was to return to the railway line\na station or two farther on than the place\n\n708\n00:52:44,620 --> 00:52:48,050\nwhere I had alighted yesterday and to\ndouble back.\n\n709\n00:52:48,050 --> 00:52:52,900\nI reckoned that that was the safest way,\nfor the police would naturally assume that\n\n710\n00:52:52,900 --> 00:52:58,810\nI was always making farther from London in\nthe direction of some western port.\n\n711\n00:52:58,809 --> 00:53:03,900\nI thought I had still a good bit of a\nstart, for, as I reasoned, it would take\n\n712\n00:53:03,900 --> 00:53:08,860\nsome hours to fix the blame on me, and\nseveral more to identify the fellow who got\n\n713\n00:53:08,860 --> 00:53:12,789\non board the train at St Pancras.\n\n714\n00:53:12,789 --> 00:53:18,080\nIt was the same jolly, clear spring\nweather, and I simply could not contrive to\n\n715\n00:53:18,080 --> 00:53:22,550\nfeel careworn.\nIndeed I was in better spirits than I had\n\n716\n00:53:22,550 --> 00:53:24,860\nbeen for months.\n\n717\n00:53:24,860 --> 00:53:30,080\nOver a long ridge of moorland I took my\nroad, skirting the side of a high hill\n\n718\n00:53:30,080 --> 00:53:34,460\nwhich the herd had called Cairnsmore of\nFleet.\n\n719\n00:53:34,460 --> 00:53:39,610\nNesting curlews and plovers were crying\neverywhere, and the links of green pasture\n\n720\n00:53:39,610 --> 00:53:43,530\nby the streams were dotted with young\nlambs.\n\n721\n00:53:43,529 --> 00:53:49,110\nAll the slackness of the past months was\nslipping from my bones, and I stepped out\n\n722\n00:53:49,110 --> 00:53:50,199\nlike a four-year-old.\n\n723\n00:53:51,360 --> 00:53:56,629\nBy-and-by I came to a swell of moorland\nwhich dipped to the vale of a little river,\n\n724\n00:53:56,629 --> 00:54:01,459\nand a mile away in the heather I saw the\nsmoke of a train.\n\n725\n00:54:01,460 --> 00:54:06,439\nThe station, when I reached it, proved to\nbe ideal for my purpose.\n\n726\n00:54:06,439 --> 00:54:12,119\nThe moor surged up around it and left room\nonly for the single line, the slender\n\n727\n00:54:12,119 --> 00:54:17,939\nsiding, a waiting-room, an office, the\nstation-master's cottage, and a tiny yard\n\n728\n00:54:17,939 --> 00:54:19,559\nof gooseberries and sweet-william.\n\n729\n00:54:19,559 --> 00:54:25,960\nThere seemed no road to it from anywhere,\nand to increase the desolation the waves of\n\n730\n00:54:25,960 --> 00:54:31,560\na tarn lapped on their grey granite beach\nhalf a mile away.\n\n731\n00:54:31,560 --> 00:54:36,259\nI waited in the deep heather till I saw the\nsmoke of an east-going train on the\n\n732\n00:54:36,259 --> 00:54:40,519\nhorizon.\nThen I approached the tiny booking-office\n\n733\n00:54:40,519 --> 00:54:43,709\nand took a ticket for Dumfries.\n\n734\n00:54:43,709 --> 00:54:49,050\nThe only occupants of the carriage were an\nold shepherd and his dog--a wall-eyed brute\n\n735\n00:54:49,050 --> 00:54:53,279\nthat I mistrusted.\nThe man was asleep, and on the cushions\n\n736\n00:54:53,279 --> 00:54:57,750\nbeside him was that morning's SCOTSMAN.\n\n737\n00:54:57,750 --> 00:55:03,110\nEagerly I seized on it, for I fancied it\nwould tell me something.\n\n738\n00:55:03,110 --> 00:55:07,370\nThere were two columns about the Portland\nPlace Murder, as it was called.\n\n739\n00:55:07,370 --> 00:55:11,490\nMy man Paddock had given the alarm and had\nthe milkman arrested.\n\n740\n00:55:11,490 --> 00:55:18,279\nPoor devil, it looked as if the latter had\nearned his sovereign hardly; but for me he\n\n741\n00:55:18,279 --> 00:55:22,120\nhad been cheap at the price, for he seemed\nto have occupied the police for the better\n\n742\n00:55:22,120 --> 00:55:24,050\npart of the day.\n\n743\n00:55:24,050 --> 00:55:28,570\nIn the latest news I found a further\ninstalment of the story.\n\n744\n00:55:28,570 --> 00:55:33,720\nThe milkman had been released, I read, and\nthe true criminal, about whose identity the\n\n745\n00:55:33,720 --> 00:55:38,850\npolice were reticent, was believed to have\ngot away from London by one of the northern\n\n746\n00:55:38,850 --> 00:55:39,970\nlines.\n\n747\n00:55:39,970 --> 00:55:43,860\nThere was a short note about me as the\nowner of the flat.\n\n748\n00:55:43,860 --> 00:55:48,800\nI guessed the police had stuck that in, as\na clumsy contrivance to persuade me that I\n\n749\n00:55:48,800 --> 00:55:51,430\nwas unsuspected.\n\n750\n00:55:51,430 --> 00:55:56,050\nThere was nothing else in the paper,\nnothing about foreign politics or\n\n751\n00:55:56,050 --> 00:56:00,190\nKarolides, or the things that had\ninterested Scudder.\n\n752\n00:56:00,190 --> 00:56:04,110\nI laid it down, and found that we were\napproaching the station at which I had got\n\n753\n00:56:04,110 --> 00:56:06,509\nout yesterday.\n\n754\n00:56:06,259 --> 00:56:11,290\nThe potato-digging station-master had been\ngingered up into some activity, for the\n\n755\n00:56:11,290 --> 00:56:17,009\nwest-going train was waiting to let us\npass, and from it had descended three men\n\n756\n00:56:17,009 --> 00:56:20,069\nwho were asking him questions.\n\n757\n00:56:20,069 --> 00:56:24,769\nI supposed that they were the local police,\nwho had been stirred up by Scotland Yard,\n\n758\n00:56:24,769 --> 00:56:28,670\nand had traced me as far as this one-horse\nsiding.\n\n759\n00:56:28,670 --> 00:56:33,430\nSitting well back in the shadow I watched\nthem carefully.\n\n760\n00:56:33,430 --> 00:56:36,730\nOne of them had a book, and took down\nnotes.\n\n761\n00:56:36,730 --> 00:56:41,899\nThe old potato-digger seemed to have turned\npeevish, but the child who had collected my\n\n762\n00:56:41,899 --> 00:56:47,190\nticket was talking volubly.\nAll the party looked out across the moor\n\n763\n00:56:47,190 --> 00:56:49,000\nwhere the white road departed.\n\n764\n00:56:49,000 --> 00:56:53,709\nI hoped they were going to take up my\ntracks there.\n\n765\n00:56:53,709 --> 00:56:57,430\nAs we moved away from that station my\ncompanion woke up.\n\n766\n00:56:57,430 --> 00:57:03,180\nHe fixed me with a wandering glance, kicked\nhis dog viciously, and inquired where he\n\n767\n00:57:03,180 --> 00:57:07,230\nwas.\nClearly he was very drunk.\n\n768\n00:57:07,230 --> 00:57:13,870\n'That's what comes o' bein' a teetotaller,'\nhe observed in bitter regret.\n\n769\n00:57:13,870 --> 00:57:18,170\nI expressed my surprise that in him I\nshould have met a blue-ribbon stalwart.\n\n770\n00:57:18,170 --> 00:57:23,660\n'Ay, but I'm a strong teetotaller,' he said\npugnaciously.\n\n771\n00:57:23,660 --> 00:57:29,829\n'I took the pledge last Martinmas, and I\nhavena touched a drop o' whisky sinsyne.\n\n772\n00:57:29,829 --> 00:57:34,899\nNot even at Hogmanay, though I was sair\ntemptit.'\n\n773\n00:57:34,899 --> 00:57:39,639\nHe swung his heels up on the seat, and\nburrowed a frowsy head into the cushions.\n\n774\n00:57:39,639 --> 00:57:43,060\n'And that's a' I get,' he moaned.\n\n775\n00:57:43,060 --> 00:57:49,389\n'A heid better than hell fire, and twae een\nlookin' different ways for the Sabbath.'\n\n776\n00:57:49,389 --> 00:57:52,060\n'What did it?'\nI asked.\n\n777\n00:57:52,060 --> 00:57:54,730\n'A drink they ca' brandy.\n\n778\n00:57:54,730 --> 00:58:01,029\nBein' a teetotaller I keepit off the\nwhisky, but I was nip-nippin' a' day at\n\n779\n00:58:01,029 --> 00:58:07,069\nthis brandy, and I doubt I'll no be weel\nfor a fortnicht.'\n\n780\n00:58:07,069 --> 00:58:14,080\nHis voice died away into a splutter, and\nsleep once more laid its heavy hand on him.\n\n781\n00:58:14,079 --> 00:58:19,259\nMy plan had been to get out at some station\ndown the line, but the train suddenly gave\n\n782\n00:58:19,259 --> 00:58:23,990\nme a better chance, for it came to a\nstandstill at the end of a culvert which\n\n783\n00:58:23,990 --> 00:58:27,740\nspanned a brawling porter-coloured river.\n\n784\n00:58:27,740 --> 00:58:33,089\nI looked out and saw that every carriage\nwindow was closed and no human figure\n\n785\n00:58:33,089 --> 00:58:35,559\nappeared in the landscape.\n\n786\n00:58:35,310 --> 00:58:40,730\nSo I opened the door, and dropped quickly\ninto the tangle of hazels which edged the\n\n787\n00:58:40,730 --> 00:58:46,389\nline. it would have been all right but for\nthat infernal dog.\n\n788\n00:58:46,389 --> 00:58:51,389\nUnder the impression that I was decamping\nwith its master's belongings, it started to\n\n789\n00:58:51,389 --> 00:58:55,459\nbark, and all but got me by the trousers.\n\n790\n00:58:55,209 --> 00:58:59,990\nThis woke up the herd, who stood bawling at\nthe carriage door in the belief that I had\n\n791\n00:58:59,990 --> 00:59:02,369\ncommitted suicide.\n\n792\n00:59:02,120 --> 00:59:06,899\nI crawled through the thicket, reached the\nedge of the stream, and in cover of the\n\n793\n00:59:06,899 --> 00:59:11,149\nbushes put a hundred yards or so behind me.\n\n794\n00:59:10,899 --> 00:59:15,920\nThen from my shelter I peered back, and saw\nthe guard and several passengers gathered\n\n795\n00:59:15,920 --> 00:59:20,329\nround the open carriage door and staring in\nmy direction.\n\n796\n00:59:20,329 --> 00:59:26,540\nI could not have made a more public\ndeparture if I had left with a bugler and a\n\n797\n00:59:26,540 --> 00:59:31,100\nbrass band.\nHappily the drunken herd provided a\n\n798\n00:59:31,100 --> 00:59:31,800\ndiversion.\n\n799\n00:59:31,800 --> 00:59:37,100\nHe and his dog, which was attached by a\nrope to his waist, suddenly cascaded out of\n\n800\n00:59:37,100 --> 00:59:42,350\nthe carriage, landed on their heads on the\ntrack, and rolled some way down the bank\n\n801\n00:59:42,350 --> 00:59:44,730\ntowards the water.\n\n802\n00:59:44,730 --> 00:59:48,779\nIn the rescue which followed the dog bit\nsomebody, for I could hear the sound of\n\n803\n00:59:48,779 --> 00:59:51,470\nhard swearing.\n\n804\n00:59:51,220 --> 00:59:55,470\nPresently they had forgotten me, and when\nafter a quarter of a mile's crawl I\n\n805\n00:59:55,470 --> 01:00:00,490\nventured to look back, the train had\nstarted again and was vanishing in the\n\n806\n01:00:00,490 --> 01:00:02,310\ncutting.\n\n807\n01:00:02,310 --> 01:00:07,040\nI was in a wide semicircle of moorland,\nwith the brown river as radius, and the\n\n808\n01:00:07,040 --> 01:00:11,230\nhigh hills forming the northern\ncircumference.\n\n809\n01:00:11,230 --> 01:00:16,990\nThere was not a sign or sound of a human\nbeing, only the plashing water and the\n\n810\n01:00:16,990 --> 01:00:22,860\ninterminable crying of curlews.\nYet, oddly enough, for the first time I\n\n811\n01:00:22,860 --> 01:00:26,149\nfelt the terror of the hunted on me.\n\n812\n01:00:26,149 --> 01:00:31,079\nIt was not the police that I thought of,\nbut the other folk, who knew that I knew\n\n813\n01:00:31,079 --> 01:00:36,220\nScudder's secret and dared not let me live.\n\n814\n01:00:35,970 --> 01:00:40,540\nI was certain that they would pursue me\nwith a keenness and vigilance unknown to\n\n815\n01:00:40,540 --> 01:00:48,310\nthe British law, and that once their grip\nclosed on me I should find no mercy.\n\n816\n01:00:48,310 --> 01:00:51,680\nI looked back, but there was nothing in the\nlandscape.\n\n817\n01:00:51,680 --> 01:00:56,529\nThe sun glinted on the metals of the line\nand the wet stones in the stream, and you\n\n818\n01:00:56,529 --> 01:01:01,220\ncould not have found a more peaceful sight\nin the world.\n\n819\n01:01:01,220 --> 01:01:03,930\nNevertheless I started to run.\n\n820\n01:01:03,930 --> 01:01:10,130\nCrouching low in the runnels of the bog, I\nran till the sweat blinded my eyes.\n\n821\n01:01:10,129 --> 01:01:14,350\nThe mood did not leave me till I had\nreached the rim of mountain and flung\n\n822\n01:01:14,350 --> 01:01:20,670\nmyself panting on a ridge high above the\nyoung waters of the brown river.\n\n823\n01:01:20,670 --> 01:01:25,779\nFrom my vantage-ground I could scan the\nwhole moor right away to the railway line\n\n824\n01:01:25,779 --> 01:01:30,330\nand to the south of it where green fields\ntook the place of heather.\n\n825\n01:01:30,329 --> 01:01:37,149\nI have eyes like a hawk, but I could see\nnothing moving in the whole countryside.\n\n826\n01:01:37,149 --> 01:01:43,430\nThen I looked east beyond the ridge and saw\na new kind of landscape--shallow green\n\n827\n01:01:43,430 --> 01:01:50,370\nvalleys with plentiful fir plantations and\nthe faint lines of dust which spoke of\n\n828\n01:01:50,370 --> 01:01:52,699\nhighroads.\n\n829\n01:01:52,699 --> 01:01:58,269\nLast of all I looked into the blue May sky,\nand there I saw that which set my pulses\n\n830\n01:01:58,269 --> 01:02:03,089\nracing ...\nLow down in the south a monoplane was\n\n831\n01:02:03,089 --> 01:02:05,819\nclimbing into the heavens.\n\n832\n01:02:05,819 --> 01:02:11,810\nI was as certain as if I had been told that\nthat aeroplane was looking for me, and that\n\n833\n01:02:11,810 --> 01:02:17,839\nit did not belong to the police.\nFor an hour or two I watched it from a pit\n\n834\n01:02:17,839 --> 01:02:19,249\nof heather.\n\n835\n01:02:19,249 --> 01:02:24,930\nIt flew low along the hill-tops, and then\nin narrow circles over the valley up which\n\n836\n01:02:24,930 --> 01:02:30,889\nI had come' Then it seemed to change its\nmind, rose to a great height, and flew away\n\n837\n01:02:30,889 --> 01:02:33,560\nback to the south.\n\n838\n01:02:33,560 --> 01:02:38,839\nI did not like this espionage from the air,\nand I began to think less well of the\n\n839\n01:02:38,839 --> 01:02:43,089\ncountryside I had chosen for a refuge.\n\n840\n01:02:42,839 --> 01:02:48,100\nThese heather hills were no sort of cover\nif my enemies were in the sky, and I must\n\n841\n01:02:48,100 --> 01:02:51,529\nfind a different kind of sanctuary.\n\n842\n01:02:51,279 --> 01:02:56,269\nI looked with more satisfaction to the\ngreen country beyond the ridge, for there I\n\n843\n01:02:56,269 --> 01:03:00,780\nshould find woods and stone houses.\n\n844\n01:03:00,530 --> 01:03:05,000\nAbout six in the evening I came out of the\nmoorland to a white ribbon of road which\n\n845\n01:03:05,000 --> 01:03:09,130\nwound up the narrow vale of a lowland\nstream.\n\n846\n01:03:09,130 --> 01:03:15,029\nAs I followed it, fields gave place to\nbent, the glen became a plateau, and\n\n847\n01:03:15,029 --> 01:03:19,779\npresently I had reached a kind of pass\nwhere a solitary house smoked in the\n\n848\n01:03:19,779 --> 01:03:21,650\ntwilight.\n\n849\n01:03:21,650 --> 01:03:27,510\nThe road swung over a bridge, and leaning\non the parapet was a young man.\n\n850\n01:03:27,510 --> 01:03:32,580\nHe was smoking a long clay pipe and\nstudying the water with spectacled eyes.\n\n851\n01:03:32,580 --> 01:03:38,730\nIn his left hand was a small book with a\nfinger marking the place.\n\n852\n01:03:38,730 --> 01:03:39,900\nSlowly he repeated--\n\n853\n01:03:40,220 --> 01:03:47,350\nAs when a Gryphon through the wilderness\nWith winged step, o'er hill and moory dale\n\n854\n01:03:47,350 --> 01:03:51,200\nPursues the Arimaspian.\n\n855\n01:03:50,950 --> 01:03:56,640\nHe jumped round as my step rung on the\nkeystone, and I saw a pleasant sunburnt\n\n856\n01:03:56,640 --> 01:04:00,750\nboyish face.\n'Good evening to you,' he said gravely.\n\n857\n01:04:00,750 --> 01:04:04,620\n'It's a fine night for the road.'\n\n858\n01:04:04,620 --> 01:04:09,850\nThe smell of peat smoke and of some savoury\nroast floated to me from the house.\n\n859\n01:04:09,850 --> 01:04:14,200\n'Is that place an inn?'\nI asked.\n\n860\n01:04:14,200 --> 01:04:16,210\n'At your service,' he said politely.\n\n861\n01:04:16,210 --> 01:04:21,779\n'I am the landlord, Sir, and I hope you\nwill stay the night, for to tell you the\n\n862\n01:04:21,779 --> 01:04:27,830\ntruth I have had no company for a week.'\nI pulled myself up on the parapet of the\n\n863\n01:04:27,830 --> 01:04:29,950\nbridge and filled my pipe.\n\n864\n01:04:29,950 --> 01:04:35,960\nI began to detect an ally.\n'You're young to be an innkeeper,' I said.\n\n865\n01:04:35,960 --> 01:04:40,270\n'My father died a year ago and left me the\nbusiness.\n\n866\n01:04:40,270 --> 01:04:42,640\nI live there with my grandmother.\n\n867\n01:04:42,640 --> 01:04:46,909\nIt's a slow job for a young man, and it\nwasn't my choice of profession.'\n\n868\n01:04:46,909 --> 01:04:51,450\n'Which was?'\nHe actually blushed.\n\n869\n01:04:51,450 --> 01:04:55,480\n'I want to write books,' he said.\n\n870\n01:04:55,480 --> 01:04:59,450\n'And what better chance could you ask?'\nI cried.\n\n871\n01:04:59,450 --> 01:05:03,520\n'Man, I've often thought that an innkeeper\nwould make the best story-teller in the\n\n872\n01:05:03,520 --> 01:05:04,100\nworld.'\n\n873\n01:05:04,100 --> 01:05:09,720\n'Not now,' he said eagerly.\n'Maybe in the old days when you had\n\n874\n01:05:09,720 --> 01:05:14,610\npilgrims and ballad-makers and highwaymen\nand mail-coaches on the road.\n\n875\n01:05:14,610 --> 01:05:16,370\nBut not now.\n\n876\n01:05:16,370 --> 01:05:21,100\nNothing comes here but motor-cars full of\nfat women, who stop for lunch, and a\n\n877\n01:05:21,100 --> 01:05:24,700\nfisherman or two in the spring, and the\nshooting tenants in August.\n\n878\n01:05:24,700 --> 01:05:28,279\nThere is not much material to be got out of\nthat.\n\n879\n01:05:28,279 --> 01:05:33,740\nI want to see life, to travel the world,\nand write things like Kipling and Conrad.\n\n880\n01:05:33,740 --> 01:05:39,860\nBut the most I've done yet is to get some\nverses printed in CHAMBERS'S JOURNAL.'\n\n881\n01:05:39,860 --> 01:05:46,120\nI looked at the inn standing golden in the\nsunset against the brown hills.\n\n882\n01:05:46,120 --> 01:05:50,370\n'I've knocked a bit about the world, and I\nwouldn't despise such a hermitage.\n\n883\n01:05:50,370 --> 01:05:57,120\nD'you think that adventure is found only in\nthe tropics or among gentry in red shirts?\n\n884\n01:05:57,120 --> 01:05:59,390\nMaybe you're rubbing shoulders with it at\nthis moment.'\n\n885\n01:05:59,390 --> 01:06:06,159\n'That's what Kipling says,' he said, his\neyes brightening, and he quoted some verse\n\n886\n01:06:06,159 --> 01:06:09,200\nabout 'Romance bringing up the 9.15'.\n\n887\n01:06:09,200 --> 01:06:16,220\n'Here's a true tale for you then,' I cried,\n'and a month from now you can make a novel\n\n888\n01:06:16,220 --> 01:06:19,880\nout of it.'\nSitting on the bridge in the soft May\n\n889\n01:06:19,880 --> 01:06:23,710\ngloaming I pitched him a lovely yarn.\n\n890\n01:06:23,710 --> 01:06:28,690\nIt was true in essentials, too, though I\naltered the minor details.\n\n891\n01:06:28,690 --> 01:06:32,990\nI made out that I was a mining magnate from\nKimberley, who had had a lot of trouble\n\n892\n01:06:32,990 --> 01:06:38,460\nwith I.D.B. and had shown up a gang.\n\n893\n01:06:38,460 --> 01:06:43,000\nThey had pursued me across the ocean, and\nhad killed my best friend, and were now on\n\n894\n01:06:43,000 --> 01:06:47,250\nmy tracks.\nI told the story well, though I say it who\n\n895\n01:06:47,250 --> 01:06:48,279\nshouldn't.\n\n896\n01:06:48,279 --> 01:06:53,899\nI pictured a flight across the Kalahari to\nGerman Africa, the crackling, parching\n\n897\n01:06:53,899 --> 01:06:57,749\ndays, the wonderful blue-velvet nights.\n\n898\n01:06:57,500 --> 01:07:02,140\nI described an attack on my life on the\nvoyage home, and I made a really horrid\n\n899\n01:07:02,140 --> 01:07:08,059\naffair of the Portland Place murder.\n'You're looking for adventure,' I cried;\n\n900\n01:07:08,059 --> 01:07:09,960\n'well, you've found it here.\n\n901\n01:07:09,960 --> 01:07:13,570\nThe devils are after me, and the police are\nafter them.\n\n902\n01:07:13,570 --> 01:07:15,400\nIt's a race that I mean to win.'\n\n903\n01:07:15,149 --> 01:07:22,669\n'By God!' he whispered, drawing his breath\nin sharply, 'it is all pure Rider Haggard\n\n904\n01:07:22,669 --> 01:07:26,940\nand Conan Doyle.'\n'You believe me,' I said gratefully.\n\n905\n01:07:26,940 --> 01:07:30,539\n'Of course I do,' and he held out his hand.\n\n906\n01:07:30,539 --> 01:07:36,330\n'I believe everything out of the common.\nThe only thing to distrust is the normal.'\n\n907\n01:07:36,330 --> 01:07:40,070\nHe was very young, but he was the man for\nmy money.\n\n908\n01:07:40,070 --> 01:07:44,820\n'I think they're off my track for the\nmoment, but I must lie close for a couple\n\n909\n01:07:44,820 --> 01:07:47,900\nof days.\nCan you take me in?'\n\n910\n01:07:47,899 --> 01:07:51,770\nHe caught my elbow in his eagerness and\ndrew me towards the house.\n\n911\n01:07:51,770 --> 01:07:55,880\n'You can lie as snug here as if you were in\na moss-hole.\n\n912\n01:07:55,880 --> 01:07:58,490\nI'll see that nobody blabs, either.\n\n913\n01:07:58,490 --> 01:08:02,600\nAnd you'll give me some more material about\nyour adventures?'\n\n914\n01:08:02,600 --> 01:08:08,050\nAs I entered the inn porch I heard from far\noff the beat of an engine.\n\n915\n01:08:08,049 --> 01:08:15,309\nThere silhouetted against the dusky West\nwas my friend, the monoplane.\n\n916\n01:08:15,309 --> 01:08:20,100\nHe gave me a room at the back of the house,\nwith a fine outlook over the plateau, and\n\n917\n01:08:20,100 --> 01:08:24,110\nhe made me free of his own study, which was\nstacked with cheap editions of his\n\n918\n01:08:24,110 --> 01:08:26,070\nfavourite authors.\n\n919\n01:08:26,070 --> 01:08:30,880\nI never saw the grandmother, so I guessed\nshe was bedridden.\n\n920\n01:08:30,880 --> 01:08:36,190\nAn old woman called Margit brought me my\nmeals, and the innkeeper was around me at\n\n921\n01:08:36,190 --> 01:08:38,070\nall hours.\n\n922\n01:08:38,070 --> 01:08:42,590\nI wanted some time to myself, so I invented\na job for him.\n\n923\n01:08:42,590 --> 01:08:47,210\nHe had a motor-bicycle, and I sent him off\nnext morning for the daily paper, which\n\n924\n01:08:47,210 --> 01:08:50,989\nusually arrived with the post in the late\nafternoon.\n\n925\n01:08:50,990 --> 01:08:57,529\nI told him to keep his eyes skinned, and\nmake note of any strange figures he saw,\n\n926\n01:08:57,529 --> 01:09:02,520\nkeeping a special sharp look-out for motors\nand aeroplanes.\n\n927\n01:09:02,520 --> 01:09:07,640\nThen I sat down in real earnest to\nScudder's note-book.\n\n928\n01:09:07,640 --> 01:09:10,600\nHe came back at midday with the SCOTSMAN.\n\n929\n01:09:10,350 --> 01:09:13,799\nThere was nothing in it, except some\nfurther evidence of Paddock and the\n\n930\n01:09:13,799 --> 01:09:19,740\nmilkman, and a repetition of yesterday's\nstatement that the murderer had gone North.\n\n931\n01:09:19,740 --> 01:09:25,179\nBut there was a long article, reprinted\nfrom THE TIMES, about Karolides and the\n\n932\n01:09:25,179 --> 01:09:29,520\nstate of affairs in the Balkans, though\nthere was no mention of any visit to\n\n933\n01:09:29,520 --> 01:09:31,049\nEngland.\n\n934\n01:09:31,049 --> 01:09:35,429\nI got rid of the innkeeper for the\nafternoon, for I was getting very warm in\n\n935\n01:09:35,429 --> 01:09:38,360\nmy search for the cypher.\n\n936\n01:09:38,110 --> 01:09:44,919\nAs I told you, it was a numerical cypher,\nand by an elaborate system of experiments I\n\n937\n01:09:44,919 --> 01:09:49,279\nhad pretty well discovered what were the\nnulls and stops.\n\n938\n01:09:49,279 --> 01:09:55,390\nThe trouble was the key word, and when I\nthought of the odd million words he might\n\n939\n01:09:55,390 --> 01:10:01,549\nhave used I felt pretty hopeless.\nBut about three o'clock I had a sudden\n\n940\n01:10:01,549 --> 01:10:02,850\ninspiration.\n\n941\n01:10:02,850 --> 01:10:08,029\nThe name Julia Czechenyi flashed across my\nmemory.\n\n942\n01:10:08,029 --> 01:10:12,330\nScudder had said it was the key to the\nKarolides business, and it occurred to me\n\n943\n01:10:12,330 --> 01:10:15,320\nto try it on his cypher.\n\n944\n01:10:15,320 --> 01:10:18,799\nIt worked.\nThe five letters of 'Julia' gave me the\n\n945\n01:10:18,799 --> 01:10:24,409\nposition of the vowels.\nA was J, the tenth letter of the alphabet,\n\n946\n01:10:24,409 --> 01:10:27,279\nand so represented by X in the cypher.\n\n947\n01:10:27,279 --> 01:10:35,470\nE was XXI, and so on.\n'Czechenyi' gave me the numerals for the\n\n948\n01:10:35,470 --> 01:10:40,010\nprincipal consonants.\nI scribbled that scheme on a bit of paper\n\n949\n01:10:40,010 --> 01:10:43,630\nand sat down to read Scudder's pages.\n\n950\n01:10:43,630 --> 01:10:47,779\nIn half an hour I was reading with a\nwhitish face and fingers that drummed on\n\n951\n01:10:47,779 --> 01:10:49,470\nthe table.\n\n952\n01:10:49,220 --> 01:10:54,789\nI glanced out of the window and saw a big\ntouring-car coming up the glen towards the\n\n953\n01:10:54,789 --> 01:10:58,269\ninn.\nIt drew up at the door, and there was the\n\n954\n01:10:58,269 --> 01:11:00,159\nsound of people alighting.\n\n955\n01:11:00,159 --> 01:11:06,429\nThere seemed to be two of them, men in\naquascutums and tweed caps.\n\n956\n01:11:06,429 --> 01:11:10,500\nTen minutes later the innkeeper slipped\ninto the room, his eyes bright with\n\n957\n01:11:10,500 --> 01:11:11,539\nexcitement.\n\n958\n01:11:11,539 --> 01:11:15,600\n'There's two chaps below looking for you,'\nhe whispered.\n\n959\n01:11:15,600 --> 01:11:17,990\n'They're in the dining-room having\nwhiskies-and-sodas.\n\n960\n01:11:19,010 --> 01:11:22,340\nThey asked about you and said they had\nhoped to meet you here.\n\n961\n01:11:22,340 --> 01:11:27,440\nOh! and they described you jolly well, down\nto your boots and shirt.\n\n962\n01:11:27,440 --> 01:11:32,019\nI told them you had been here last night\nand had gone off on a motor bicycle this\n\n963\n01:11:32,019 --> 01:11:35,850\nmorning, and one of the chaps swore like a\nnavvy.'\n\n964\n01:11:35,850 --> 01:11:38,760\nI made him tell me what they looked like.\n\n965\n01:11:38,760 --> 01:11:45,159\nOne was a dark-eyed thin fellow with bushy\neyebrows, the other was always smiling and\n\n966\n01:11:45,159 --> 01:11:50,159\nlisped in his talk.\nNeither was any kind of foreigner; on this\n\n967\n01:11:50,159 --> 01:11:53,019\nmy young friend was positive.\n\n968\n01:11:53,019 --> 01:11:59,320\nI took a bit of paper and wrote these words\nin German as if they were part of a letter-\n\n969\n01:11:59,320 --> 01:11:59,570\n-\n\n970\n01:11:59,320 --> 01:12:01,740\n...\n'Black Stone.\n\n971\n01:12:01,740 --> 01:12:05,290\nScudder had got on to this, but he could\nnot act for a fortnight.\n\n972\n01:12:05,289 --> 01:12:11,070\nI doubt if I can do any good now,\nespecially as Karolides is uncertain about\n\n973\n01:12:11,070 --> 01:12:15,340\nhis plans.\nBut if Mr T. advises I will do the best I\n\n974\n01:12:15,340 --> 01:12:16,450\n...'\n\n975\n01:12:16,450 --> 01:12:21,760\nI manufactured it rather neatly, so that it\nlooked like a loose page of a private\n\n976\n01:12:21,760 --> 01:12:23,520\nletter.\n\n977\n01:12:23,269 --> 01:12:28,610\n'Take this down and say it was found in my\nbedroom, and ask them to return it to me if\n\n978\n01:12:28,610 --> 01:12:31,440\nthey overtake me.'\n\n979\n01:12:31,190 --> 01:12:35,549\nThree minutes later I heard the car begin\nto move, and peeping from behind the\n\n980\n01:12:35,549 --> 01:12:42,929\ncurtain caught sight of the two figures.\nOne was slim, the other was sleek; that was\n\n981\n01:12:42,929 --> 01:12:46,330\nthe most I could make of my reconnaissance.\n\n982\n01:12:46,330 --> 01:12:51,019\nThe innkeeper appeared in great excitement.\n'Your paper woke them up,' he said\n\n983\n01:12:51,019 --> 01:12:52,059\ngleefully.\n\n984\n01:12:51,809 --> 01:12:57,360\n'The dark fellow went as white as death and\ncursed like blazes, and the fat one\n\n985\n01:12:57,360 --> 01:13:01,140\nwhistled and looked ugly.\nThey paid for their drinks with half-a-\n\n986\n01:13:01,140 --> 01:13:04,210\nsovereign and wouldn't wait for change.'\n\n987\n01:13:04,210 --> 01:13:07,279\n'Now I'll tell you what I want you to do,'\nI said.\n\n988\n01:13:07,279 --> 01:13:11,630\n'Get on your bicycle and go off to Newton-\nStewart to the Chief Constable.\n\n989\n01:13:11,630 --> 01:13:16,320\nDescribe the two men, and say you suspect\nthem of having had something to do with the\n\n990\n01:13:16,320 --> 01:13:19,840\nLondon murder.\nYou can invent reasons.\n\n991\n01:13:19,840 --> 01:13:22,590\nThe two will come back, never fear.\n\n992\n01:13:22,590 --> 01:13:27,750\nNot tonight, for they'll follow me forty\nmiles along the road, but first thing\n\n993\n01:13:27,750 --> 01:13:30,789\ntomorrow morning.\nTell the police to be here bright and\n\n994\n01:13:30,789 --> 01:13:32,429\nearly.'\n\n995\n01:13:32,429 --> 01:13:37,480\nHe set off like a docile child, while I\nworked at Scudder's notes.\n\n996\n01:13:37,480 --> 01:13:43,580\nWhen he came back we dined together, and in\ncommon decency I had to let him pump me.\n\n997\n01:13:43,580 --> 01:13:48,830\nI gave him a lot of stuff about lion hunts\nand the Matabele War, thinking all the\n\n998\n01:13:48,830 --> 01:13:54,809\nwhile what tame businesses these were\ncompared to this I was now engaged in!\n\n999\n01:13:54,809 --> 01:13:58,799\nWhen he went to bed I sat up and finished\nScudder.\n\n1000\n01:13:58,799 --> 01:14:04,140\nI smoked in a chair till daylight, for I\ncould not sleep.\n\n1001\n01:14:04,139 --> 01:14:09,250\nAbout eight next morning I witnessed the\narrival of two constables and a sergeant.\n\n1002\n01:14:09,250 --> 01:14:13,529\nThey put their car in a coach-house under\nthe innkeeper's instructions, and entered\n\n1003\n01:14:13,529 --> 01:14:15,360\nthe house.\n\n1004\n01:14:15,360 --> 01:14:20,190\nTwenty minutes later I saw from my window a\nsecond car come across the plateau from the\n\n1005\n01:14:20,190 --> 01:14:22,320\nopposite direction.\n\n1006\n01:14:22,070 --> 01:14:27,360\nIt did not come up to the inn, but stopped\ntwo hundred yards off in the shelter of a\n\n1007\n01:14:27,360 --> 01:14:31,419\npatch of wood.\nI noticed that its occupants carefully\n\n1008\n01:14:31,419 --> 01:14:34,429\nreversed it before leaving it.\n\n1009\n01:14:34,429 --> 01:14:40,029\nA minute or two later I heard their steps\non the gravel outside the window.\n\n1010\n01:14:40,029 --> 01:14:44,470\nMy plan had been to lie hid in my bedroom,\nand see what happened.\n\n1011\n01:14:44,470 --> 01:14:49,970\nI had a notion that, if I could bring the\npolice and my other more dangerous pursuers\n\n1012\n01:14:49,970 --> 01:14:53,880\ntogether, something might work out of it to\nmy advantage.\n\n1013\n01:14:53,880 --> 01:14:58,010\nBut now I had a better idea.\n\n1014\n01:14:58,010 --> 01:15:03,299\nI scribbled a line of thanks to my host,\nopened the window, and dropped quietly into\n\n1015\n01:15:03,299 --> 01:15:05,490\na gooseberry bush.\n\n1016\n01:15:05,240 --> 01:15:10,990\nUnobserved I crossed the dyke, crawled down\nthe side of a tributary burn, and won the\n\n1017\n01:15:10,990 --> 01:15:14,890\nhighroad on the far side of the patch of\ntrees.\n\n1018\n01:15:14,889 --> 01:15:20,490\nThere stood the car, very spick and span in\nthe morning sunlight, but with the dust on\n\n1019\n01:15:20,490 --> 01:15:23,419\nher which told of a long journey.\n\n1020\n01:15:23,169 --> 01:15:28,429\nI started her, jumped into the chauffeur's\nseat, and stole gently out on to the\n\n1021\n01:15:28,429 --> 01:15:30,330\nplateau.\n\n1022\n01:15:30,080 --> 01:15:36,029\nAlmost at once the road dipped so that I\nlost sight of the inn, but the wind seemed\n\n1023\n01:15:36,029 --> 01:15:43,059\nto bring me the sound of angry voices.\n\n1024\n01:15:43,750 --> 01:15:44,750\n>\n\n1025\n01:15:44,750 --> 01:15:54,030\nCHAPTER FOUR\nThe Adventure of the Radical Candidate\n\n1026\n01:15:55,539 --> 01:16:01,430\nYou may picture me driving that 40 h.p. car\nfor all she was worth over the crisp moor\n\n1027\n01:16:01,430 --> 01:16:07,250\nroads on that shining May morning; glancing\nback at first over my shoulder, and looking\n\n1028\n01:16:07,250 --> 01:16:10,460\nanxiously to the next turning; then driving\n\n1029\n01:16:10,460 --> 01:16:15,320\nwith a vague eye, just wide enough awake to\nkeep on the highway.\n\n1030\n01:16:15,320 --> 01:16:20,460\nFor I was thinking desperately of what I\nhad found in Scudder's pocket-book.\n\n1031\n01:16:20,460 --> 01:16:23,550\nThe little man had told me a pack of lies.\n\n1032\n01:16:23,550 --> 01:16:29,399\nAll his yarns about the Balkans and the\nJew-Anarchists and the Foreign Office\n\n1033\n01:16:29,399 --> 01:16:34,579\nConference were eyewash, and so was\nKarolides.\n\n1034\n01:16:34,579 --> 01:16:38,559\nAnd yet not quite, as you shall hear.\n\n1035\n01:16:38,559 --> 01:16:43,879\nI had staked everything on my belief in his\nstory, and had been let down; here was his\n\n1036\n01:16:43,879 --> 01:16:49,809\nbook telling me a different tale, and\ninstead of being once-bitten-twice-shy, I\n\n1037\n01:16:49,809 --> 01:16:53,190\nbelieved it absolutely.\n\n1038\n01:16:53,190 --> 01:16:59,060\nWhy, I don't know.\nIt rang desperately true, and the first\n\n1039\n01:16:59,060 --> 01:17:05,880\nyarn, if you understand me, had been in a\nqueer way true also in spirit.\n\n1040\n01:17:05,880 --> 01:17:11,420\nThe fifteenth day of June was going to be a\nday of destiny, a bigger destiny than the\n\n1041\n01:17:11,420 --> 01:17:14,030\nkilling of a Dago.\n\n1042\n01:17:13,780 --> 01:17:18,469\nIt was so big that I didn't blame Scudder\nfor keeping me out of the game and wanting\n\n1043\n01:17:18,469 --> 01:17:23,100\nto play a lone hand.\nThat, I was pretty clear, was his\n\n1044\n01:17:23,100 --> 01:17:24,390\nintention.\n\n1045\n01:17:24,390 --> 01:17:29,049\nHe had told me something which sounded big\nenough, but the real thing was so\n\n1046\n01:17:29,049 --> 01:17:36,630\nimmortally big that he, the man who had\nfound it out, wanted it all for himself.\n\n1047\n01:17:36,630 --> 01:17:38,259\nI didn't blame him.\n\n1048\n01:17:38,259 --> 01:17:42,789\nIt was risks after all that he was chiefly\ngreedy about.\n\n1049\n01:17:42,789 --> 01:17:46,960\nThe whole story was in the notes--with\ngaps, you understand, which he would have\n\n1050\n01:17:46,960 --> 01:17:49,850\nfilled up from his memory.\n\n1051\n01:17:49,850 --> 01:17:54,970\nHe stuck down his authorities, too, and had\nan odd trick of giving them all a numerical\n\n1052\n01:17:54,970 --> 01:18:00,319\nvalue and then striking a balance, which\nstood for the reliability of each stage in\n\n1053\n01:18:00,319 --> 01:18:02,120\nthe yarn.\n\n1054\n01:18:02,120 --> 01:18:07,709\nThe four names he had printed were\nauthorities, and there was a man, Ducrosne,\n\n1055\n01:18:07,709 --> 01:18:15,359\nwho got five out of a possible five; and\nanother fellow, Ammersfoort, who got three.\n\n1056\n01:18:15,360 --> 01:18:20,250\nThe bare bones of the tale were all that\nwas in the book--these, and one queer\n\n1057\n01:18:20,250 --> 01:18:26,269\nphrase which occurred half a dozen times\ninside brackets.\n\n1058\n01:18:26,269 --> 01:18:31,250\n'(Thirty-nine steps)' was the phrase; and\nat its last time of use it ran--'(Thirty-\n\n1059\n01:18:31,250 --> 01:18:39,080\nnine steps, I counted them--high tide 10.17\np.m.)'.\n\n1060\n01:18:39,080 --> 01:18:42,280\nI could make nothing of that.\n\n1061\n01:18:42,280 --> 01:18:47,340\nThe first thing I learned was that it was\nno question of preventing a war.\n\n1062\n01:18:47,340 --> 01:18:52,709\nThat was coming, as sure as Christmas: had\nbeen arranged, said Scudder, ever since\n\n1063\n01:18:52,709 --> 01:18:55,670\nFebruary 1912.\n\n1064\n01:18:55,670 --> 01:19:00,750\nKarolides was going to be the occasion.\nHe was booked all right, and was to hand in\n\n1065\n01:19:00,750 --> 01:19:06,590\nhis checks on June 14th, two weeks and four\ndays from that May morning.\n\n1066\n01:19:06,590 --> 01:19:12,209\nI gathered from Scudder's notes that\nnothing on earth could prevent that.\n\n1067\n01:19:12,209 --> 01:19:17,659\nHis talk of Epirote guards that would skin\ntheir own grandmothers was all billy-o.\n\n1068\n01:19:18,739 --> 01:19:23,299\nThe second thing was that this war was\ngoing to come as a mighty surprise to\n\n1069\n01:19:23,299 --> 01:19:24,579\nBritain.\n\n1070\n01:19:24,329 --> 01:19:29,659\nKarolides' death would set the Balkans by\nthe ears, and then Vienna would chip in\n\n1071\n01:19:29,659 --> 01:19:33,890\nwith an ultimatum.\nRussia wouldn't like that, and there would\n\n1072\n01:19:33,890 --> 01:19:35,650\nbe high words.\n\n1073\n01:19:35,650 --> 01:19:41,760\nBut Berlin would play the peacemaker, and\npour oil on the waters, till suddenly she\n\n1074\n01:19:41,760 --> 01:19:49,380\nwould find a good cause for a quarrel, pick\nit up, and in five hours let fly at us.\n\n1075\n01:19:49,379 --> 01:19:53,500\nThat was the idea, and a pretty good one\ntoo.\n\n1076\n01:19:53,500 --> 01:19:58,159\nHoney and fair speeches, and then a stroke\nin the dark.\n\n1077\n01:19:58,159 --> 01:20:03,250\nWhile we were talking about the goodwill\nand good intentions of Germany our coast\n\n1078\n01:20:03,250 --> 01:20:08,680\nwould be silently ringed with mines, and\nsubmarines would be waiting for every\n\n1079\n01:20:08,680 --> 01:20:10,410\nbattleship.\n\n1080\n01:20:10,410 --> 01:20:16,090\nBut all this depended upon the third thing,\nwhich was due to happen on June 15th.\n\n1081\n01:20:16,090 --> 01:20:21,270\nI would never have grasped this if I hadn't\nonce happened to meet a French staff\n\n1082\n01:20:21,270 --> 01:20:27,490\nofficer, coming back from West Africa, who\nhad told me a lot of things.\n\n1083\n01:20:27,490 --> 01:20:31,870\nOne was that, in spite of all the nonsense\ntalked in Parliament, there was a real\n\n1084\n01:20:31,870 --> 01:20:36,590\nworking alliance between France and\nBritain, and that the two General Staffs\n\n1085\n01:20:36,590 --> 01:20:42,520\nmet every now and then, and made plans for\njoint action in case of war.\n\n1086\n01:20:42,520 --> 01:20:48,840\nWell, in June a very great swell was coming\nover from Paris, and he was going to get\n\n1087\n01:20:48,840 --> 01:20:54,139\nnothing less than a statement of the\ndisposition of the British Home Fleet on\n\n1088\n01:20:54,139 --> 01:20:55,190\nmobilization.\n\n1089\n01:20:55,190 --> 01:21:00,389\nAt least I gathered it was something like\nthat; anyhow, it was something uncommonly\n\n1090\n01:21:00,389 --> 01:21:01,590\nimportant.\n\n1091\n01:21:01,340 --> 01:21:07,680\nBut on the 15th day of June there were to\nbe others in London--others, at whom I\n\n1092\n01:21:07,680 --> 01:21:11,460\ncould only guess.\nScudder was content to call them\n\n1093\n01:21:11,460 --> 01:21:15,360\ncollectively the 'Black Stone'.\n\n1094\n01:21:15,360 --> 01:21:21,220\nThey represented not our Allies, but our\ndeadly foes; and the information, destined\n\n1095\n01:21:21,220 --> 01:21:26,080\nfor France, was to be diverted to their\npockets.\n\n1096\n01:21:26,080 --> 01:21:32,000\nAnd it was to be used, remember--used a\nweek or two later, with great guns and\n\n1097\n01:21:32,000 --> 01:21:38,530\nswift torpedoes, suddenly in the darkness\nof a summer night.\n\n1098\n01:21:38,530 --> 01:21:43,900\nThis was the story I had been deciphering\nin a back room of a country inn,\n\n1099\n01:21:43,900 --> 01:21:46,610\noverlooking a cabbage garden.\n\n1100\n01:21:46,360 --> 01:21:52,580\nThis was the story that hummed in my brain\nas I swung in the big touring-car from glen\n\n1101\n01:21:52,580 --> 01:21:54,770\nto glen.\n\n1102\n01:21:54,520 --> 01:21:59,210\nMy first impulse had been to write a letter\nto the Prime Minister, but a little\n\n1103\n01:21:59,210 --> 01:22:03,300\nreflection convinced me that that would be\nuseless.\n\n1104\n01:22:03,300 --> 01:22:05,050\nWho would believe my tale?\n\n1105\n01:22:05,050 --> 01:22:12,730\nI must show a sign, some token in proof,\nand Heaven knew what that could be.\n\n1106\n01:22:12,729 --> 01:22:18,580\nAbove all, I must keep going myself, ready\nto act when things got riper, and that was\n\n1107\n01:22:18,580 --> 01:22:24,360\ngoing to be no light job with the police of\nthe British Isles in full cry after me and\n\n1108\n01:22:24,360 --> 01:22:31,000\nthe watchers of the Black Stone running\nsilently and swiftly on my trail.\n\n1109\n01:22:31,000 --> 01:22:36,720\nI had no very clear purpose in my journey,\nbut I steered east by the sun, for I\n\n1110\n01:22:36,720 --> 01:22:41,080\nremembered from the map that if I went\nnorth I would come into a region of\n\n1111\n01:22:41,080 --> 01:22:45,099\ncoalpits and industrial towns.\n\n1112\n01:22:45,099 --> 01:22:50,949\nPresently I was down from the moorlands and\ntraversing the broad haugh of a river.\n\n1113\n01:22:50,949 --> 01:22:56,349\nFor miles I ran alongside a park wall, and\nin a break of the trees I saw a great\n\n1114\n01:22:56,349 --> 01:22:58,120\ncastle.\n\n1115\n01:22:58,120 --> 01:23:03,590\nI swung through little old thatched\nvillages, and over peaceful lowland\n\n1116\n01:23:03,590 --> 01:23:09,530\nstreams, and past gardens blazing with\nhawthorn and yellow laburnum.\n\n1117\n01:23:09,530 --> 01:23:14,569\nThe land was so deep in peace that I could\nscarcely believe that somewhere behind me\n\n1118\n01:23:14,569 --> 01:23:22,139\nwere those who sought my life; ay, and that\nin a month's time, unless I had the\n\n1119\n01:23:22,139 --> 01:23:25,770\nalmightiest of luck, these round country\n\n1120\n01:23:25,770 --> 01:23:34,050\nfaces would be pinched and staring, and men\nwould be lying dead in English fields.\n\n1121\n01:23:34,050 --> 01:23:40,389\nAbout mid-day I entered a long straggling\nvillage, and had a mind to stop and eat.\n\n1122\n01:23:40,389 --> 01:23:45,120\nHalf-way down was the Post Office, and on\nthe steps of it stood the postmistress and\n\n1123\n01:23:45,120 --> 01:23:49,320\na policeman hard at work conning a\ntelegram.\n\n1124\n01:23:49,319 --> 01:23:54,370\nWhen they saw me they wakened up, and the\npoliceman advanced with raised hand, and\n\n1125\n01:23:54,370 --> 01:23:59,009\ncried on me to stop.\nI nearly was fool enough to obey.\n\n1126\n01:23:59,009 --> 01:24:03,690\nThen it flashed upon me that the wire had\nto do with me; that my friends at the inn\n\n1127\n01:24:03,690 --> 01:24:09,210\nhad come to an understanding, and were\nunited in desiring to see more of me, and\n\n1128\n01:24:09,210 --> 01:24:11,940\nthat it had been easy enough for them to\n\n1129\n01:24:11,940 --> 01:24:18,169\nwire the description of me and the car to\nthirty villages through which I might pass.\n\n1130\n01:24:18,169 --> 01:24:21,640\nI released the brakes just in time.\n\n1131\n01:24:21,390 --> 01:24:26,180\nAs it was, the policeman made a claw at the\nhood, and only dropped off when he got my\n\n1132\n01:24:26,180 --> 01:24:31,350\nleft in his eye.\nI saw that main roads were no place for me,\n\n1133\n01:24:31,350 --> 01:24:33,900\nand turned into the byways.\n\n1134\n01:24:33,900 --> 01:24:38,900\nIt wasn't an easy job without a map, for\nthere was the risk of getting on to a farm\n\n1135\n01:24:38,900 --> 01:24:43,660\nroad and ending in a duck-pond or a stable-\nyard, and I couldn't afford that kind of\n\n1136\n01:24:43,660 --> 01:24:45,130\ndelay.\n\n1137\n01:24:45,130 --> 01:24:49,340\nI began to see what an ass I had been to\nsteal the car.\n\n1138\n01:24:49,340 --> 01:24:54,030\nThe big green brute would be the safest\nkind of clue to me over the breadth of\n\n1139\n01:24:54,030 --> 01:24:55,730\nScotland.\n\n1140\n01:24:55,730 --> 01:25:00,590\nIf I left it and took to my feet, it would\nbe discovered in an hour or two and I would\n\n1141\n01:25:00,590 --> 01:25:06,100\nget no start in the race.\nThe immediate thing to do was to get to the\n\n1142\n01:25:06,100 --> 01:25:08,310\nloneliest roads.\n\n1143\n01:25:08,310 --> 01:25:12,980\nThese I soon found when I struck up a\ntributary of the big river, and got into a\n\n1144\n01:25:12,980 --> 01:25:14,150\nglen with steep hills all about me, and a\ncorkscrew road at the end which climbed\n\n1145\n01:25:14,150 --> 01:25:16,460\nover a pass.\n\n1146\n01:25:16,460 --> 01:25:22,250\nHere I met nobody, but it was taking me too\nfar north, so I slewed east along a bad\n\n1147\n01:25:22,250 --> 01:25:27,550\ntrack and finally struck a big double-line\nrailway.\n\n1148\n01:25:27,550 --> 01:25:32,000\nAway below me I saw another broadish\nvalley, and it occurred to me that if I\n\n1149\n01:25:32,000 --> 01:25:36,770\ncrossed it I might find some remote inn to\npass the night.\n\n1150\n01:25:36,770 --> 01:25:41,960\nThe evening was now drawing in, and I was\nfuriously hungry, for I had eaten nothing\n\n1151\n01:25:41,960 --> 01:25:47,820\nsince breakfast except a couple of buns I\nhad bought from a baker's cart.\n\n1152\n01:25:47,820 --> 01:25:53,610\nJust then I heard a noise in the sky, and\nlo and behold there was that infernal\n\n1153\n01:25:53,610 --> 01:26:01,170\naeroplane, flying low, about a dozen miles\nto the south and rapidly coming towards me.\n\n1154\n01:26:01,170 --> 01:26:06,950\nI had the sense to remember that on a bare\nmoor I was at the aeroplane's mercy, and\n\n1155\n01:26:06,950 --> 01:26:11,600\nthat my only chance was to get to the leafy\ncover of the valley.\n\n1156\n01:26:11,600 --> 01:26:17,150\nDown the hill I went like blue lightning,\nscrewing my head round, whenever I dared,\n\n1157\n01:26:17,150 --> 01:26:22,880\nto watch that damned flying machine.\nSoon I was on a road between hedges, and\n\n1158\n01:26:22,880 --> 01:26:26,230\ndipping to the deep-cut glen of a stream.\n\n1159\n01:26:26,230 --> 01:26:30,740\nThen came a bit of thick wood where I\nslackened speed.\n\n1160\n01:26:30,740 --> 01:26:35,880\nSuddenly on my left I heard the hoot of\nanother car, and realized to my horror that\n\n1161\n01:26:35,880 --> 01:26:41,480\nI was almost up on a couple of gate-posts\nthrough which a private road debouched on\n\n1162\n01:26:41,480 --> 01:26:42,950\nthe highway.\n\n1163\n01:26:42,950 --> 01:26:47,400\nMy horn gave an agonized roar, but it was\ntoo late.\n\n1164\n01:26:47,400 --> 01:26:53,110\nI clapped on my brakes, but my impetus was\ntoo great, and there before me a car was\n\n1165\n01:26:53,110 --> 01:26:55,740\nsliding athwart my course.\n\n1166\n01:26:55,740 --> 01:26:59,140\nIn a second there would have been the deuce\nof a wreck.\n\n1167\n01:26:59,140 --> 01:27:04,050\nI did the only thing possible, and ran slap\ninto the hedge on the right, trusting to\n\n1168\n01:27:04,050 --> 01:27:06,080\nfind something soft beyond.\n\n1169\n01:27:06,080 --> 01:27:11,140\nBut there I was mistaken.\nMy car slithered through the hedge like\n\n1170\n01:27:11,140 --> 01:27:15,200\nbutter, and then gave a sickening plunge\nforward.\n\n1171\n01:27:15,200 --> 01:27:19,520\nI saw what was coming, leapt on the seat\nand would have jumped out.\n\n1172\n01:27:19,520 --> 01:27:24,310\nBut a branch of hawthorn got me in the\nchest, lifted me up and held me, while a\n\n1173\n01:27:24,310 --> 01:27:30,940\nton or two of expensive metal slipped below\nme, bucked and pitched, and then dropped\n\n1174\n01:27:30,940 --> 01:27:37,520\nwith an almighty smash fifty feet to the\nbed of the stream.\n\n1175\n01:27:37,520 --> 01:27:42,800\nSlowly that thorn let me go.\nI subsided first on the hedge, and then\n\n1176\n01:27:42,800 --> 01:27:45,240\nvery gently on a bower of nettles.\n\n1177\n01:27:45,240 --> 01:27:52,100\nAs I scrambled to my feet a hand took me by\nthe arm, and a sympathetic and badly scared\n\n1178\n01:27:52,100 --> 01:27:55,240\nvoice asked me if I were hurt.\n\n1179\n01:27:54,990 --> 01:28:00,670\nI found myself looking at a tall young man\nin goggles and a leather ulster, who kept\n\n1180\n01:28:00,670 --> 01:28:05,180\non blessing his soul and whinnying\napologies.\n\n1181\n01:28:05,180 --> 01:28:09,820\nFor myself, once I got my wind back, I was\nrather glad than otherwise.\n\n1182\n01:28:09,820 --> 01:28:15,510\nThis was one way of getting rid of the car.\n'My blame, Sir,' I answered him.\n\n1183\n01:28:15,510 --> 01:28:19,350\n'It's lucky that I did not add homicide to\nmy follies.\n\n1184\n01:28:19,350 --> 01:28:24,390\nThat's the end of my Scotch motor tour, but\nit might have been the end of my life.'\n\n1185\n01:28:24,390 --> 01:28:26,710\nHe plucked out a watch and studied it.\n\n1186\n01:28:26,710 --> 01:28:31,700\n'You're the right sort of fellow,' he said.\n'I can spare a quarter of an hour, and my\n\n1187\n01:28:31,700 --> 01:28:35,710\nhouse is two minutes off.\nI'll see you clothed and fed and snug in\n\n1188\n01:28:35,710 --> 01:28:36,190\nbed.\n\n1189\n01:28:36,190 --> 01:28:42,080\nWhere's your kit, by the way?\nIs it in the burn along with the car?'\n\n1190\n01:28:42,080 --> 01:28:46,110\n'It's in my pocket,' I said, brandishing a\ntoothbrush.\n\n1191\n01:28:46,110 --> 01:28:48,760\n'I'm a Colonial and travel light.'\n\n1192\n01:28:48,760 --> 01:28:52,950\n'A Colonial,' he cried.\n'By Gad, you're the very man I've been\n\n1193\n01:28:52,950 --> 01:28:56,450\npraying for.\nAre you by any blessed chance a Free\n\n1194\n01:28:56,450 --> 01:28:57,000\nTrader?'\n\n1195\n01:28:57,000 --> 01:29:02,380\n'I am,' said I, without the foggiest notion\nof what he meant.\n\n1196\n01:29:02,380 --> 01:29:05,980\nHe patted my shoulder and hurried me into\nhis car.\n\n1197\n01:29:05,980 --> 01:29:10,800\nThree minutes later we drew up before a\ncomfortable-looking shooting box set among\n\n1198\n01:29:10,800 --> 01:29:15,060\npine-trees, and he ushered me indoors.\n\n1199\n01:29:14,810 --> 01:29:20,050\nHe took me first to a bedroom and flung\nhalf a dozen of his suits before me, for my\n\n1200\n01:29:20,050 --> 01:29:23,500\nown had been pretty well reduced to rags.\n\n1201\n01:29:23,250 --> 01:29:29,100\nI selected a loose blue serge, which\ndiffered most conspicuously from my former\n\n1202\n01:29:29,100 --> 01:29:32,240\ngarments, and borrowed a linen collar.\n\n1203\n01:29:31,990 --> 01:29:36,440\nThen he haled me to the dining-room, where\nthe remnants of a meal stood on the table,\n\n1204\n01:29:36,440 --> 01:29:40,110\nand announced that I had just five minutes\nto feed.\n\n1205\n01:29:40,110 --> 01:29:44,740\n'You can take a snack in your pocket, and\nwe'll have supper when we get back.\n\n1206\n01:29:44,740 --> 01:29:50,330\nI've got to be at the Masonic Hall at eight\no'clock, or my agent will comb my hair.'\n\n1207\n01:29:50,330 --> 01:29:56,430\nI had a cup of coffee and some cold ham,\nwhile he yarned away on the hearth-rug.\n\n1208\n01:29:56,430 --> 01:30:03,420\n'You find me in the deuce of a mess, Mr--\nby-the-by, you haven't told me your name.\n\n1209\n01:30:03,420 --> 01:30:04,230\nTwisdon?\n\n1210\n01:30:04,230 --> 01:30:07,579\nAny relation of old Tommy Twisdon of the\nSixtieth?\n\n1211\n01:30:07,580 --> 01:30:13,160\nNo? Well, you see I'm Liberal Candidate for\nthis part of the world, and I had a meeting\n\n1212\n01:30:13,160 --> 01:30:19,790\non tonight at Brattleburn--that's my chief\ntown, and an infernal Tory stronghold.\n\n1213\n01:30:19,790 --> 01:30:24,760\nI had got the Colonial ex-Premier fellow,\nCrumpleton, coming to speak for me tonight,\n\n1214\n01:30:24,760 --> 01:30:29,300\nand had the thing tremendously billed and\nthe whole place ground-baited.\n\n1215\n01:30:30,140 --> 01:30:35,580\nThis afternoon I had a wire from the\nruffian saying he had got influenza at\n\n1216\n01:30:35,580 --> 01:30:39,750\nBlackpool, and here am I left to do the\nwhole thing myself.\n\n1217\n01:30:39,750 --> 01:30:44,350\nI had meant to speak for ten minutes and\nmust now go on for forty, and, though I've\n\n1218\n01:30:44,350 --> 01:30:49,410\nbeen racking my brains for three hours to\nthink of something, I simply cannot last\n\n1219\n01:30:49,410 --> 01:30:50,540\nthe course.\n\n1220\n01:30:50,540 --> 01:30:53,470\nNow you've got to be a good chap and help\nme.\n\n1221\n01:30:53,470 --> 01:30:58,820\nYou're a Free Trader and can tell our\npeople what a wash-out Protection is in the\n\n1222\n01:30:58,820 --> 01:30:59,520\nColonies.\n\n1223\n01:30:59,520 --> 01:31:04,540\nAll you fellows have the gift of the gab--I\nwish to Heaven I had it.\n\n1224\n01:31:04,540 --> 01:31:06,620\nI'll be for evermore in your debt.'\n\n1225\n01:31:07,550 --> 01:31:12,790\nI had very few notions about Free Trade one\nway or the other, but I saw no other chance\n\n1226\n01:31:12,790 --> 01:31:15,600\nto get what I wanted.\n\n1227\n01:31:15,350 --> 01:31:20,140\nMy young gentleman was far too absorbed in\nhis own difficulties to think how odd it\n\n1228\n01:31:20,140 --> 01:31:26,500\nwas to ask a stranger who had just missed\ndeath by an ace and had lost a 1,000-guinea\n\n1229\n01:31:26,500 --> 01:31:31,030\ncar to address a meeting for him on the\nspur of the moment.\n\n1230\n01:31:31,030 --> 01:31:36,790\nBut my necessities did not allow me to\ncontemplate oddnesses or to pick and choose\n\n1231\n01:31:36,790 --> 01:31:38,130\nmy supports.\n\n1232\n01:31:38,130 --> 01:31:42,870\n'All right,' I said.\n'I'm not much good as a speaker, but I'll\n\n1233\n01:31:42,870 --> 01:31:44,980\ntell them a bit about Australia.'\n\n1234\n01:31:46,120 --> 01:31:51,240\nAt my words the cares of the ages slipped\nfrom his shoulders, and he was rapturous in\n\n1235\n01:31:51,240 --> 01:31:53,089\nhis thanks.\n\n1236\n01:31:52,840 --> 01:31:57,640\nHe lent me a big driving coat--and never\ntroubled to ask why I had started on a\n\n1237\n01:31:57,640 --> 01:32:02,970\nmotor tour without possessing an ulster--\nand, as we slipped down the dusty roads,\n\n1238\n01:32:02,970 --> 01:32:07,180\npoured into my ears the simple facts of his\nhistory.\n\n1239\n01:32:07,180 --> 01:32:12,390\nHe was an orphan, and his uncle had brought\nhim up--I've forgotten the uncle's name,\n\n1240\n01:32:12,390 --> 01:32:17,000\nbut he was in the Cabinet, and you can read\nhis speeches in the papers.\n\n1241\n01:32:17,000 --> 01:32:21,630\nHe had gone round the world after leaving\nCambridge, and then, being short of a job,\n\n1242\n01:32:21,630 --> 01:32:26,900\nhis uncle had advised politics.\nI gathered that he had no preference in\n\n1243\n01:32:26,900 --> 01:32:28,030\nparties.\n\n1244\n01:32:28,030 --> 01:32:33,630\n'Good chaps in both,' he said cheerfully,\n'and plenty of blighters, too.\n\n1245\n01:32:33,630 --> 01:32:36,730\nI'm Liberal, because my family have always\nbeen Whigs.'\n\n1246\n01:32:37,650 --> 01:32:42,560\nBut if he was lukewarm politically he had\nstrong views on other things.\n\n1247\n01:32:42,560 --> 01:32:48,290\nHe found out I knew a bit about horses, and\njawed away about the Derby entries; and he\n\n1248\n01:32:48,290 --> 01:32:50,810\nwas full of plans for improving his\nshooting.\n\n1249\n01:32:50,809 --> 01:32:56,430\nAltogether, a very clean, decent, callow\nyoung man.\n\n1250\n01:32:56,430 --> 01:33:01,440\nAs we passed through a little town two\npolicemen signalled us to stop, and flashed\n\n1251\n01:33:01,440 --> 01:33:03,089\ntheir lanterns on us.\n\n1252\n01:33:03,089 --> 01:33:07,390\n'Beg pardon, Sir Harry,' said one.\n'We've got instructions to look out for a\n\n1253\n01:33:07,390 --> 01:33:11,380\ncar, and the description's no unlike\nyours.'\n\n1254\n01:33:11,380 --> 01:33:16,790\n'Right-o,' said my host, while I thanked\nProvidence for the devious ways I had been\n\n1255\n01:33:16,790 --> 01:33:19,660\nbrought to safety.\n\n1256\n01:33:19,410 --> 01:33:24,880\nAfter that he spoke no more, for his mind\nbegan to labour heavily with his coming\n\n1257\n01:33:24,880 --> 01:33:26,440\nspeech.\n\n1258\n01:33:26,190 --> 01:33:32,330\nHis lips kept muttering, his eye wandered,\nand I began to prepare myself for a second\n\n1259\n01:33:32,330 --> 01:33:35,690\ncatastrophe.\nI tried to think of something to say\n\n1260\n01:33:35,690 --> 01:33:40,310\nmyself, but my mind was dry as a stone.\n\n1261\n01:33:40,310 --> 01:33:44,750\nThe next thing I knew we had drawn up\noutside a door in a street, and were being\n\n1262\n01:33:44,750 --> 01:33:48,700\nwelcomed by some noisy gentlemen with\nrosettes.\n\n1263\n01:33:48,700 --> 01:33:54,730\nThe hall had about five hundred in it,\nwomen mostly, a lot of bald heads, and a\n\n1264\n01:33:54,730 --> 01:33:57,560\ndozen or two young men.\n\n1265\n01:33:57,310 --> 01:34:02,160\nThe chairman, a weaselly minister with a\nreddish nose, lamented Crumpleton's\n\n1266\n01:34:02,160 --> 01:34:08,530\nabsence, soliloquized on his influenza, and\ngave me a certificate as a 'trusted leader\n\n1267\n01:34:08,530 --> 01:34:10,360\nof Australian thought'.\n\n1268\n01:34:10,360 --> 01:34:16,700\nThere were two policemen at the door, and I\nhoped they took note of that testimonial.\n\n1269\n01:34:16,700 --> 01:34:20,910\nThen Sir Harry started.\nI never heard anything like it.\n\n1270\n01:34:20,910 --> 01:34:23,630\nHe didn't begin to know how to talk.\n\n1271\n01:34:23,630 --> 01:34:28,160\nHe had about a bushel of notes from which\nhe read, and when he let go of them he fell\n\n1272\n01:34:28,160 --> 01:34:31,570\ninto one prolonged stutter.\n\n1273\n01:34:31,320 --> 01:34:35,600\nEvery now and then he remembered a phrase\nhe had learned by heart, straightened his\n\n1274\n01:34:35,600 --> 01:34:40,510\nback, and gave it off like Henry Irving,\nand the next moment he was bent double and\n\n1275\n01:34:40,510 --> 01:34:42,930\ncrooning over his papers.\n\n1276\n01:34:42,930 --> 01:34:47,230\nIt was the most appalling rot, too.\n\n1277\n01:34:46,980 --> 01:34:52,260\nHe talked about the 'German menace', and\nsaid it was all a Tory invention to cheat\n\n1278\n01:34:52,260 --> 01:34:57,210\nthe poor of their rights and keep back the\ngreat flood of social reform, but that\n\n1279\n01:34:57,340 --> 01:35:03,510\n'organized labour' realized this and\nlaughed the Tories to scorn.\n\n1280\n01:35:03,510 --> 01:35:08,750\nHe was all for reducing our Navy as a proof\nof our good faith, and then sending Germany\n\n1281\n01:35:08,750 --> 01:35:14,659\nan ultimatum telling her to do the same or\nwe would knock her into a cocked hat.\n\n1282\n01:35:14,660 --> 01:35:19,300\nHe said that, but for the Tories, Germany\nand Britain would be fellow-workers in\n\n1283\n01:35:19,300 --> 01:35:24,130\npeace and reform.\nI thought of the little black book in my\n\n1284\n01:35:24,130 --> 01:35:24,930\npocket!\n\n1285\n01:35:24,930 --> 01:35:31,070\nA giddy lot Scudder's friends cared for\npeace and reform.\n\n1286\n01:35:31,070 --> 01:35:34,610\nYet in a queer way I liked the speech.\n\n1287\n01:35:34,360 --> 01:35:38,300\nYou could see the niceness of the chap\nshining out behind the muck with which he\n\n1288\n01:35:38,300 --> 01:35:42,750\nhad been spoon-fed.\nAlso it took a load off my mind.\n\n1289\n01:35:42,750 --> 01:35:47,890\nI mightn't be much of an orator, but I was\na thousand per cent better than Sir Harry.\n\n1290\n01:35:47,890 --> 01:35:51,270\nI didn't get on so badly when it came to my\nturn.\n\n1291\n01:35:51,270 --> 01:35:55,640\nI simply told them all I could remember\nabout Australia, praying there should be no\n\n1292\n01:35:55,640 --> 01:36:01,730\nAustralian there--all about its labour\nparty and emigration and universal service.\n\n1293\n01:36:01,730 --> 01:36:06,940\nI doubt if I remembered to mention Free\nTrade, but I said there were no Tories in\n\n1294\n01:36:06,940 --> 01:36:10,610\nAustralia, only Labour and Liberals.\n\n1295\n01:36:10,360 --> 01:36:14,770\nThat fetched a cheer, and I woke them up a\nbit when I started in to tell them the kind\n\n1296\n01:36:14,770 --> 01:36:19,630\nof glorious business I thought could be\nmade out of the Empire if we really put our\n\n1297\n01:36:19,630 --> 01:36:21,030\nbacks into it.\n\n1298\n01:36:21,030 --> 01:36:24,440\nAltogether I fancy I was rather a success.\n\n1299\n01:36:24,190 --> 01:36:28,930\nThe minister didn't like me, though, and\nwhen he proposed a vote of thanks, spoke of\n\n1300\n01:36:28,930 --> 01:36:35,350\nSir Harry's speech as 'statesmanlike' and\nmine as having 'the eloquence of an\n\n1301\n01:36:35,350 --> 01:36:38,260\nemigration agent'.\n\n1302\n01:36:38,260 --> 01:36:43,780\nWhen we were in the car again my host was\nin wild spirits at having got his job over.\n\n1303\n01:36:43,780 --> 01:36:49,350\n'A ripping speech, Twisdon,' he said.\n'Now, you're coming home with me.\n\n1304\n01:36:49,350 --> 01:36:53,870\nI'm all alone, and if you'll stop a day or\ntwo I'll show you some very decent\n\n1305\n01:36:53,870 --> 01:36:54,660\nfishing.'\n\n1306\n01:36:55,470 --> 01:37:01,380\nWe had a hot supper--and I wanted it pretty\nbadly--and then drank grog in a big cheery\n\n1307\n01:37:01,380 --> 01:37:06,490\nsmoking-room with a crackling wood fire.\nI thought the time had come for me to put\n\n1308\n01:37:06,490 --> 01:37:08,610\nmy cards on the table.\n\n1309\n01:37:08,610 --> 01:37:12,860\nI saw by this man's eye that he was the\nkind you can trust.\n\n1310\n01:37:12,860 --> 01:37:17,390\n'Listen, Sir Harry,' I said.\n'I've something pretty important to say to\n\n1311\n01:37:17,390 --> 01:37:18,130\nyou.\n\n1312\n01:37:18,130 --> 01:37:21,110\nYou're a good fellow, and I'm going to be\nfrank.\n\n1313\n01:37:21,110 --> 01:37:25,410\nWhere on earth did you get that poisonous\nrubbish you talked tonight?'\n\n1314\n01:37:25,410 --> 01:37:26,520\nHis face fell.\n\n1315\n01:37:26,520 --> 01:37:32,440\n'Was it as bad as that?' he asked ruefully.\n'It did sound rather thin.\n\n1316\n01:37:32,440 --> 01:37:37,880\nI got most of it out of the PROGRESSIVE\nMAGAZINE and pamphlets that agent chap of\n\n1317\n01:37:37,880 --> 01:37:39,330\nmine keeps sending me.\n\n1318\n01:37:39,330 --> 01:37:43,130\nBut you surely don't think Germany would\never go to war with us?'\n\n1319\n01:37:43,130 --> 01:37:48,370\n'Ask that question in six weeks and it\nwon't need an answer,' I said.\n\n1320\n01:37:48,370 --> 01:37:53,390\n'If you'll give me your attention for half\nan hour I am going to tell you a story.'\n\n1321\n01:37:55,070 --> 01:37:59,730\nI can see yet that bright room with the\ndeers' heads and the old prints on the\n\n1322\n01:37:59,730 --> 01:38:06,120\nwalls, Sir Harry standing restlessly on the\nstone curb of the hearth, and myself lying\n\n1323\n01:38:06,120 --> 01:38:08,850\nback in an armchair, speaking.\n\n1324\n01:38:08,850 --> 01:38:14,010\nI seemed to be another person, standing\naside and listening to my own voice, and\n\n1325\n01:38:14,010 --> 01:38:18,030\njudging carefully the reliability of my\ntale.\n\n1326\n01:38:18,030 --> 01:38:23,200\nIt was the first time I had ever told\nanyone the exact truth, so far as I\n\n1327\n01:38:23,200 --> 01:38:28,440\nunderstood it, and it did me no end of\ngood, for it straightened out the thing in\n\n1328\n01:38:28,440 --> 01:38:30,270\nmy own mind.\n\n1329\n01:38:30,270 --> 01:38:35,250\nI blinked no detail.\nHe heard all about Scudder, and the\n\n1330\n01:38:35,250 --> 01:38:39,520\nmilkman, and the note-book, and my doings\nin Galloway.\n\n1331\n01:38:39,520 --> 01:38:42,760\nPresently he got very excited and walked up\nand down the hearth-rug.\n\n1332\n01:38:42,760 --> 01:38:49,290\n'So you see,' I concluded, 'you have got\nhere in your house the man that is wanted\n\n1333\n01:38:49,290 --> 01:38:51,900\nfor the Portland Place murder.\n\n1334\n01:38:51,900 --> 01:38:56,170\nYour duty is to send your car for the\npolice and give me up.\n\n1335\n01:38:56,170 --> 01:38:58,650\nI don't think I'll get very far.\n\n1336\n01:38:58,400 --> 01:39:02,310\nThere'll be an accident, and I'll have a\nknife in my ribs an hour or so after\n\n1337\n01:39:02,310 --> 01:39:05,350\narrest.\nNevertheless, it's your duty, as a law-\n\n1338\n01:39:05,350 --> 01:39:06,490\nabiding citizen.\n\n1339\n01:39:06,490 --> 01:39:13,120\nPerhaps in a month's time you'll be sorry,\nbut you have no cause to think of that.'\n\n1340\n01:39:13,120 --> 01:39:16,720\nHe was looking at me with bright steady\neyes.\n\n1341\n01:39:16,720 --> 01:39:21,110\n'What was your job in Rhodesia, Mr Hannay?'\nhe asked.\n\n1342\n01:39:21,110 --> 01:39:26,450\n'Mining engineer,' I said.\n'I've made my pile cleanly and I've had a\n\n1343\n01:39:26,450 --> 01:39:28,350\ngood time in the making of it.'\n\n1344\n01:39:28,350 --> 01:39:32,300\n'Not a profession that weakens the nerves,\nis it?'\n\n1345\n01:39:32,300 --> 01:39:36,490\nI laughed.\n'Oh, as to that, my nerves are good\n\n1346\n01:39:36,490 --> 01:39:37,130\nenough.'\n\n1347\n01:39:37,130 --> 01:39:42,510\nI took down a hunting-knife from a stand on\nthe wall, and did the old Mashona trick of\n\n1348\n01:39:42,510 --> 01:39:49,420\ntossing it and catching it in my lips.\nThat wants a pretty steady heart.\n\n1349\n01:39:49,420 --> 01:39:51,230\nHe watched me with a smile.\n\n1350\n01:39:51,230 --> 01:39:55,950\n'I don't want proof.\nI may be an ass on the platform, but I can\n\n1351\n01:39:55,950 --> 01:40:00,320\nsize up a man.\nYou're no murderer and you're no fool, and\n\n1352\n01:40:00,320 --> 01:40:02,350\nI believe you are speaking the truth.\n\n1353\n01:40:02,350 --> 01:40:06,770\nI'm going to back you up.\nNow, what can I do?'\n\n1354\n01:40:06,770 --> 01:40:10,420\n'First, I want you to write a letter to\nyour uncle.\n\n1355\n01:40:10,420 --> 01:40:13,970\nI've got to get in touch with the\nGovernment people sometime before the 15th\n\n1356\n01:40:13,970 --> 01:40:17,340\nof June.'\nHe pulled his moustache.\n\n1357\n01:40:17,340 --> 01:40:19,730\n'That won't help you.\n\n1358\n01:40:19,730 --> 01:40:23,860\nThis is Foreign Office business, and my\nuncle would have nothing to do with it.\n\n1359\n01:40:23,860 --> 01:40:28,960\nBesides, you'd never convince him.\nNo, I'll go one better.\n\n1360\n01:40:28,960 --> 01:40:32,880\nI'll write to the Permanent Secretary at\nthe Foreign Office.\n\n1361\n01:40:32,880 --> 01:40:36,750\nHe's my godfather, and one of the best\ngoing.\n\n1362\n01:40:36,750 --> 01:40:38,330\nWhat do you want?'\n\n1363\n01:40:38,330 --> 01:40:41,700\nHe sat down at a table and wrote to my\ndictation.\n\n1364\n01:40:41,700 --> 01:40:46,520\nThe gist of it was that if a man called\nTwisdon (I thought I had better stick to\n\n1365\n01:40:46,520 --> 01:40:52,260\nthat name) turned up before June 15th he\nwas to entreat him kindly.\n\n1366\n01:40:52,260 --> 01:40:58,190\nHe said Twisdon would prove his bona fides\nby passing the word 'Black Stone' and\n\n1367\n01:40:58,190 --> 01:41:02,710\nwhistling 'Annie Laurie'.\n'Good,' said Sir Harry.\n\n1368\n01:41:02,710 --> 01:41:04,800\n'That's the proper style.\n\n1369\n01:41:04,800 --> 01:41:10,170\nBy the way, you'll find my godfather--his\nname's Sir Walter Bullivant--down at his\n\n1370\n01:41:10,170 --> 01:41:15,559\ncountry cottage for Whitsuntide.\nIt's close to Artinswell on the Kenner.\n\n1371\n01:41:15,559 --> 01:41:16,520\nThat's done.\n\n1372\n01:41:16,520 --> 01:41:20,580\nNow, what's the next thing?'\n'You're about my height.\n\n1373\n01:41:20,580 --> 01:41:24,400\nLend me the oldest tweed suit you've got.\n\n1374\n01:41:24,150 --> 01:41:27,770\nAnything will do, so long as the colour is\nthe opposite of the clothes I destroyed\n\n1375\n01:41:27,770 --> 01:41:31,540\nthis afternoon.\nThen show me a map of the neighbourhood and\n\n1376\n01:41:31,540 --> 01:41:34,690\nexplain to me the lie of the land.\n\n1377\n01:41:34,690 --> 01:41:40,400\nLastly, if the police come seeking me, just\nshow them the car in the glen.\n\n1378\n01:41:40,400 --> 01:41:44,390\nIf the other lot turn up, tell them I\ncaught the south express after your\n\n1379\n01:41:44,390 --> 01:41:46,100\nmeeting.'\n\n1380\n01:41:46,100 --> 01:41:50,020\nHe did, or promised to do, all these\nthings.\n\n1381\n01:41:50,020 --> 01:41:55,900\nI shaved off the remnants of my moustache,\nand got inside an ancient suit of what I\n\n1382\n01:41:55,900 --> 01:41:58,880\nbelieve is called heather mixture.\n\n1383\n01:41:58,880 --> 01:42:02,960\nThe map gave me some notion of my\nwhereabouts, and told me the two things I\n\n1384\n01:42:02,960 --> 01:42:08,140\nwanted to know--where the main railway to\nthe south could be joined and what were the\n\n1385\n01:42:08,140 --> 01:42:11,200\nwildest districts near at hand.\n\n1386\n01:42:11,200 --> 01:42:15,690\nAt two o'clock he wakened me from my\nslumbers in the smoking-room armchair, and\n\n1387\n01:42:15,690 --> 01:42:22,630\nled me blinking into the dark starry night.\nAn old bicycle was found in a tool-shed and\n\n1388\n01:42:22,630 --> 01:42:25,030\nhanded over to me.\n\n1389\n01:42:25,030 --> 01:42:28,920\n'First turn to the right up by the long\nfir-wood,' he enjoined.\n\n1390\n01:42:28,920 --> 01:42:35,350\n'By daybreak you'll be well into the hills.\nThen I should pitch the machine into a bog\n\n1391\n01:42:35,350 --> 01:42:37,890\nand take to the moors on foot.\n\n1392\n01:42:37,890 --> 01:42:41,480\nYou can put in a week among the shepherds,\nand be as safe as if you were in New\n\n1393\n01:42:41,480 --> 01:42:42,160\nGuinea.'\n\n1394\n01:42:41,910 --> 01:42:49,290\nI pedalled diligently up steep roads of\nhill gravel till the skies grew pale with\n\n1395\n01:42:49,290 --> 01:42:51,140\nmorning.\n\n1396\n01:42:50,890 --> 01:42:56,410\nAs the mists cleared before the sun, I\nfound myself in a wide green world with\n\n1397\n01:42:56,410 --> 01:43:01,179\nglens falling on every side and a far-away\nblue horizon.\n\n1398\n01:43:01,180 --> 01:43:09,140\nHere, at any rate, I could get early news\nof my enemies.\n\n1399\n01:43:11,000 --> 01:43:12,000\n>\n\n1400\n01:43:12,000 --> 01:43:21,430\nCHAPTER FIVE\nThe Adventure of the Spectacled Roadman\n\n1401\n01:43:22,900 --> 01:43:28,779\nI sat down on the very crest of the pass\nand took stock of my position.\n\n1402\n01:43:28,779 --> 01:43:33,060\nBehind me was the road climbing through a\nlong cleft in the hills, which was the\n\n1403\n01:43:33,060 --> 01:43:36,579\nupper glen of some notable river.\n\n1404\n01:43:36,579 --> 01:43:42,290\nIn front was a flat space of maybe a mile,\nall pitted with bog-holes and rough with\n\n1405\n01:43:42,290 --> 01:43:48,340\ntussocks, and then beyond it the road fell\nsteeply down another glen to a plain whose\n\n1406\n01:43:48,340 --> 01:43:53,000\nblue dimness melted into the distance.\n\n1407\n01:43:53,000 --> 01:43:58,830\nTo left and right were round-shouldered\ngreen hills as smooth as pancakes, but to\n\n1408\n01:43:58,830 --> 01:44:05,140\nthe south--that is, the left hand--there\nwas a glimpse of high heathery mountains,\n\n1409\n01:44:05,140 --> 01:44:07,850\nwhich I remembered from the map as the big\n\n1410\n01:44:07,850 --> 01:44:12,300\nknot of hill which I had chosen for my\nsanctuary.\n\n1411\n01:44:12,300 --> 01:44:17,640\nI was on the central boss of a huge upland\ncountry, and could see everything moving\n\n1412\n01:44:17,640 --> 01:44:19,670\nfor miles.\n\n1413\n01:44:19,670 --> 01:44:25,000\nIn the meadows below the road half a mile\nback a cottage smoked, but it was the only\n\n1414\n01:44:25,000 --> 01:44:29,070\nsign of human life.\nOtherwise there was only the calling of\n\n1415\n01:44:29,070 --> 01:44:33,540\nplovers and the tinkling of little streams.\n\n1416\n01:44:33,540 --> 01:44:38,950\nIt was now about seven o'clock, and as I\nwaited I heard once again that ominous beat\n\n1417\n01:44:38,950 --> 01:44:42,880\nin the air.\nThen I realized that my vantage-ground\n\n1418\n01:44:42,880 --> 01:44:45,960\nmight be in reality a trap.\n\n1419\n01:44:45,960 --> 01:44:51,049\nThere was no cover for a tomtit in those\nbald green places.\n\n1420\n01:44:51,049 --> 01:44:56,539\nI sat quite still and hopeless while the\nbeat grew louder.\n\n1421\n01:44:56,540 --> 01:44:59,590\nThen I saw an aeroplane coming up from the\neast.\n\n1422\n01:44:59,590 --> 01:45:03,930\nIt was flying high, but as I looked it\ndropped several hundred feet and began to\n\n1423\n01:45:03,930 --> 01:45:09,830\ncircle round the knot of hill in narrowing\ncircles, just as a hawk wheels before it\n\n1424\n01:45:09,830 --> 01:45:11,869\npounces.\n\n1425\n01:45:11,869 --> 01:45:18,640\nNow it was flying very low, and now the\nobserver on board caught sight of me.\n\n1426\n01:45:18,640 --> 01:45:23,730\nI could see one of the two occupants\nexamining me through glasses.\n\n1427\n01:45:23,730 --> 01:45:28,870\nSuddenly it began to rise in swift whorls,\nand the next I knew it was speeding\n\n1428\n01:45:28,870 --> 01:45:33,650\neastward again till it became a speck in\nthe blue morning.\n\n1429\n01:45:33,650 --> 01:45:36,889\nThat made me do some savage thinking.\n\n1430\n01:45:36,889 --> 01:45:41,849\nMy enemies had located me, and the next\nthing would be a cordon round me.\n\n1431\n01:45:41,849 --> 01:45:46,109\nI didn't know what force they could\ncommand, but I was certain it would be\n\n1432\n01:45:46,109 --> 01:45:47,730\nsufficient.\n\n1433\n01:45:47,730 --> 01:45:51,799\nThe aeroplane had seen my bicycle, and\nwould conclude that I would try to escape\n\n1434\n01:45:51,799 --> 01:45:55,359\nby the road.\nIn that case there might be a chance on the\n\n1435\n01:45:55,359 --> 01:45:58,059\nmoors to the right or left.\n\n1436\n01:45:58,059 --> 01:46:02,409\nI wheeled the machine a hundred yards from\nthe highway, and plunged it into a moss-\n\n1437\n01:46:02,409 --> 01:46:05,739\nhole, where it sank among pond-weed and\nwater-buttercups.\n\n1438\n01:46:07,669 --> 01:46:12,269\nThen I climbed to a knoll which gave me a\nview of the two valleys.\n\n1439\n01:46:12,269 --> 01:46:15,739\nNothing was stirring on the long white\nribbon that threaded them.\n\n1440\n01:46:15,739 --> 01:46:20,799\nI have said there was not cover in the\nwhole place to hide a rat.\n\n1441\n01:46:20,799 --> 01:46:26,129\nAs the day advanced it was flooded with\nsoft fresh light till it had the fragrant\n\n1442\n01:46:26,129 --> 01:46:28,769\nsunniness of the South African veld.\n\n1443\n01:46:28,769 --> 01:46:35,760\nAt other times I would have liked the\nplace, but now it seemed to suffocate me.\n\n1444\n01:46:35,760 --> 01:46:40,969\nThe free moorlands were prison walls, and\nthe keen hill air was the breath of a\n\n1445\n01:46:40,969 --> 01:46:43,889\ndungeon.\n\n1446\n01:46:43,889 --> 01:46:51,409\nI tossed a coin--heads right, tails left--\nand it fell heads, so I turned to the\n\n1447\n01:46:51,409 --> 01:46:54,999\nnorth.\nIn a little I came to the brow of the ridge\n\n1448\n01:46:54,999 --> 01:46:57,709\nwhich was the containing wall of the pass.\n\n1449\n01:46:57,709 --> 01:47:04,299\nI saw the highroad for maybe ten miles, and\nfar down it something that was moving, and\n\n1450\n01:47:04,299 --> 01:47:05,769\nthat I took to be a motor-car.\n\n1451\n01:47:06,889 --> 01:47:11,489\nBeyond the ridge I looked on a rolling\ngreen moor, which fell away into wooded\n\n1452\n01:47:11,489 --> 01:47:13,430\nglens.\n\n1453\n01:47:13,180 --> 01:47:18,829\nNow my life on the veld has given me the\neyes of a kite, and I can see things for\n\n1454\n01:47:18,829 --> 01:47:21,010\nwhich most men need a telescope ...\n\n1455\n01:47:22,529 --> 01:47:26,939\nAway down the slope, a couple of miles\naway, several men were advancing, like a\n\n1456\n01:47:26,939 --> 01:47:31,840\nrow of beaters at a shoot ...\nI dropped out of sight behind the sky-line.\n\n1457\n01:47:32,900 --> 01:47:37,030\nThat way was shut to me, and I must try the\nbigger hills to the south beyond the\n\n1458\n01:47:37,030 --> 01:47:38,900\nhighway.\n\n1459\n01:47:38,650 --> 01:47:43,500\nThe car I had noticed was getting nearer,\nbut it was still a long way off with some\n\n1460\n01:47:43,500 --> 01:47:46,650\nvery steep gradients before it.\n\n1461\n01:47:46,400 --> 01:47:52,450\nI ran hard, crouching low except in the\nhollows, and as I ran I kept scanning the\n\n1462\n01:47:52,450 --> 01:47:55,080\nbrow of the hill before me.\n\n1463\n01:47:54,840 --> 01:48:02,060\nWas it imagination, or did I see figures--\none, two, perhaps more--moving in a glen\n\n1464\n01:48:02,060 --> 01:48:04,979\nbeyond the stream?\n\n1465\n01:48:04,730 --> 01:48:09,570\nIf you are hemmed in on all sides in a\npatch of land there is only one chance of\n\n1466\n01:48:09,570 --> 01:48:13,320\nescape.\nYou must stay in the patch, and let your\n\n1467\n01:48:13,320 --> 01:48:16,780\nenemies search it and not find you.\n\n1468\n01:48:16,780 --> 01:48:23,730\nThat was good sense, but how on earth was I\nto escape notice in that table-cloth of a\n\n1469\n01:48:23,730 --> 01:48:24,710\nplace?\n\n1470\n01:48:24,450 --> 01:48:29,750\nI would have buried myself to the neck in\nmud or lain below water or climbed the\n\n1471\n01:48:29,750 --> 01:48:31,350\ntallest tree.\n\n1472\n01:48:31,100 --> 01:48:37,720\nBut there was not a stick of wood, the bog-\nholes were little puddles, the stream was a\n\n1473\n01:48:37,720 --> 01:48:41,980\nslender trickle.\nThere was nothing but short heather, and\n\n1474\n01:48:41,980 --> 01:48:45,240\nbare hill bent, and the white highway.\n\n1475\n01:48:45,240 --> 01:48:52,490\nThen in a tiny bight of road, beside a heap\nof stones, I found the roadman.\n\n1476\n01:48:52,490 --> 01:48:57,159\nHe had just arrived, and was wearily\nflinging down his hammer.\n\n1477\n01:48:57,160 --> 01:49:00,050\nHe looked at me with a fishy eye and\nyawned.\n\n1478\n01:49:00,050 --> 01:49:07,290\n'Confoond the day I ever left the herdin'!'\nhe said, as if to the world at large.\n\n1479\n01:49:07,290 --> 01:49:10,340\n'There I was my ain maister.\n\n1480\n01:49:10,340 --> 01:49:16,910\nNow I'm a slave to the Goavernment,\ntethered to the roadside, wi' sair een, and\n\n1481\n01:49:16,910 --> 01:49:18,530\na back like a suckle.'\n\n1482\n01:49:18,390 --> 01:49:25,170\nHe took up the hammer, struck a stone,\ndropped the implement with an oath, and put\n\n1483\n01:49:25,170 --> 01:49:29,000\nboth hands to his ears.\n'Mercy on me!\n\n1484\n01:49:29,000 --> 01:49:32,970\nMy heid's burstin'!' he cried.\n\n1485\n01:49:32,970 --> 01:49:39,840\nHe was a wild figure, about my own size but\nmuch bent, with a week's beard on his chin,\n\n1486\n01:49:39,840 --> 01:49:46,230\nand a pair of big horn spectacles.\n'I canna dae't,' he cried again.\n\n1487\n01:49:46,230 --> 01:49:49,260\n'The Surveyor maun just report me.\n\n1488\n01:49:49,260 --> 01:49:54,000\nI'm for my bed.'\nI asked him what was the trouble, though\n\n1489\n01:49:54,000 --> 01:50:00,240\nindeed that was clear enough.\n'The trouble is that I'm no sober.\n\n1490\n01:50:00,240 --> 01:50:06,780\nLast nicht my dochter Merran was waddit,\nand they danced till fower in the byre.\n\n1491\n01:50:06,780 --> 01:50:10,710\nMe and some ither chiels sat down to the\ndrinkin', and here I am.\n\n1492\n01:50:10,710 --> 01:50:16,050\nPeety that I ever lookit on the wine when\nit was red!'\n\n1493\n01:50:16,050 --> 01:50:21,550\nI agreed with him about bed.\n'It's easy speakin',' he moaned.\n\n1494\n01:50:21,550 --> 01:50:26,990\n'But I got a postcard yestreen sayin' that\nthe new Road Surveyor would be round the\n\n1495\n01:50:26,990 --> 01:50:28,310\nday.\n\n1496\n01:50:28,060 --> 01:50:32,930\nHe'll come and he'll no find me, or else\nhe'll find me fou, and either way I'm a\n\n1497\n01:50:32,930 --> 01:50:34,160\ndone man.\n\n1498\n01:50:33,910 --> 01:50:40,630\nI'll awa' back to my bed and say I'm no\nweel, but I doot that'll no help me, for\n\n1499\n01:50:40,630 --> 01:50:46,760\nthey ken my kind o' no-weel-ness.'\nThen I had an inspiration.\n\n1500\n01:50:46,760 --> 01:50:49,120\n'Does the new Surveyor know you?'\n\n1501\n01:50:49,120 --> 01:50:51,840\nI asked.\n'No him.\n\n1502\n01:50:51,840 --> 01:50:57,010\nHe's just been a week at the job.\nHe rins about in a wee motor-cawr, and wad\n\n1503\n01:50:57,010 --> 01:51:00,210\nspeir the inside oot o' a whelk.'\n\n1504\n01:51:00,210 --> 01:51:03,960\n'Where's your house?'\nI asked, and was directed by a wavering\n\n1505\n01:51:03,960 --> 01:51:09,030\nfinger to the cottage by the stream.\n'Well, back to your bed,' I said, 'and\n\n1506\n01:51:09,030 --> 01:51:10,330\nsleep in peace.\n\n1507\n01:51:10,330 --> 01:51:13,180\nI'll take on your job for a bit and see the\nSurveyor.'\n\n1508\n01:51:14,150 --> 01:51:19,620\nHe stared at me blankly; then, as the\nnotion dawned on his fuddled brain, his\n\n1509\n01:51:19,620 --> 01:51:23,040\nface broke into the vacant drunkard's\nsmile.\n\n1510\n01:51:23,040 --> 01:51:25,810\n'You're the billy,' he cried.\n\n1511\n01:51:25,810 --> 01:51:30,730\n'It'll be easy eneuch managed.\nI've finished that bing o' stanes, so you\n\n1512\n01:51:30,730 --> 01:51:34,400\nneedna chap ony mair this forenoon.\n\n1513\n01:51:34,150 --> 01:51:39,810\nJust take the barry, and wheel eneuch metal\nfrae yon quarry doon the road to mak\n\n1514\n01:51:39,810 --> 01:51:42,370\nanither bing the morn.\n\n1515\n01:51:42,120 --> 01:51:48,700\nMy name's Alexander Turnbull, and I've been\nseeven year at the trade, and twenty afore\n\n1516\n01:51:48,700 --> 01:51:51,610\nthat herdin' on Leithen Water.\n\n1517\n01:51:51,360 --> 01:51:57,720\nMy freens ca' me Ecky, and whiles Specky,\nfor I wear glesses, being waik i' the\n\n1518\n01:51:57,720 --> 01:52:01,759\nsicht.\nJust you speak the Surveyor fair, and ca'\n\n1519\n01:52:01,759 --> 01:52:04,749\nhim Sir, and he'll be fell pleased.\n\n1520\n01:52:04,749 --> 01:52:07,759\nI'll be back or mid-day.'\n\n1521\n01:52:07,509 --> 01:52:13,300\nI borrowed his spectacles and filthy old\nhat; stripped off coat, waistcoat, and\n\n1522\n01:52:13,300 --> 01:52:18,480\ncollar, and gave him them to carry home;\nborrowed, too, the foul stump of a clay\n\n1523\n01:52:18,480 --> 01:52:21,980\npipe as an extra property.\n\n1524\n01:52:21,980 --> 01:52:29,079\nHe indicated my simple tasks, and without\nmore ado set off at an amble bedwards.\n\n1525\n01:52:29,079 --> 01:52:34,089\nBed may have been his chief object, but I\nthink there was also something left in the\n\n1526\n01:52:34,089 --> 01:52:35,910\nfoot of a bottle.\n\n1527\n01:52:35,910 --> 01:52:40,939\nI prayed that he might be safe under cover\nbefore my friends arrived on the scene.\n\n1528\n01:52:40,939 --> 01:52:44,120\nThen I set to work to dress for the part.\n\n1529\n01:52:43,870 --> 01:52:48,930\nI opened the collar of my shirt--it was a\nvulgar blue-and-white check such as\n\n1530\n01:52:48,930 --> 01:52:53,910\nploughmen wear--and revealed a neck as\nbrown as any tinker's.\n\n1531\n01:52:53,910 --> 01:52:57,569\nI rolled up my sleeves, and there was a\nforearm which might have been a\n\n1532\n01:52:57,569 --> 01:53:02,269\nblacksmith's, sunburnt and rough with old\nscars.\n\n1533\n01:53:02,269 --> 01:53:07,029\nI got my boots and trouser-legs all white\nfrom the dust of the road, and hitched up\n\n1534\n01:53:07,029 --> 01:53:11,079\nmy trousers, tying them with string below\nthe knee.\n\n1535\n01:53:11,079 --> 01:53:13,980\nThen I set to work on my face.\n\n1536\n01:53:13,980 --> 01:53:19,199\nWith a handful of dust I made a water-mark\nround my neck, the place where Mr\n\n1537\n01:53:19,199 --> 01:53:23,139\nTurnbull's Sunday ablutions might be\nexpected to stop.\n\n1538\n01:53:23,149 --> 01:53:27,970\nI rubbed a good deal of dirt also into the\nsunburn of my cheeks.\n\n1539\n01:53:27,970 --> 01:53:33,639\nA roadman's eyes would no doubt be a little\ninflamed, so I contrived to get some dust\n\n1540\n01:53:33,639 --> 01:53:39,970\nin both of mine, and by dint of vigorous\nrubbing produced a bleary effect.\n\n1541\n01:53:39,970 --> 01:53:44,949\nThe sandwiches Sir Harry had given me had\ngone off with my coat, but the roadman's\n\n1542\n01:53:44,949 --> 01:53:49,199\nlunch, tied up in a red handkerchief, was\nat my disposal.\n\n1543\n01:53:49,199 --> 01:53:54,619\nI ate with great relish several of the\nthick slabs of scone and cheese and drank a\n\n1544\n01:53:54,619 --> 01:53:57,800\nlittle of the cold tea.\n\n1545\n01:53:57,550 --> 01:54:03,040\nIn the handkerchief was a local paper tied\nwith string and addressed to Mr Turnbull--\n\n1546\n01:54:03,040 --> 01:54:06,410\nobviously meant to solace his mid-day\nleisure.\n\n1547\n01:54:06,410 --> 01:54:12,069\nI did up the bundle again, and put the\npaper conspicuously beside it.\n\n1548\n01:54:12,069 --> 01:54:17,759\nMy boots did not satisfy me, but by dint of\nkicking among the stones I reduced them to\n\n1549\n01:54:17,759 --> 01:54:21,180\nthe granite-like surface which marks a\nroadman's foot-gear.\n\n1550\n01:54:22,660 --> 01:54:28,119\nThen I bit and scraped my finger-nails till\nthe edges were all cracked and uneven.\n\n1551\n01:54:28,119 --> 01:54:32,209\nThe men I was matched against would miss no\ndetail.\n\n1552\n01:54:32,209 --> 01:54:37,339\nI broke one of the bootlaces and retied it\nin a clumsy knot, and loosed the other so\n\n1553\n01:54:37,339 --> 01:54:41,629\nthat my thick grey socks bulged over the\nuppers.\n\n1554\n01:54:41,629 --> 01:54:43,800\nStill no sign of anything on the road.\n\n1555\n01:54:43,800 --> 01:54:48,290\nThe motor I had observed half an hour ago\nmust have gone home.\n\n1556\n01:54:48,290 --> 01:54:53,199\nMy toilet complete, I took up the barrow\nand began my journeys to and from the\n\n1557\n01:54:53,199 --> 01:54:55,600\nquarry a hundred yards off.\n\n1558\n01:54:55,600 --> 01:55:01,139\nI remember an old scout in Rhodesia, who\nhad done many queer things in his day, once\n\n1559\n01:55:01,139 --> 01:55:06,220\ntelling me that the secret of playing a\npart was to think yourself into it.\n\n1560\n01:55:06,220 --> 01:55:10,759\nYou could never keep it up, he said, unless\nyou could manage to convince yourself that\n\n1561\n01:55:10,759 --> 01:55:15,540\nyou were it.\nSo I shut off all other thoughts and\n\n1562\n01:55:15,540 --> 01:55:17,670\nswitched them on to the road-mending.\n\n1563\n01:55:17,670 --> 01:55:23,259\nI thought of the little white cottage as my\nhome, I recalled the years I had spent\n\n1564\n01:55:23,259 --> 01:55:29,869\nherding on Leithen Water, I made my mind\ndwell lovingly on sleep in a box-bed and a\n\n1565\n01:55:29,869 --> 01:55:32,589\nbottle of cheap whisky.\n\n1566\n01:55:32,589 --> 01:55:36,490\nStill nothing appeared on that long white\nroad.\n\n1567\n01:55:36,490 --> 01:55:39,790\nNow and then a sheep wandered off the\nheather to stare at me.\n\n1568\n01:55:39,790 --> 01:55:45,360\nA heron flopped down to a pool in the\nstream and started to fish, taking no more\n\n1569\n01:55:45,360 --> 01:55:49,620\nnotice of me than if I had been a\nmilestone.\n\n1570\n01:55:49,619 --> 01:55:55,889\nOn I went, trundling my loads of stone,\nwith the heavy step of the professional.\n\n1571\n01:55:55,889 --> 01:56:01,319\nSoon I grew warm, and the dust on my face\nchanged into solid and abiding grit.\n\n1572\n01:56:01,319 --> 01:56:05,920\nI was already counting the hours till\nevening should put a limit to Mr Turnbull's\n\n1573\n01:56:05,920 --> 01:56:09,459\nmonotonous toil.\n\n1574\n01:56:09,209 --> 01:56:14,059\nSuddenly a crisp voice spoke from the road,\nand looking up I saw a little Ford two-\n\n1575\n01:56:14,059 --> 01:56:17,699\nseater, and a round-faced young man in a\nbowler hat.\n\n1576\n01:56:17,699 --> 01:56:21,480\n'Are you Alexander Turnbull?' he asked.\n\n1577\n01:56:21,480 --> 01:56:27,470\n'I am the new County Road Surveyor.\nYou live at Blackhopefoot, and have charge\n\n1578\n01:56:27,470 --> 01:56:30,579\nof the section from Laidlawbyres to the\nRiggs?\n\n1579\n01:56:30,579 --> 01:56:31,379\nGood!\n\n1580\n01:56:31,379 --> 01:56:36,499\nA fair bit of road, Turnbull, and not badly\nengineered.\n\n1581\n01:56:36,499 --> 01:56:40,290\nA little soft about a mile off, and the\nedges want cleaning.\n\n1582\n01:56:40,290 --> 01:56:41,509\nSee you look after that.\n\n1583\n01:56:41,509 --> 01:56:45,040\nGood morning.\nYou'll know me the next time you see me.'\n\n1584\n01:56:45,040 --> 01:56:48,730\nClearly my get-up was good enough for the\ndreaded Surveyor.\n\n1585\n01:56:48,730 --> 01:56:53,839\nI went on with my work, and as the morning\ngrew towards noon I was cheered by a little\n\n1586\n01:56:53,839 --> 01:56:55,319\ntraffic.\n\n1587\n01:56:55,069 --> 01:57:00,129\nA baker's van breasted the hill, and sold\nme a bag of ginger biscuits which I stowed\n\n1588\n01:57:00,129 --> 01:57:03,929\nin my trouser-pockets against emergencies.\n\n1589\n01:57:03,679 --> 01:57:08,050\nThen a herd passed with sheep, and\ndisturbed me somewhat by asking loudly,\n\n1590\n01:57:08,050 --> 01:57:09,569\n'What had become o' Specky?'\n\n1591\n01:57:09,319 --> 01:57:18,439\n'In bed wi' the colic,' I replied, and the\nherd passed on ... just about mid-day a big\n\n1592\n01:57:18,439 --> 01:57:24,040\ncar stole down the hill, glided past and\ndrew up a hundred yards beyond.\n\n1593\n01:57:24,040 --> 01:57:28,470\nIts three occupants descended as if to\nstretch their legs, and sauntered towards\n\n1594\n01:57:28,470 --> 01:57:29,240\nme.\n\n1595\n01:57:28,989 --> 01:57:34,369\nTwo of the men I had seen before from the\nwindow of the Galloway inn--one lean,\n\n1596\n01:57:34,369 --> 01:57:38,629\nsharp, and dark, the other comfortable and\nsmiling.\n\n1597\n01:57:38,629 --> 01:57:44,910\nThe third had the look of a countryman--a\nvet, perhaps, or a small farmer.\n\n1598\n01:57:44,910 --> 01:57:50,160\nHe was dressed in ill-cut knickerbockers,\nand the eye in his head was as bright and\n\n1599\n01:57:50,160 --> 01:57:52,529\nwary as a hen's.\n\n1600\n01:57:52,529 --> 01:57:57,629\n'Morning,' said the last.\n'That's a fine easy job o' yours.'\n\n1601\n01:57:57,629 --> 01:58:02,569\nI had not looked up on their approach, and\nnow, when accosted, I slowly and painfully\n\n1602\n01:58:02,569 --> 01:58:07,779\nstraightened my back, after the manner of\nroadmen; spat vigorously, after the manner\n\n1603\n01:58:07,779 --> 01:58:12,629\nof the low Scot; and regarded them steadily\nbefore replying.\n\n1604\n01:58:12,629 --> 01:58:16,139\nI confronted three pairs of eyes that\nmissed nothing.\n\n1605\n01:58:16,139 --> 01:58:21,230\n'There's waur jobs and there's better,' I\nsaid sententiously.\n\n1606\n01:58:21,230 --> 01:58:28,110\n'I wad rather hae yours, sittin' a' day on\nyour hinderlands on thae cushions.\n\n1607\n01:58:28,110 --> 01:58:32,069\nIt's you and your muckle cawrs that wreck\nmy roads!\n\n1608\n01:58:32,069 --> 01:58:36,649\nIf we a' had oor richts, ye sud be made to\nmend what ye break.'\n\n1609\n01:58:37,689 --> 01:58:42,569\nThe bright-eyed man was looking at the\nnewspaper lying beside Turnbull's bundle.\n\n1610\n01:58:42,569 --> 01:58:46,869\n'I see you get your papers in good time,'\nhe said.\n\n1611\n01:58:46,869 --> 01:58:48,439\nI glanced at it casually.\n\n1612\n01:58:48,439 --> 01:58:52,569\n'Aye, in gude time.\nSeein' that that paper cam' out last\n\n1613\n01:58:52,569 --> 01:58:58,610\nSetterday I'm just Sax days late.'\nHe picked it up, glanced at the\n\n1614\n01:58:58,610 --> 01:59:01,869\nsuperscription, and laid it down again.\n\n1615\n01:59:01,869 --> 01:59:05,689\nOne of the others had been looking at my\nboots, and a word in German called the\n\n1616\n01:59:05,689 --> 01:59:11,269\nspeaker's attention to them.\n'You've a fine taste in boots,' he said.\n\n1617\n01:59:11,269 --> 01:59:14,149\n'These were never made by a country\nshoemaker.'\n\n1618\n01:59:14,149 --> 01:59:19,119\n'They were not,' I said readily.\n'They were made in London.\n\n1619\n01:59:19,119 --> 01:59:23,489\nI got them frae the gentleman that was here\nlast year for the shootin'.\n\n1620\n01:59:23,489 --> 01:59:28,399\nWhat was his name now?'\nAnd I scratched a forgetful head.\n\n1621\n01:59:28,399 --> 01:59:30,829\nAgain the sleek one spoke in German.\n\n1622\n01:59:30,829 --> 01:59:35,379\n'Let us get on,' he said.\n'This fellow is all right.'\n\n1623\n01:59:35,379 --> 01:59:40,860\nThey asked one last question.\n'Did you see anyone pass early this\n\n1624\n01:59:40,860 --> 01:59:41,529\nmorning?\n\n1625\n01:59:41,529 --> 01:59:45,230\nHe might be on a bicycle or he might be on\nfoot.'\n\n1626\n01:59:45,230 --> 01:59:49,649\nI very nearly fell into the trap and told a\nstory of a bicyclist hurrying past in the\n\n1627\n01:59:49,649 --> 01:59:50,549\ngrey dawn.\n\n1628\n01:59:50,549 --> 01:59:55,709\nBut I had the sense to see my danger.\nI pretended to consider very deeply.\n\n1629\n01:59:55,709 --> 02:00:02,199\n'I wasna up very early,' I said.\n'Ye see, my dochter was merrit last nicht,\n\n1630\n02:00:02,199 --> 02:00:04,610\nand we keepit it up late.\n\n1631\n02:00:04,610 --> 02:00:09,829\nI opened the house door about seeven and\nthere was naebody on the road then.\n\n1632\n02:00:09,829 --> 02:00:14,809\nSince I cam' up here there has just been\nthe baker and the Ruchill herd, besides you\n\n1633\n02:00:14,809 --> 02:00:16,189\ngentlemen.'\n\n1634\n02:00:16,189 --> 02:00:21,959\nOne of them gave me a cigar, which I smelt\ngingerly and stuck in Turnbull's bundle.\n\n1635\n02:00:21,959 --> 02:00:25,880\nThey got into their car and were out of\nsight in three minutes.\n\n1636\n02:00:25,880 --> 02:00:31,820\nMy heart leaped with an enormous relief,\nbut I went on wheeling my stones.\n\n1637\n02:00:31,820 --> 02:00:36,800\nIt was as well, for ten minutes later the\ncar returned, one of the occupants waving a\n\n1638\n02:00:36,800 --> 02:00:38,240\nhand to me.\n\n1639\n02:00:38,240 --> 02:00:44,670\nThose gentry left nothing to chance.\nI finished Turnbull's bread and cheese, and\n\n1640\n02:00:44,670 --> 02:00:49,590\npretty soon I had finished the stones.\nThe next step was what puzzled me.\n\n1641\n02:00:49,590 --> 02:00:53,570\nI could not keep up this roadmaking\nbusiness for long.\n\n1642\n02:00:53,570 --> 02:00:58,770\nA merciful Providence had kept Mr Turnbull\nindoors, but if he appeared on the scene\n\n1643\n02:00:58,770 --> 02:01:00,950\nthere would be trouble.\n\n1644\n02:01:00,950 --> 02:01:05,580\nI had a notion that the cordon was still\ntight round the glen, and that if I walked\n\n1645\n02:01:05,580 --> 02:01:09,130\nin any direction I should meet with\nquestioners.\n\n1646\n02:01:09,130 --> 02:01:11,680\nBut get out I must.\n\n1647\n02:01:11,680 --> 02:01:16,260\nNo man's nerve could stand more than a day\nof being spied on.\n\n1648\n02:01:16,260 --> 02:01:19,779\nI stayed at my post till five o'clock.\n\n1649\n02:01:19,530 --> 02:01:23,670\nBy that time I had resolved to go down to\nTurnbull's cottage at nightfall and take my\n\n1650\n02:01:23,670 --> 02:01:26,790\nchance of getting over the hills in the\ndarkness.\n\n1651\n02:01:26,790 --> 02:01:32,070\nBut suddenly a new car came up the road,\nand slowed down a yard or two from me.\n\n1652\n02:01:32,070 --> 02:01:37,770\nA fresh wind had risen, and the occupant\nwanted to light a cigarette.\n\n1653\n02:01:37,770 --> 02:01:42,380\nIt was a touring car, with the tonneau full\nof an assortment of baggage.\n\n1654\n02:01:42,380 --> 02:01:47,290\nOne man sat in it, and by an amazing chance\nI knew him.\n\n1655\n02:01:47,290 --> 02:01:52,390\nHis name was Marmaduke Jopley, and he was\nan offence to creation.\n\n1656\n02:01:52,390 --> 02:01:57,640\nHe was a sort of blood stockbroker, who did\nhis business by toadying eldest sons and\n\n1657\n02:01:57,640 --> 02:02:01,960\nrich young peers and foolish old ladies.\n\n1658\n02:02:01,960 --> 02:02:06,910\n'Marmie' was a familiar figure, I\nunderstood, at balls and polo-weeks and\n\n1659\n02:02:06,910 --> 02:02:09,210\ncountry houses.\n\n1660\n02:02:08,960 --> 02:02:13,950\nHe was an adroit scandal-monger, and would\ncrawl a mile on his belly to anything that\n\n1661\n02:02:13,950 --> 02:02:16,880\nhad a title or a million.\n\n1662\n02:02:16,630 --> 02:02:20,390\nI had a business introduction to his firm\nwhen I came to London, and he was good\n\n1663\n02:02:20,390 --> 02:02:24,620\nenough to ask me to dinner at his club.\n\n1664\n02:02:24,370 --> 02:02:28,810\nThere he showed off at a great rate, and\npattered about his duchesses till the\n\n1665\n02:02:28,810 --> 02:02:32,240\nsnobbery of the creature turned me sick.\n\n1666\n02:02:31,990 --> 02:02:37,110\nI asked a man afterwards why nobody kicked\nhim, and was told that Englishmen\n\n1667\n02:02:37,110 --> 02:02:40,350\nreverenced the weaker sex.\n\n1668\n02:02:40,100 --> 02:02:46,050\nAnyhow there he was now, nattily dressed,\nin a fine new car, obviously on his way to\n\n1669\n02:02:46,050 --> 02:02:48,880\nvisit some of his smart friends.\n\n1670\n02:02:48,630 --> 02:02:54,160\nA sudden daftness took me, and in a second\nI had jumped into the tonneau and had him\n\n1671\n02:02:54,160 --> 02:02:58,040\nby the shoulder.\n'Hullo, Jopley,' I sang out.\n\n1672\n02:02:58,040 --> 02:03:00,260\n'Well met, my lad!'\n\n1673\n02:03:00,260 --> 02:03:04,230\nHe got a horrid fright.\nHis chin dropped as he stared at me.\n\n1674\n02:03:04,230 --> 02:03:09,710\n'Who the devil are YOU?' he gasped.\n'My name's Hannay,' I said.\n\n1675\n02:03:09,710 --> 02:03:12,280\n'From Rhodesia, you remember.'\n\n1676\n02:03:12,280 --> 02:03:17,890\n'Good God, the murderer!' he choked.\n'Just so.\n\n1677\n02:03:17,890 --> 02:03:22,010\nAnd there'll be a second murder, my dear,\nif you don't do as I tell you.\n\n1678\n02:03:22,010 --> 02:03:23,640\nGive me that coat of yours.\n\n1679\n02:03:23,640 --> 02:03:27,960\nThat cap, too.'\nHe did as bid, for he was blind with\n\n1680\n02:03:27,960 --> 02:03:29,059\nterror.\n\n1681\n02:03:28,810 --> 02:03:34,360\nOver my dirty trousers and vulgar shirt I\nput on his smart driving-coat, which\n\n1682\n02:03:34,360 --> 02:03:40,180\nbuttoned high at the top and thereby hid\nthe deficiencies of my collar.\n\n1683\n02:03:40,180 --> 02:03:44,420\nI stuck the cap on my head, and added his\ngloves to my get-up.\n\n1684\n02:03:44,420 --> 02:03:48,250\nThe dusty roadman in a minute was\ntransformed into one of the neatest\n\n1685\n02:03:48,250 --> 02:03:50,480\nmotorists in Scotland.\n\n1686\n02:03:50,480 --> 02:03:56,770\nOn Mr Jopley's head I clapped Turnbull's\nunspeakable hat, and told him to keep it\n\n1687\n02:03:56,770 --> 02:04:00,850\nthere.\nThen with some difficulty I turned the car.\n\n1688\n02:04:00,850 --> 02:04:05,170\nMy plan was to go back the road he had\ncome, for the watchers, having seen it\n\n1689\n02:04:05,170 --> 02:04:10,350\nbefore, would probably let it pass\nunremarked, and Marmie's figure was in no\n\n1690\n02:04:10,350 --> 02:04:12,350\nway like mine.\n\n1691\n02:04:12,350 --> 02:04:17,910\n'Now, my child,' I said, 'sit quite still\nand be a good boy.\n\n1692\n02:04:17,910 --> 02:04:21,530\nI mean you no harm.\nI'm only borrowing your car for an hour or\n\n1693\n02:04:21,530 --> 02:04:22,010\ntwo.\n\n1694\n02:04:22,010 --> 02:04:28,660\nBut if you play me any tricks, and above\nall if you open your mouth, as sure as\n\n1695\n02:04:28,660 --> 02:04:31,990\nthere's a God above me I'll wring your\nneck.\n\n1696\n02:04:31,990 --> 02:04:32,950\nSAVEZ?'\n\n1697\n02:04:32,950 --> 02:04:37,710\nI enjoyed that evening's ride.\nWe ran eight miles down the valley, through\n\n1698\n02:04:37,710 --> 02:04:42,450\na village or two, and I could not help\nnoticing several strange-looking folk\n\n1699\n02:04:42,450 --> 02:04:45,230\nlounging by the roadside.\n\n1700\n02:04:45,230 --> 02:04:50,140\nThese were the watchers who would have had\nmuch to say to me if I had come in other\n\n1701\n02:04:50,140 --> 02:04:54,760\ngarb or company.\nAs it was, they looked incuriously on.\n\n1702\n02:04:54,760 --> 02:04:59,850\nOne touched his cap in salute, and I\nresponded graciously.\n\n1703\n02:04:59,850 --> 02:05:05,020\nAs the dark fell I turned up a side glen\nwhich, as I remember from the map, led into\n\n1704\n02:05:05,020 --> 02:05:08,440\nan unfrequented corner of the hills.\n\n1705\n02:05:08,440 --> 02:05:13,310\nSoon the villages were left behind, then\nthe farms, and then even the wayside\n\n1706\n02:05:13,310 --> 02:05:15,160\ncottage.\n\n1707\n02:05:14,910 --> 02:05:20,070\nPresently we came to a lonely moor where\nthe night was blackening the sunset gleam\n\n1708\n02:05:20,070 --> 02:05:22,740\nin the bog pools.\n\n1709\n02:05:22,490 --> 02:05:28,400\nHere we stopped, and I obligingly reversed\nthe car and restored to Mr Jopley his\n\n1710\n02:05:28,400 --> 02:05:31,710\nbelongings.\n'A thousand thanks,' I said.\n\n1711\n02:05:31,710 --> 02:05:34,130\n'There's more use in you than I thought.\n\n1712\n02:05:34,130 --> 02:05:39,400\nNow be off and find the police.'\nAs I sat on the hillside, watching the\n\n1713\n02:05:39,400 --> 02:05:45,520\ntail-light dwindle, I reflected on the\nvarious kinds of crime I had now sampled.\n\n1714\n02:05:45,520 --> 02:05:50,680\nContrary to general belief, I was not a\nmurderer, but I had become an unholy liar,\n\n1715\n02:05:50,680 --> 02:05:56,900\na shameless impostor, and a highwayman with\na marked taste for expensive motor-cars.\n\n1716\n02:06:02,000 --> 02:06:03,000\n>\n\n","markerStore":{"nextMarkerId":538,"markersById":{"0":{"range":{"start":{"row":131,"column":0},"end":{"row":131,"column":9}},"properties":{"type":"selection","editorId":16,"goalScreenRange":null,"autoscroll":false,"preserveFolds":true},"reversed":false,"tailed":true,"valid":true,"invalidate":"never","maintainHistory":true}},"version":2},"history":{"version":3,"nextCheckpointId":1,"undoStack":[],"redoStack":[]},"encoding":"utf8","filePath":"/Users/joegesualdo/code/node/vocabulary-context/videos-srt/Part1-TheThirty-NineStepsAudiobookbyJohnBuchan(Chs1-5)-b6_WiCV3B3c.en.srt","digestWhenLastPersisted":"9e387c252a4ebf26a16d40b67912531491004a73","preferredLineEnding":null,"deserializer":"TextBuffer","version":2},{"text":"1\n00:00:01,209 --> 00:00:08,040\nOur Mutual Friend by Charles Dickens\nCHAPTER 4\n\n2\n00:00:08,040 --> 00:00:09,090\nA RUNAWAY MATCH\n\n3\n00:00:10,990 --> 00:00:16,219\nCherubic Pa arose with as little noise as\npossible from beside majestic Ma, one\n\n4\n00:00:16,219 --> 00:00:21,699\nmorning early, having a holiday before him.\nPa and the lovely woman had a rather\n\n5\n00:00:21,699 --> 00:00:24,560\nparticular appointment to keep.\n\n6\n00:00:24,560 --> 00:00:27,789\nYet Pa and the lovely woman were not going\nout together.\n\n7\n00:00:27,789 --> 00:00:31,299\nBella was up before four, but had no bonnet\non.\n\n8\n00:00:31,300 --> 00:00:36,100\nShe was waiting at the foot of the stairs--\nwas sitting on the bottom stair, in fact--\n\n9\n00:00:36,100 --> 00:00:41,820\nto receive Pa when he came down, but her\nonly object seemed to be to get Pa well out\n\n10\n00:00:41,820 --> 00:00:42,989\nof the house.\n\n11\n00:00:42,989 --> 00:00:48,820\n'Your breakfast is ready, sir,' whispered\nBella, after greeting him with a hug, 'and\n\n12\n00:00:48,820 --> 00:00:54,070\nall you have to do, is, to eat it up and\ndrink it up, and escape.\n\n13\n00:00:54,070 --> 00:00:55,510\nHow do you feel, Pa?'\n\n14\n00:00:55,510 --> 00:01:01,780\n'To the best of my judgement, like a\nhousebreaker new to the business, my dear,\n\n15\n00:01:01,780 --> 00:01:06,960\nwho can't make himself quite comfortable\ntill he is off the premises.'\n\n16\n00:01:06,960 --> 00:01:11,299\nBella tucked her arm in his with a merry\nnoiseless laugh, and they went down to the\n\n17\n00:01:11,299 --> 00:01:16,040\nkitchen on tiptoe; she stopping on every\nseparate stair to put the tip of her\n\n18\n00:01:16,040 --> 00:01:18,710\nforefinger on her rosy lips, and then lay\n\n19\n00:01:18,710 --> 00:01:23,360\nit on his lips, according to her favourite\npetting way of kissing Pa.\n\n20\n00:01:23,360 --> 00:01:29,920\n'How do YOU feel, my love?' asked R. W., as\nshe gave him his breakfast.\n\n21\n00:01:29,920 --> 00:01:36,240\n'I feel as if the Fortune-teller was coming\ntrue, dear Pa, and the fair little man was\n\n22\n00:01:36,240 --> 00:01:43,729\nturning out as was predicted.'\n'Ho! Only the fair little man?' said her\n\n23\n00:01:43,729 --> 00:01:44,090\nfather.\n\n24\n00:01:44,090 --> 00:01:49,350\nBella put another of those finger-seals\nupon his lips, and then said, kneeling down\n\n25\n00:01:49,350 --> 00:01:53,680\nby him as he sat at table: 'Now, look here,\nsir.\n\n26\n00:01:53,680 --> 00:01:59,119\nIf you keep well up to the mark this day,\nwhat do you think you deserve?\n\n27\n00:01:59,119 --> 00:02:08,100\nWhat did I promise you should have, if you\nwere good, upon a certain occasion?'\n\n28\n00:02:08,100 --> 00:02:11,160\n'Upon my word I don't remember, Precious.\n\n29\n00:02:11,160 --> 00:02:16,540\nYes, I do, though.\nWasn't it one of these beau--tiful\n\n30\n00:02:16,540 --> 00:02:20,990\ntresses?' with his caressing hand upon her\nhair.\n\n31\n00:02:20,990 --> 00:02:24,840\n'Wasn't it, too!' returned Bella,\npretending to pout.\n\n32\n00:02:24,840 --> 00:02:26,470\n'Upon my word!\n\n33\n00:02:26,220 --> 00:02:31,310\nDo you know, sir, that the Fortune-teller\nwould give five thousand guineas (if it was\n\n34\n00:02:31,310 --> 00:02:35,700\nquite convenient to him, which it isn't)\nfor the lovely piece I have cut off for\n\n35\n00:02:35,700 --> 00:02:35,950\nyou?\n\n36\n00:02:35,890 --> 00:02:41,910\nYou can form no idea, sir, of the number of\ntimes he kissed quite a scrubby little\n\n37\n00:02:41,910 --> 00:02:45,230\npiece--in comparison--that I cut off for\nHIM.\n\n38\n00:02:45,230 --> 00:02:48,710\nAnd he wears it, too, round his neck, I can\ntell you!\n\n39\n00:02:48,710 --> 00:02:54,380\nNear his heart!' said Bella, nodding.\n'Ah! very near his heart!\n\n40\n00:02:54,380 --> 00:03:00,280\nHowever, you have been a good, good boy,\nand you are the best of all the dearest\n\n41\n00:03:00,280 --> 00:03:07,440\nboys that ever were, this morning, and\nhere's the chain I have made of it, Pa, and\n\n42\n00:03:07,440 --> 00:03:12,810\nyou must let me put it round your neck with\nmy own loving hands.'\n\n43\n00:03:12,810 --> 00:03:18,310\nAs Pa bent his head, she cried over him a\nlittle, and then said (after having stopped\n\n44\n00:03:18,310 --> 00:03:23,210\nto dry her eyes on his white waistcoat, the\ndiscovery of which incongruous circumstance\n\n45\n00:03:23,210 --> 00:03:27,880\nmade her laugh): 'Now, darling Pa, give me\n\n46\n00:03:27,880 --> 00:03:35,610\nyour hands that I may fold them together,\nand do you say after me:--My little Bella.'\n\n47\n00:03:35,610 --> 00:03:42,070\n'My little Bella,' repeated Pa.\n'I am very fond of you.'\n\n48\n00:03:42,070 --> 00:03:45,920\n'I am very fond of you, my darling,' said\nPa.\n\n49\n00:03:45,920 --> 00:03:49,790\n'You mustn't say anything not dictated to\nyou, sir.\n\n50\n00:03:49,790 --> 00:03:53,230\nYou daren't do it in your responses at\nChurch, and you mustn't do it in your\n\n51\n00:03:53,230 --> 00:03:58,760\nresponses out of Church.'\n'I withdraw the darling,' said Pa.\n\n52\n00:03:58,760 --> 00:04:01,250\n'That's a pious boy!\n\n53\n00:04:01,250 --> 00:04:07,770\nNow again:--You were always--'\n'You were always,' repeated Pa.\n\n54\n00:04:07,770 --> 00:04:11,910\n'A vexatious--'\n'No you weren't,' said Pa.\n\n55\n00:04:11,910 --> 00:04:16,639\n'A vexatious (do you hear, sir?), a\nvexatious, capricious, thankless,\n\n56\n00:04:16,639 --> 00:04:22,569\ntroublesome, Animal; but I hope you'll do\nbetter in the time to come, and I bless you\n\n57\n00:04:22,569 --> 00:04:23,590\nand forgive you!'\n\n58\n00:04:23,590 --> 00:04:27,680\nHere, she quite forgot that it was Pa's\nturn to make the responses, and clung to\n\n59\n00:04:27,680 --> 00:04:28,419\nhis neck.\n\n60\n00:04:28,169 --> 00:04:34,439\n'Dear Pa, if you knew how much I think this\nmorning of what you told me once, about the\n\n61\n00:04:34,439 --> 00:04:39,979\nfirst time of our seeing old Mr Harmon,\nwhen I stamped and screamed and beat you\n\n62\n00:04:39,979 --> 00:04:42,120\nwith my detestable little bonnet!\n\n63\n00:04:42,120 --> 00:04:46,400\nI feel as if I had been stamping and\nscreaming and beating you with my hateful\n\n64\n00:04:46,400 --> 00:04:50,590\nlittle bonnet, ever since I was born,\ndarling!'\n\n65\n00:04:50,590 --> 00:04:51,909\n'Nonsense, my love.\n\n66\n00:04:51,909 --> 00:04:58,120\nAnd as to your bonnets, they have always\nbeen nice bonnets, for they have always\n\n67\n00:04:58,120 --> 00:05:03,539\nbecome you--or you have become them;\nperhaps it was that--at every age.'\n\n68\n00:05:03,539 --> 00:05:10,810\n'Did I hurt you much, poor little Pa?'\nasked Bella, laughing (notwithstanding her\n\n69\n00:05:10,810 --> 00:05:15,830\nrepentance), with fantastic pleasure in the\npicture, 'when I beat you with my bonnet?'\n\n70\n00:05:15,830 --> 00:05:17,770\n'No, my child.\n\n71\n00:05:17,770 --> 00:05:23,550\nWouldn't have hurt a fly!'\n'Ay, but I am afraid I shouldn't have beat\n\n72\n00:05:23,550 --> 00:05:27,840\nyou at all, unless I had meant to hurt\nyou,' said Bella.\n\n73\n00:05:27,840 --> 00:05:30,419\n'Did I pinch your legs, Pa?'\n\n74\n00:05:30,419 --> 00:05:35,099\n'Not much, my dear; but I think it's almost\ntime I--'\n\n75\n00:05:35,099 --> 00:05:39,979\n'Oh, yes!' cried Bella.\n'If I go on chattering, you'll be taken\n\n76\n00:05:39,979 --> 00:05:40,919\nalive.\n\n77\n00:05:40,919 --> 00:05:43,990\nFly, Pa, fly!'\n\n78\n00:05:43,740 --> 00:05:49,439\nSo, they went softly up the kitchen stairs\non tiptoe, and Bella with her light hand\n\n79\n00:05:49,439 --> 00:05:54,460\nsoftly removed the fastenings of the house\ndoor, and Pa, having received a parting\n\n80\n00:05:54,460 --> 00:05:56,509\nhug, made off.\n\n81\n00:05:56,509 --> 00:05:59,479\nWhen he had gone a little way, he looked\nback.\n\n82\n00:05:59,479 --> 00:06:04,219\nUpon which, Bella set another of those\nfinger seals upon the air, and thrust out\n\n83\n00:06:04,219 --> 00:06:06,909\nher little foot expressive of the mark.\n\n84\n00:06:06,909 --> 00:06:12,210\nPa, in appropriate action, expressed\nfidelity to the mark, and made off as fast\n\n85\n00:06:12,210 --> 00:06:14,589\nas he could go.\n\n86\n00:06:14,340 --> 00:06:18,499\nBella walked thoughtfully in the garden for\nan hour and more, and then, returning to\n\n87\n00:06:18,499 --> 00:06:23,360\nthe bedroom where Lavvy the Irrepressible\nstill slumbered, put on a little bonnet of\n\n88\n00:06:23,360 --> 00:06:28,370\nquiet, but on the whole of sly appearance,\nwhich she had yesterday made.\n\n89\n00:06:28,370 --> 00:06:34,789\n'I am going for a walk, Lavvy,' she said,\nas she stooped down and kissed her.\n\n90\n00:06:34,789 --> 00:06:38,699\nThe Irrepressible, with a bounce in the\nbed, and a remark that it wasn't time to\n\n91\n00:06:38,699 --> 00:06:43,979\nget up yet, relapsed into unconsciousness,\nif she had come out of it.\n\n92\n00:06:43,979 --> 00:06:48,569\nBehold Bella tripping along the streets,\nthe dearest girl afoot under the summer\n\n93\n00:06:48,569 --> 00:06:50,149\nsun!\n\n94\n00:06:49,900 --> 00:06:54,599\nBehold Pa waiting for Bella behind a pump,\nat least three miles from the parental\n\n95\n00:06:54,599 --> 00:06:58,620\nroof-tree.\nBehold Bella and Pa aboard an early\n\n96\n00:06:58,620 --> 00:07:00,300\nsteamboat for Greenwich.\n\n97\n00:07:00,300 --> 00:07:04,960\nWere they expected at Greenwich?\nProbably.\n\n98\n00:07:04,960 --> 00:07:09,779\nAt least, Mr John Rokesmith was on the pier\nlooking out, about a couple of hours before\n\n99\n00:07:09,779 --> 00:07:16,139\nthe coaly (but to him gold-dusty) little\nsteamboat got her steam up in London.\n\n100\n00:07:16,139 --> 00:07:17,360\nProbably.\n\n101\n00:07:17,360 --> 00:07:21,050\nAt least, Mr John Rokesmith seemed\nperfectly satisfied when he descried them\n\n102\n00:07:21,050 --> 00:07:22,789\non board.\nProbably.\n\n103\n00:07:22,789 --> 00:07:28,270\nAt least, Bella no sooner stepped ashore\nthan she took Mr John Rokesmith's arm,\n\n104\n00:07:28,270 --> 00:07:32,870\nwithout evincing surprise, and the two\nwalked away together with an ethereal air\n\n105\n00:07:32,870 --> 00:07:35,749\nof happiness which, as it were, wafted up\n\n106\n00:07:35,749 --> 00:07:41,690\nfrom the earth and drew after them a gruff\nand glum old pensioner to see it out.\n\n107\n00:07:41,699 --> 00:07:46,819\nTwo wooden legs had this gruff and glum old\npensioner, and, a minute before Bella\n\n108\n00:07:46,819 --> 00:07:51,069\nstepped out of the boat, and drew that\nconfiding little arm of hers through\n\n109\n00:07:51,069 --> 00:07:57,059\nRokesmith's, he had had no object in life\nbut tobacco, and not enough of that.\n\n110\n00:07:57,059 --> 00:08:02,349\nStranded was Gruff and Glum in a harbour of\neverlasting mud, when all in an instant\n\n111\n00:08:02,349 --> 00:08:05,460\nBella floated him, and away he went.\n\n112\n00:08:05,460 --> 00:08:10,999\nSay, cherubic parent taking the lead, in\nwhat direction do we steer first?\n\n113\n00:08:10,999 --> 00:08:15,960\nWith some such inquiry in his thoughts,\nGruff and Glum, stricken by so sudden an\n\n114\n00:08:15,960 --> 00:08:20,299\ninterest that he perked his neck and looked\nover the intervening people, as if he were\n\n115\n00:08:20,300 --> 00:08:25,309\ntrying to stand on tiptoe with his two\nwooden legs, took an observation of R. W.\n\n116\n00:08:26,279 --> 00:08:32,440\nThere was no 'first' in the case, Gruff and\nGlum made out; the cherubic parent was\n\n117\n00:08:32,440 --> 00:08:37,650\nbearing down and crowding on direct for\nGreenwich church, to see his relations.\n\n118\n00:08:37,650 --> 00:08:42,640\nFor, Gruff and Glum, though most events\nacted on him simply as tobacco-stoppers,\n\n119\n00:08:42,640 --> 00:08:47,910\npressing down and condensing the quids\nwithin him, might be imagined to trace a\n\n120\n00:08:47,910 --> 00:08:50,420\nfamily resemblance between the cherubs in\n\n121\n00:08:50,420 --> 00:08:54,720\nthe church architecture, and the cherub in\nthe white waistcoat.\n\n122\n00:08:54,720 --> 00:08:59,650\nSome remembrance of old Valentines, wherein\na cherub, less appropriately attired for a\n\n123\n00:08:59,650 --> 00:09:04,699\nproverbially uncertain climate, had been\nseen conducting lovers to the altar, might\n\n124\n00:09:04,700 --> 00:09:08,990\nhave been fancied to inflame the ardour of\nhis timber toes.\n\n125\n00:09:08,990 --> 00:09:14,570\nBe it as it might, he gave his moorings the\nslip, and followed in chase.\n\n126\n00:09:14,570 --> 00:09:20,720\nThe cherub went before, all beaming smiles;\nBella and John Rokesmith followed; Gruff\n\n127\n00:09:20,720 --> 00:09:23,270\nand Glum stuck to them like wax.\n\n128\n00:09:23,020 --> 00:09:28,580\nFor years, the wings of his mind had gone\nto look after the legs of his body; but\n\n129\n00:09:28,580 --> 00:09:33,080\nBella had brought them back for him per\nsteamer, and they were spread again.\n\n130\n00:09:33,090 --> 00:09:37,430\nHe was a slow sailer on a wind of\nhappiness, but he took a cross cut for the\n\n131\n00:09:37,430 --> 00:09:41,980\nrendezvous, and pegged away as if he were\nscoring furiously at cribbage.\n\n132\n00:09:41,980 --> 00:09:46,600\nWhen the shadow of the church-porch\nswallowed them up, victorious Gruff and\n\n133\n00:09:46,600 --> 00:09:50,710\nGlum likewise presented himself to be\nswallowed up.\n\n134\n00:09:50,710 --> 00:09:55,450\nAnd by this time the cherubic parent was so\nfearful of surprise, that, but for the two\n\n135\n00:09:55,450 --> 00:10:00,370\nwooden legs on which Gruff and Glum was\nreassuringly mounted, his conscience might\n\n136\n00:10:00,370 --> 00:10:02,520\nhave introduced, in the person of that\n\n137\n00:10:02,520 --> 00:10:08,400\npensioner, his own stately lady disguised,\narrived at Greenwich in a car and griffins,\n\n138\n00:10:08,400 --> 00:10:12,720\nlike the spiteful Fairy at the christenings\nof the Princesses, to do something dreadful\n\n139\n00:10:12,720 --> 00:10:14,820\nto the marriage service.\n\n140\n00:10:14,820 --> 00:10:19,990\nAnd truly he had a momentary reason to be\npale of face, and to whisper to Bella, 'You\n\n141\n00:10:19,990 --> 00:10:26,430\ndon't think that can be your Ma; do you, my\ndear?' on account of a mysterious rustling\n\n142\n00:10:26,430 --> 00:10:28,550\nand a stealthy movement somewhere in the\n\n143\n00:10:28,550 --> 00:10:33,780\nremote neighbourhood of the organ, though\nit was gone directly and was heard no more.\n\n144\n00:10:33,780 --> 00:10:37,760\nAlbeit it was heard of afterwards, as will\nafterwards be read in this veracious\n\n145\n00:10:37,760 --> 00:10:40,260\nregister of marriage.\n\n146\n00:10:40,260 --> 00:10:45,190\nWho taketh?\nI, John, and so do I, Bella.\n\n147\n00:10:45,190 --> 00:10:46,330\nWho giveth?\n\n148\n00:10:46,080 --> 00:10:52,450\nI, R. W. Forasmuch, Gruff and Glum, as John\nand Bella have consented together in holy\n\n149\n00:10:52,450 --> 00:10:57,240\nwedlock, you may (in short) consider it\ndone, and withdraw your two wooden legs\n\n150\n00:10:57,240 --> 00:10:58,470\nfrom this temple.\n\n151\n00:10:58,470 --> 00:11:03,260\nTo the foregoing purport, the Minister\nspeaking, as directed by the Rubric, to the\n\n152\n00:11:03,260 --> 00:11:08,630\nPeople, selectly represented in the present\ninstance by G. and G. above mentioned.\n\n153\n00:11:08,630 --> 00:11:14,480\nAnd now, the church-porch having swallowed\nup Bella Wilfer for ever and ever, had it\n\n154\n00:11:14,480 --> 00:11:19,250\nnot in its power to relinquish that young\nwoman, but slid into the happy sunlight,\n\n155\n00:11:19,250 --> 00:11:22,010\nMrs John Rokesmith instead.\n\n156\n00:11:22,010 --> 00:11:26,570\nAnd long on the bright steps stood Gruff\nand Glum, looking after the pretty bride,\n\n157\n00:11:26,570 --> 00:11:30,690\nwith a narcotic consciousness of having\ndreamed a dream.\n\n158\n00:11:30,690 --> 00:11:34,950\nAfter which, Bella took out from her pocket\na little letter, and read it aloud to Pa\n\n159\n00:11:34,950 --> 00:11:38,960\nand John; this being a true copy of the\nsame.\n\n160\n00:11:38,960 --> 00:11:41,450\n'DEAREST MA,\n\n161\n00:11:41,450 --> 00:11:46,840\nI hope you won't be angry, but I am most\nhappily married to Mr John Rokesmith, who\n\n162\n00:11:46,840 --> 00:11:52,110\nloves me better than I can ever deserve,\nexcept by loving him with all my heart.\n\n163\n00:11:52,110 --> 00:11:55,770\nI thought it best not to mention it\nbeforehand, in case it should cause any\n\n164\n00:11:55,770 --> 00:11:59,050\nlittle difference at home.\nPlease tell darling Pa.\n\n165\n00:11:59,050 --> 00:12:01,330\nWith love to Lavvy,\n\n166\n00:12:01,330 --> 00:12:06,850\nEver dearest Ma, Your affectionate\ndaughter, BELLA (P.S.--Rokesmith).'\n\n167\n00:12:06,850 --> 00:12:11,700\nThen, John Rokesmith put the queen's\ncountenance on the letter--when had Her\n\n168\n00:12:11,700 --> 00:12:16,440\nGracious Majesty looked so benign as on\nthat blessed morning!--and then Bella\n\n169\n00:12:16,440 --> 00:12:18,480\npopped it into the post-office, and said\n\n170\n00:12:18,480 --> 00:12:24,500\nmerrily, 'Now, dearest Pa, you are safe,\nand will never be taken alive!'\n\n171\n00:12:24,500 --> 00:12:31,140\nPa was, at first, in the stirred depths of\nhis conscience, so far from sure of being\n\n172\n00:12:31,140 --> 00:12:36,350\nsafe yet, that he made out majestic matrons\nlurking in ambush among the harmless trees\n\n173\n00:12:36,350 --> 00:12:38,580\nof Greenwich Park, and seemed to see a\n\n174\n00:12:38,580 --> 00:12:43,300\nstately countenance tied up in a well-known\npocket-handkerchief glooming down at him\n\n175\n00:12:43,300 --> 00:12:47,750\nfrom a window of the Observatory, where the\nFamiliars of the Astronomer Royal nightly\n\n176\n00:12:47,750 --> 00:12:49,750\noutwatch the winking stars.\n\n177\n00:12:49,750 --> 00:12:55,720\nBut, the minutes passing on and no Mrs\nWilfer in the flesh appearing, he became\n\n178\n00:12:55,720 --> 00:13:00,590\nmore confident, and so repaired with good\nheart and appetite to Mr and Mrs John\n\n179\n00:13:00,590 --> 00:13:04,440\nRokesmith's cottage on Blackheath, where\nbreakfast was ready.\n\n180\n00:13:04,440 --> 00:13:09,200\nA modest little cottage but a bright and a\nfresh, and on the snowy tablecloth the\n\n181\n00:13:09,200 --> 00:13:11,350\nprettiest of little breakfasts.\n\n182\n00:13:11,350 --> 00:13:16,310\nIn waiting, too, like an attendant summer\nbreeze, a fluttering young damsel, all pink\n\n183\n00:13:16,310 --> 00:13:20,740\nand ribbons, blushing as if she had been\nmarried instead of Bella, and yet asserting\n\n184\n00:13:20,740 --> 00:13:23,200\nthe triumph of her sex over both John and\n\n185\n00:13:23,200 --> 00:13:28,870\nPa, in an exulting and exalted flurry: as\nwho should say, 'This is what you must all\n\n186\n00:13:28,870 --> 00:13:31,960\ncome to, gentlemen, when we choose to bring\nyou to book.'\n\n187\n00:13:31,960 --> 00:13:37,530\nThis same young damsel was Bella's serving-\nmaid, and unto her did deliver a bunch of\n\n188\n00:13:37,530 --> 00:13:43,050\nkeys, commanding treasures in the way of\ndry-saltery, groceries, jams and pickles,\n\n189\n00:13:43,050 --> 00:13:45,450\nthe investigation of which made pastime\n\n190\n00:13:45,450 --> 00:13:51,670\nafter breakfast, when Bella declared that\n'Pa must taste everything, John dear, or it\n\n191\n00:13:51,670 --> 00:13:56,700\nwill never be lucky,' and when Pa had all\nsorts of things poked into his mouth, and\n\n192\n00:13:56,700 --> 00:13:59,360\ndidn't quite know what to do with them when\nthey were put there.\n\n193\n00:13:59,360 --> 00:14:05,320\nThen they, all three, out for a charming\nride, and for a charming stroll among heath\n\n194\n00:14:05,320 --> 00:14:10,160\nin bloom, and there behold the identical\nGruff and Glum with his wooden legs\n\n195\n00:14:10,160 --> 00:14:12,310\nhorizontally disposed before him,\n\n196\n00:14:12,310 --> 00:14:15,630\napparently sitting meditating on the\nvicissitudes of life!\n\n197\n00:14:15,630 --> 00:14:21,510\nTo whom said Bella, in her light-hearted\nsurprise: 'Oh! How do you do again?\n\n198\n00:14:21,510 --> 00:14:24,890\nWhat a dear old pensioner you are!'\n\n199\n00:14:24,890 --> 00:14:29,420\nTo which Gruff and Glum responded that he\nsee her married this morning, my Beauty,\n\n200\n00:14:29,420 --> 00:14:34,890\nand that if it warn't a liberty he wished\nher ji and the fairest of fair wind and\n\n201\n00:14:34,890 --> 00:14:36,430\nweather; further, in a general way\n\n202\n00:14:36,430 --> 00:14:41,370\nrequesting to know what cheer? and\nscrambling up on his two wooden legs to\n\n203\n00:14:41,370 --> 00:14:46,410\nsalute, hat in hand, ship-shape, with the\ngallantry of a man-of-warsman and a heart\n\n204\n00:14:46,410 --> 00:14:47,950\nof oak.\n\n205\n00:14:47,950 --> 00:14:52,850\nIt was a pleasant sight, in the midst of\nthe golden bloom, to see this salt old\n\n206\n00:14:52,850 --> 00:14:58,290\nGruff and Glum, waving his shovel hat at\nBella, while his thin white hair flowed\n\n207\n00:14:58,290 --> 00:15:02,550\nfree, as if she had once more launched him\ninto blue water again.\n\n208\n00:15:02,550 --> 00:15:10,150\n'You are a charming old pensioner,' said\nBella, 'and I am so happy that I wish I\n\n209\n00:15:10,150 --> 00:15:12,730\ncould make you happy, too.'\n\n210\n00:15:12,730 --> 00:15:20,630\nAnswered Gruff and Glum, 'Give me leave to\nkiss your hand, my Lovely, and it's done!'\n\n211\n00:15:20,630 --> 00:15:25,540\nSo it was done to the general contentment;\nand if Gruff and Glum didn't in the course\n\n212\n00:15:25,540 --> 00:15:30,449\nof the afternoon splice the main brace, it\nwas not for want of the means of inflicting\n\n213\n00:15:30,450 --> 00:15:34,440\nthat outrage on the feelings of the Infant\nBands of Hope.\n\n214\n00:15:34,440 --> 00:15:40,150\nBut, the marriage dinner was the crowning\nsuccess, for what had bride and bridegroom\n\n215\n00:15:40,150 --> 00:15:46,010\nplotted to do, but to have and to hold that\ndinner in the very room of the very hotel\n\n216\n00:15:46,300 --> 00:15:50,680\nwhere Pa and the lovely woman had once\ndined together!\n\n217\n00:15:50,680 --> 00:15:55,590\nBella sat between Pa and John, and divided\nher attentions pretty equally, but felt it\n\n218\n00:15:55,590 --> 00:16:00,900\nnecessary (in the waiter's absence before\ndinner) to remind Pa that she was HIS\n\n219\n00:16:00,900 --> 00:16:02,860\nlovely woman no longer.\n\n220\n00:16:02,860 --> 00:16:11,060\n'I am well aware of it, my dear,' returned\nthe cherub, 'and I resign you willingly.'\n\n221\n00:16:11,060 --> 00:16:15,930\n'Willingly, sir?\nYou ought to be brokenhearted.'\n\n222\n00:16:15,930 --> 00:16:21,780\n'So I should be, my dear, if I thought that\nI was going to lose you.'\n\n223\n00:16:21,780 --> 00:16:26,450\n'But you know you are not; don't you, poor\ndear Pa?\n\n224\n00:16:26,450 --> 00:16:31,690\nYou know that you have only made a new\nrelation who will be as fond of you and as\n\n225\n00:16:31,690 --> 00:16:38,110\nthankful to you--for my sake and your own\nsake both--as I am; don't you, dear little\n\n226\n00:16:38,110 --> 00:16:38,690\nPa?\n\n227\n00:16:38,690 --> 00:16:42,600\nLook here, Pa!'\nBella put her finger on her own lip, and\n\n228\n00:16:42,600 --> 00:16:47,029\nthen on Pa's, and then on her own lip\nagain, and then on her husband's.\n\n229\n00:16:47,030 --> 00:16:52,770\n'Now, we are a partnership of three, dear\nPa.'\n\n230\n00:16:52,770 --> 00:16:56,970\nThe appearance of dinner here cut Bella\nshort in one of her disappearances: the\n\n231\n00:16:56,970 --> 00:17:01,240\nmore effectually, because it was put on\nunder the auspices of a solemn gentleman in\n\n232\n00:17:01,240 --> 00:17:03,770\nblack clothes and a white cravat, who\n\n233\n00:17:03,770 --> 00:17:08,120\nlooked much more like a clergyman than THE\nclergyman, and seemed to have mounted a\n\n234\n00:17:08,120 --> 00:17:12,309\ngreat deal higher in the church: not to\nsay, scaled the steeple.\n\n235\n00:17:12,309 --> 00:17:16,980\nThis dignitary, conferring in secrecy with\nJohn Rokesmith on the subject of punch and\n\n236\n00:17:16,980 --> 00:17:22,079\nwines, bent his head as though stooping to\nthe Papistical practice of receiving\n\n237\n00:17:22,079 --> 00:17:23,730\nauricular confession.\n\n238\n00:17:23,730 --> 00:17:28,490\nLikewise, on John's offering a suggestion\nwhich didn't meet his views, his face\n\n239\n00:17:28,490 --> 00:17:32,419\nbecame overcast and reproachful, as\nenjoining penance.\n\n240\n00:17:32,419 --> 00:17:35,450\nWhat a dinner!\n\n241\n00:17:35,450 --> 00:17:40,159\nSpecimens of all the fishes that swim in\nthe sea, surely had swum their way to it,\n\n242\n00:17:40,159 --> 00:17:44,960\nand if samples of the fishes of divers\ncolours that made a speech in the Arabian\n\n243\n00:17:44,960 --> 00:17:47,470\nNights (quite a ministerial explanation in\n\n244\n00:17:47,470 --> 00:17:51,789\nrespect of cloudiness), and then jumped out\nof the frying-pan, were not to be\n\n245\n00:17:51,789 --> 00:17:56,769\nrecognized, it was only because they had\nall become of one hue by being cooked in\n\n246\n00:17:56,769 --> 00:17:59,289\nbatter among the whitebait.\n\n247\n00:17:59,289 --> 00:18:04,259\nAnd the dishes being seasoned with Bliss--\nan article which they are sometimes out of,\n\n248\n00:18:04,259 --> 00:18:08,679\nat Greenwich--were of perfect flavour, and\nthe golden drinks had been bottled in the\n\n249\n00:18:08,730 --> 00:18:13,350\ngolden age and hoarding up their sparkles\never since.\n\n250\n00:18:13,350 --> 00:18:17,899\nThe best of it was, that Bella and John and\nthe cherub had made a covenant that they\n\n251\n00:18:17,899 --> 00:18:22,889\nwould not reveal to mortal eyes any\nappearance whatever of being a wedding\n\n252\n00:18:22,889 --> 00:18:23,549\nparty.\n\n253\n00:18:23,549 --> 00:18:28,309\nNow, the supervising dignitary, the\nArchbishop of Greenwich, knew this as well\n\n254\n00:18:28,309 --> 00:18:31,179\nas if he had performed the nuptial\nceremony.\n\n255\n00:18:31,179 --> 00:18:34,879\nAnd the loftiness with which his Grace\nentered into their confidence without being\n\n256\n00:18:34,879 --> 00:18:39,340\ninvited, and insisted on a show of keeping\nthe waiters out of it, was the crowning\n\n257\n00:18:39,340 --> 00:18:40,909\nglory of the entertainment.\n\n258\n00:18:40,909 --> 00:18:47,090\nThere was an innocent young waiter of a\nslender form and with weakish legs, as yet\n\n259\n00:18:47,090 --> 00:18:51,759\nunversed in the wiles of waiterhood, and\nbut too evidently of a romantic\n\n260\n00:18:51,759 --> 00:18:54,289\ntemperament, and deeply (it were not too\n\n261\n00:18:54,289 --> 00:19:00,480\nmuch to add hopelessly) in love with some\nyoung female not aware of his merit.\n\n262\n00:19:00,480 --> 00:19:04,409\nThis guileless youth, descrying the\nposition of affairs, which even his\n\n263\n00:19:04,409 --> 00:19:09,429\ninnocence could not mistake, limited his\nwaiting to languishing admiringly against\n\n264\n00:19:09,429 --> 00:19:14,489\nthe sideboard when Bella didn't want\nanything, and swooping at her when she did.\n\n265\n00:19:14,490 --> 00:19:19,649\nHim, his Grace the Archbishop perpetually\nobstructed, cutting him out with his elbow\n\n266\n00:19:19,649 --> 00:19:24,679\nin the moment of success, despatching him\nin degrading quest of melted butter, and,\n\n267\n00:19:24,679 --> 00:19:26,870\nwhen by any chance he got hold of any dish\n\n268\n00:19:26,870 --> 00:19:31,519\nworth having, bereaving him of it, and\nordering him to stand back.\n\n269\n00:19:31,519 --> 00:19:38,440\n'Pray excuse him, madam,' said the\nArchbishop in a low stately voice; 'he is a\n\n270\n00:19:38,440 --> 00:19:43,379\nvery young man on liking, and we DON'T like\nhim.'\n\n271\n00:19:43,379 --> 00:19:48,129\nThis induced John Rokesmith to observe--by\nway of making the thing more natural--\n\n272\n00:19:48,129 --> 00:19:54,160\n'Bella, my love, this is so much more\nsuccessful than any of our past\n\n273\n00:19:54,159 --> 00:19:59,309\nanniversaries, that I think we must keep\nour future anniversaries here.'\n\n274\n00:19:59,309 --> 00:20:04,009\nWhereunto Bella replied, with probably the\nleast successful attempt at looking\n\n275\n00:20:04,009 --> 00:20:11,360\nmatronly that ever was seen: 'Indeed, I\nthink so, John, dear.'\n\n276\n00:20:11,360 --> 00:20:16,049\nHere the Archbishop of Greenwich coughed a\nstately cough to attract the attention of\n\n277\n00:20:16,049 --> 00:20:21,139\nthree of his ministers present, and staring\nat them, seemed to say: 'I call upon you by\n\n278\n00:20:21,139 --> 00:20:24,289\nyour fealty to believe this!'\n\n279\n00:20:24,289 --> 00:20:29,129\nWith his own hands he afterwards put on the\ndessert, as remarking to the three guests,\n\n280\n00:20:29,129 --> 00:20:32,840\n'The period has now arrived at which we can\ndispense with the assistance of those\n\n281\n00:20:32,840 --> 00:20:35,369\nfellows who are not in our confidence,' and\n\n282\n00:20:35,369 --> 00:20:39,600\nwould have retired with complete dignity\nbut for a daring action issuing from the\n\n283\n00:20:39,600 --> 00:20:43,899\nmisguided brain of the young man on liking.\n\n284\n00:20:43,649 --> 00:20:49,090\nHe finding, by ill-fortune, a piece of\norange flower somewhere in the lobbies now\n\n285\n00:20:49,090 --> 00:20:54,190\napproached undetected with the same in a\nfinger-glass, and placed it on Bella's\n\n286\n00:20:54,190 --> 00:20:55,809\nright hand.\n\n287\n00:20:55,809 --> 00:21:01,409\nThe Archbishop instantly ejected and\nexcommunicated him; but the thing was done.\n\n288\n00:21:01,409 --> 00:21:09,690\n'I trust, madam,' said his Grace, returning\nalone, 'that you will have the kindness to\n\n289\n00:21:09,690 --> 00:21:15,869\noverlook it, in consideration of its being\nthe act of a very young man who is merely\n\n290\n00:21:15,869 --> 00:21:19,779\nhere on liking, and who will never answer.'\n\n291\n00:21:19,779 --> 00:21:26,710\nWith that, he solemnly bowed and retired,\nand they all burst into laughter, long and\n\n292\n00:21:26,710 --> 00:21:27,710\nmerry.\n\n293\n00:21:27,460 --> 00:21:37,049\n'Disguise is of no use,' said Bella; 'they\nall find me out; I think it must be, Pa and\n\n294\n00:21:37,049 --> 00:21:41,010\nJohn dear, because I look so happy!'\n\n295\n00:21:40,759 --> 00:21:44,749\nHer husband feeling it necessary at this\npoint to demand one of those mysterious\n\n296\n00:21:44,749 --> 00:21:49,230\ndisappearances on Bella's part, she\ndutifully obeyed; saying in a softened\n\n297\n00:21:49,230 --> 00:21:51,610\nvoice from her place of concealment:\n\n298\n00:21:51,610 --> 00:21:55,789\n'You remember how we talked about the ships\nthat day, Pa?'\n\n299\n00:21:55,789 --> 00:22:00,950\n'Yes, my dear.'\n'Isn't it strange, now, to think that there\n\n300\n00:22:00,950 --> 00:22:03,499\nwas no John in all the ships, Pa?'\n\n301\n00:22:03,499 --> 00:22:07,740\n'Not at all, my dear.'\n'Oh, Pa!\n\n302\n00:22:07,740 --> 00:22:11,329\nNot at all?'\n'No, my dear.\n\n303\n00:22:11,340 --> 00:22:17,139\nHow can we tell what coming people are\naboard the ships that may be sailing to us\n\n304\n00:22:17,139 --> 00:22:21,610\nnow from the unknown seas!'\n\n305\n00:22:21,360 --> 00:22:26,759\nBella remaining invisible and silent, her\nfather remained at his dessert and wine,\n\n306\n00:22:26,759 --> 00:22:30,200\nuntil he remembered it was time for him to\nget home to Holloway.\n\n307\n00:22:30,200 --> 00:22:38,139\n'Though I positively cannot tear myself\naway,' he cherubically added, '--it would\n\n308\n00:22:38,139 --> 00:22:45,590\nbe a sin--without drinking to many, many\nhappy returns of this most happy day.'\n\n309\n00:22:45,590 --> 00:22:50,169\n'Here! ten thousand times!' cried John.\n\n310\n00:22:50,169 --> 00:22:54,510\n'I fill my glass and my precious wife's.'\n\n311\n00:22:54,259 --> 00:23:00,249\n'Gentlemen,' said the cherub, inaudibly\naddressing, in his Anglo-Saxon tendency to\n\n312\n00:23:00,249 --> 00:23:04,600\nthrow his feelings into the form of a\nspeech, the boys down below, who were\n\n313\n00:23:04,600 --> 00:23:05,909\nbidding against each other to put their\n\n314\n00:23:05,909 --> 00:23:12,690\nheads in the mud for sixpence: 'Gentlemen--\nand Bella and John--you will readily\n\n315\n00:23:12,690 --> 00:23:18,110\nsuppose that it is not my intention to\ntrouble you with many observations on the\n\n316\n00:23:18,110 --> 00:23:19,929\npresent occasion.\n\n317\n00:23:19,929 --> 00:23:25,100\nYou will also at once infer the nature and\neven the terms of the toast I am about to\n\n318\n00:23:25,100 --> 00:23:28,159\npropose on the present occasion.\n\n319\n00:23:27,909 --> 00:23:33,419\nGentlemen--and Bella and John--the present\noccasion is an occasion fraught with\n\n320\n00:23:33,419 --> 00:23:37,090\nfeelings that I cannot trust myself to\nexpress.\n\n321\n00:23:37,090 --> 00:23:43,450\nBut gentlemen--and Bella and John--for the\npart I have had in it, for the confidence\n\n322\n00:23:43,450 --> 00:23:48,669\nyou have placed in me, and for the\naffectionate good-nature and kindness with\n\n323\n00:23:48,669 --> 00:23:51,190\nwhich you have determined not to find me in\n\n324\n00:23:51,190 --> 00:23:56,720\nthe way, when I am well aware that I cannot\nbe otherwise than in it more or less, I do\n\n325\n00:23:56,720 --> 00:23:59,880\nmost heartily thank you.\n\n326\n00:23:59,629 --> 00:24:06,799\nGentlemen--and Bella and John--my love to\nyou, and may we meet, as on the present\n\n327\n00:24:06,799 --> 00:24:14,190\noccasion, on many future occasions; that is\nto say, gentlemen--and Bella and John--on\n\n328\n00:24:14,190 --> 00:24:20,190\nmany happy returns of the present happy\noccasion.'\n\n329\n00:24:20,190 --> 00:24:25,080\nHaving thus concluded his address, the\namiable cherub embraced his daughter, and\n\n330\n00:24:25,080 --> 00:24:29,770\ntook his flight to the steamboat which was\nto convey him to London, and was then lying\n\n331\n00:24:29,769 --> 00:24:33,820\nat the floating pier, doing its best to\nbump the same to bits.\n\n332\n00:24:33,820 --> 00:24:38,200\nBut, the happy couple were not going to\npart with him in that way, and before he\n\n333\n00:24:38,200 --> 00:24:42,970\nhad been on board two minutes, there they\nwere, looking down at him from the wharf\n\n334\n00:24:42,970 --> 00:24:44,070\nabove.\n\n335\n00:24:44,070 --> 00:24:49,940\n'Pa, dear!' cried Bella, beckoning him with\nher parasol to approach the side, and\n\n336\n00:24:49,940 --> 00:24:53,809\nbending gracefully to whisper.\n'Yes, my darling.'\n\n337\n00:24:53,809 --> 00:24:58,029\n'Did I beat you much with that horrid\nlittle bonnet, Pa?'\n\n338\n00:24:58,029 --> 00:25:03,179\n'Nothing to speak of; my dear.'\n'Did I pinch your legs, Pa?'\n\n339\n00:25:03,179 --> 00:25:05,590\n'Only nicely, my pet.'\n\n340\n00:25:05,590 --> 00:25:12,710\n'You are sure you quite forgive me, Pa?\nPlease, Pa, please, forgive me quite!'\n\n341\n00:25:12,710 --> 00:25:17,080\nHalf laughing at him and half crying to\nhim, Bella besought him in the prettiest\n\n342\n00:25:17,080 --> 00:25:21,840\nmanner; in a manner so engaging and so\nplayful and so natural, that her cherubic\n\n343\n00:25:21,840 --> 00:25:24,580\nparent made a coaxing face as if she had\n\n344\n00:25:24,580 --> 00:25:29,749\nnever grown up, and said, 'What a silly\nlittle Mouse it is!'\n\n345\n00:25:29,749 --> 00:25:35,159\n'But you do forgive me that, and everything\nelse; don't you, Pa?'\n\n346\n00:25:35,159 --> 00:25:36,570\n'Yes, my dearest.'\n\n347\n00:25:36,570 --> 00:25:42,909\n'And you don't feel solitary or neglected,\ngoing away by yourself; do you, Pa?'\n\n348\n00:25:42,909 --> 00:25:46,080\n'Lord bless you!\nNo, my Life!'\n\n349\n00:25:46,080 --> 00:25:48,429\n'Good-bye, dearest Pa.\n\n350\n00:25:48,429 --> 00:25:51,559\nGood-bye!'\n'Good-bye, my darling!\n\n351\n00:25:51,559 --> 00:25:58,600\nTake her away, my dear John.\nTake her home!'\n\n352\n00:25:58,600 --> 00:26:04,610\nSo, she leaning on her husband's arm, they\nturned homeward by a rosy path which the\n\n353\n00:26:04,610 --> 00:26:08,559\ngracious sun struck out for them in its\nsetting.\n\n354\n00:26:08,559 --> 00:26:12,669\nAnd O there are days in this life, worth\nlife and worth death.\n\n355\n00:26:12,669 --> 00:26:21,309\nAnd O what a bright old song it is, that O\n'tis love, 'tis love, 'tis love that makes\n\n356\n00:26:21,309 --> 00:26:27,090\nthe world go round!\n\n","markerStore":{"nextMarkerId":615,"markersById":{"0":{"range":{"start":{"row":436,"column":17},"end":{"row":436,"column":39}},"properties":{"type":"selection","editorId":26,"goalScreenRange":null},"reversed":false,"tailed":true,"valid":true,"invalidate":"never","maintainHistory":true}},"version":2},"history":{"version":3,"nextCheckpointId":2,"undoStack":[],"redoStack":[]},"encoding":"utf8","filePath":"/Users/joegesualdo/code/node/vocabulary-context/videos-srt/Book4,Chapter04-OurMutualFriendbyCharlesDickens-ARunawayMatch-4ZwWEadNjmE.en.srt","digestWhenLastPersisted":"d736cecdde8338165db2843ec2e42c76b46d9d1e","preferredLineEnding":null,"deserializer":"TextBuffer","version":2}],"deserializer":"Project"},"workspace":{"paneContainer":{"root":{"id":3,"items":[{"id":8,"softTabs":true,"displayBuffer":